<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
By JULIA LIEBLICH, AP Religion Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- While thousands of people formed a human chain
around the U.S. Capitol earlier this month in a loud appeal to
cancel debts owed by impoverished nations, some religious leaders
have quietly preached for decades against what they call ''economic
chains of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Thomas Burns, a Maryknoll priest, traveled
from Lima, Peru, to Washington to urge members of Congress to
cancel the debts of poor countries, among other economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   He told of performing emergency baptisms on babies -- three a day
-- who were dying of dysentery while scarce resources were going to
debt payments, not health care.
</P>
<P>
   Back then it was lonely work. Today religious leaders as diverse
as Pope John Paul II, Bishop Desmond Tutu, the Rev. Billy Graham,
and the Rev. Pat Robertson support what Tutu calls ''a moral
crusade.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't seen the religious community come around an issue
like this since the (anti-) apartheid movement,'' said Thomas Hart,
director of government relations for the Episcopal Church, a member
of the Jubilee 2000/USA campaign for debt reduction, a coalition of
religious and secular groups.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 of the poorest countries in Africa, Latin America,
and Asia, owe about $220 billion in debt to the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund, regional development banks and donor
governments. In some cases, says Hart, debt payments consume 30
percent to 40 percent of countries' budgets.
</P>
<P>
   The Jubilee 2000 campaign began in England in the late 1990s,
named after the biblical jubilee year when God called for the
freeing of slaves and canceling of debts. It soon spread to 60
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in June 1997, the Jubilee 2000/USA effort includes such
religious groups as the National Council of Churches, the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, the Union of American
Hebrew Congregations, Catholic Relief Services and the Muslim
Public Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''The concept of economic justice is a cornerstone of Islamic
social and political thought,'' says Salam Al-Marayati, director of
the Muslim Public Affairs Council. Debt cancellation is necessary,
he says, ''so future generations will not always be shackled in
economic enslavement by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee 2000/USA organized the April 9 rally in Washington. The
group wants world leaders to cancel unpayable loans and ensure that
the freed resources are used to reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
   There has already been some success. Under a 1996 international
debt relief arrangement for Uganda, for example, annual debt
service payments were cut from $50 million from $150 million. The
government has used the savings to spend more on education and to
double enrollment in primary schools, monitoring groups say.
</P>
<P>
   A plan to offer $90 billion in debt relief to the world's
poorest nations was endorsed last June by the world's seven major
industrialized democracies at their annual economic summit and
adopted by the World Bank and the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has asked Congress for the U.S.
share, about $920 million over four years. Congress has authorized
$320 million and funded the first year's installment of $110
million. But that was to cover cancellation of bilateral loans,
those between the United States and another nation.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee 2000 also wants cancellation of $600 million in
multilateral loans between impoverished countries and institutions
such as the Interamerican Development Bank. But Congress hasn't
approved it.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Knippers, president of the Institute for Religion and
Democracy, finds some Jubilee supporters misguided, particularly
those who reject stringent lender-imposed economic reforms.
''There's quite a bit of naivete. You can't always assume that the
clergy or church leaders are trained economists.''
</P>
<P>
   But religious leaders say they have economists on their side,
including Jeffrey Sachs, director of Harvard's Center for
International Development. And they maintain that they're among the
most reliable sources because of their work in indebted countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''My guidance comes from the real human-face stories that
Maryknoll people from different countries send our way,'' says
Marie Dennis of the Maryknoll Office for Global Concerns. ''We know
the impact of debt. ...
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, you need economists. But economists who are disconnected
from impact of policies will never have the tools to evaluate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis sees real progress. ''Within the last six months, the
same institutions began to move from talking about how any debtor
country would pay off as much as it could ... to talking about
poverty reduction and the goal of debt cancellation. Whether they
do it is another challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jubilee 2000 campaign will meet next month to discuss how to
exert more pressure and to address questions such as how to hold
creditors and debtors responsible for loans lost to corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Hart sees a growing consensus that unpayable debts should be
written off. ''The question is how and when.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, hopes Burns, the Maryknoll priest. Last September, he
happened to hear President Clinton on the BBC calling for debt
relief for the most impoverished nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew that if Clinton did it there was going to be a domino
effect,'' says Burns, who still lives in the same Lima shantytown.
''I jumped up and started dancing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
