<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group: Growth in campaign spending not due to cost rise  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Campaign spending is going through the roof
but it is not being driven by a corresponding increase in the cost
of mounting a big-time campaign, a group is contending.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Fair Elections Project, which favors campaign
finance reform, said Thursday a study of George Pataki's campaigns
in 1994 and 1998 show that politicians are spending far more on
campaigns basically because they can raise the money.
</P>
<P>
   The group's co-chairman is Evan Davis, former counsel to
ex-Democratic New York Gov. Mario Cuomo. Davis ran unsuccessfully
for state attorney general in 1998 in a campaign in which he
stressed the need for campaign reform in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A question raised in both New York and nationally by the
escalating costs of campaigns is whether they have occurred because
of a ''rise in campaign costs or simply an arms race by the
candidates,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This study, conducted in the largest media market in the
nation, provides a clear answer,'' Davis, a New York City lawyer,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spent $10.7 million to beat Cuomo in 1994 in a close
race, according to the New York Fair Elections Project study.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a weaker Democratic challenger in 1998 in New York City
Council Speaker Peter Vallone, Pataki spent $23.7 million, the New
York Fair Elections Project noted.
</P>
<P>
   The group created a special price index to measure increases in
the cost of goods and services that affect campaigns, things like
buying television time, print advertisements, travel, campaign
workers and consultant salaries plus inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1994 and 1998, those factors went up by 27 percent, but
Pataki's overall campaign spending increased 121 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The results are decisive and clear,'' Lauren Stiroh, a
consultant for National Economic Research Associates of White
Plains, which conducted the research for the study. ''There is no
doubt in New York state the cost of campaigning does not explain
the rise in campaign spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, a close Pataki adviser who ran his 1998 campaign,
called the study ''bogus'' and an ''absolutely worthless piece of
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   In both 1994 and 1998 Pataki was up against extremely
well-financed opponents and spent as much as necessary to ''get his
message out,'' Mucha said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You cannot be outspent 10 to 1, 15 to 1,'' she said. ''You
have to match your opponents' spending.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fair Elections Project only counted money it said Pataki
spent on actual campaign expenses. In all, Pataki's election
committee reported spending $14.4 million in 1994 vs. $10.6 million
for Cuomo and $6.6 million for B. Thomas Golisano, the Independence
Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Vallone spent $6 million and Golisano $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though Golisano did not garner much support among voters in
either 1994 or 1998, the presence in both races of the Rochester
millionaire influenced Pataki's political calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Spending his own money almost exclusively, Golisano raised the
monetary stakes in both campaigns, Mucha said. Pataki felt he had
to generate the funds necessary to respond to the attacks from
someone who could afford to spend ''an enormous amount of time and
effort'' to respond to attacks from Golisano, according to the
Pataki aide.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki camp was stung in particular in 1998 by Golisano's
incessant television advertisement attacks against the debt
policies of Pataki's first term.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has often said he had to spend too much to become
governor, Mucha said, and he proposed a bill in 1999 to slash the
size of maximum campaign contributions and to ban the use of
''soft'' money in statewide campaigns. That proposal did not pass
in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner of the New York Public Interest Research Group said
he found it interesting that Pataki spent less than half as much
getting elected in 1994 in his tight race against the incumbent
Mario Cuomo than he did against weaker opposition in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could be a chicken-and-egg thing where he had a $25 million
war chest (in 1998) so he warded off any serious challenges. ...
You have to spend it somewhere,'' Horner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
