<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exec Convicted in Inside Trade Case  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A former top Wall Street executive could face a
decade in prison for giving inside information on bank stocks to an
X-rated movie actress.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in U.S. District Court in Manhattan returned a guilty
verdict against James McDermott Jr., and codefendant Anthony
Pomponio on Thursday, after deliberating for parts of three days.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, a former chief executive at a New York investment
bank, and Pomponio were convicted on seven of eight counts in the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, former head of Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, took a deep
breath before the verdict was read but showed no emotion once it
was delivered, holding his head high as the jury forewoman spoke.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, 48, of Briarcliff Manor, N.Y., and Pomponio, 45, of
North Caldwell, N.J., had both admitted having extramarital affairs
with Kathryn Gannon, 30, but had denied engaging in insider
trading.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott allegedly gave inside information to Gannon, a woman
described to the jury only as an actress, dancer and model who
sometimes goes by the stage name ''Marylin Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Two jurors who declined to identify themselves said outside
court that they did not know Gannon was a porn star and that it
would not have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   One male juror added, though, ''We didn't think she was the
Queen of England.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood set sentencing for July 17 on
charges conspiracy and securities fraud that could bring up to 10
years in prison for McDermott and Pomponio.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged McDermott gave Gannon secret information
about six stocks, allowing her to buy bank stocks that were about
to skyrocket in value after public announcements of mergers.
</P>
<P>
   She was accused of giving the information to Pomponio, the owner
of a New Jersey quartz- and glass-cutting company who met Gannon at
an adult trade show in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, McDermott's lawyer, Denis McInerney, referred
to his client as a ''rocket scientist on bank stocks'' and admitted
that McDermott gave Gannon tips on stocks -- but only before he
learned the stock involved merger deals.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott and McInerney declined to comment after the verdict.
Pomponio's lawyer, Thomas Dunn, said he would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon and Pomponio allegedly made $170,000 in illegal profits.
Gannon, who has a home in Miami, Fla., is a fugitive. Prosecutors
have sought her extradition from Canada, where she is believed to
be living.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Howard Shapiro, said he was disappointed with the
verdict and that his client will vigorously defend herself.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the verdict were correct, Shapiro said, ''It does not
follow that Kathryn Gannon is guilty of the charges brought against
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said the Department of Justice must decide whether it
will pursue plans to extradite Gannon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're taking it one step at a time. I expect her to eventually
appear in a courtroom somewhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury exonerated McDermott and Pomponio on one count of the
indictment, finding they did not conspire to trade illegally in one
of the six stock deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
