<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Janitor's Strike Holds Lessons  </HEADLINE>
By GARY GENTILE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The successful campaign waged by janitors to
gain significant wage and benefit increases was carefully scripted,
planned years in advance and may provide a blueprint for job
actions throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a watershed moment,'' said Kent Wong, director of the
Labor Center at the University of California, Los Angeles. ''They
did thorough research, they skillfully utilized community allies,
religious allies and created broad popular support. All are
significant lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the drama that unfolded in Los Angeles, with its wide
disparity between the very rich and the very poor, will be replayed
to even greater effect in the coming weeks in Silicon Valley, where
the contrast between stock-option millionaires and the janitors who
clean up after them is even greater.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the script written by Mike Garcia, president of
the 20,000-member Service Employees International Union Local 1877,
which represents both the Los Angeles janitors and those in San
Jose, Oakland and other Northern California cities.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Garcia and staff have prepared
janitors for the fight that would be waged in 2000. They forged
alliances among the city's many unions, which historically have not
worked together. They also met with building owners and worked in
election campaigns -- all in preparation for this year's showdown.
</P>
<P>
   ''We taught them they needed to struggle to win, they needed to
be prepared to do whatever was necessary if they really wanted to
win a good contract, if they wanted to win respect and dignity,''
Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   But can the drama be repeated when the players are teachers and
truck drivers instead of Hispanic janitors earning below-poverty
wages?
</P>
<P>
   ''They (the janitors union) can be successful in this type of
dispute because these were largely marginalized workers and they
turned it into a civil rights demonstration,'' said Gary Chaison, a
professor of Industrial Relations at Clark University in Worcester,
Mass. ''It's not going to work in a typical manufacturing dispute
or a hospital dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   During the three-week strike, representatives from other SEIU
locals, the Teamsters Union and the AFL-CIO came to Los Angeles to
observe and take notes. While the cast of characters may change,
the strategies devised by Garcia and his staff are likely to be
emulated.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, Garcia said he decided to ''reinvent the
strike,'' using it as an offensive tool rather than a defensive
move born of desperation
</P>
<P>
   ''We realized we needed a crisis,'' he said. ''We were able to
create an image for the janitors as a group of workers who were
fighting back, who were going to lift themselves out of poverty.
... The janitors created a fight the world would not let them
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   A key strategy was to bypass the cleaning contractors, who
negotiate with the unions and hire the janitors, and appeal
directly to building owners. Garcia said he waited too long to make
building owners the villains in the drama. It's a blunder he
promises not to repeat in Silicon Valley, where a contract covering
thousands of janitors expires at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our janitors were well-defined, but the enemy was faceless for
too long. It took a while for pressure to mount on the building
owners only because we didn't expose who they were sooner,'' Garcia
said
</P>
<P>
   Another key strategy was to build political power by mobilizing
the union to elect candidates and then call on officials to
publicly support the strike, pressure building owners and
contractors and even get arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ''We lifted the bar for our political endorsements and asked
more from our elected leaders,'' said Miguel Contreras, executive
secretary of the Los Angeles County Federation of Labor. ''We were
able to parlay our political leverage to get them to engage in
civil disobedience.''
</P>
<P>
   The union persuaded Vice President Al Gore, Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass, Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan and members of
the state Assembly and various city councils to pass resolutions,
give speeches and lead marches.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the end of the day, we amassed so much political support,
they were calling and hounding these building owners to get this
done,'' Garcia said. ''As Mayor Riordan told me, 'Everybody wants a
part of this kill.'''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said other unions can learn from the techniques used in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't be afraid to take risks,'' he said. ''You can't be
afraid to ask your members to do the ultimate and you can't be
afraid to lead them there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
