<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Verdict Against Wal-Mart Thrown Out  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The Arkansas Supreme Court on Thursday
threw out a $2.75 million verdict won by a former Wal-Mart employee
who said she was falsely accused of stealing from the cash
registers.
</P>
<P>
   The court said there was no evidence to support the jury's
finding that Wal-Mart maliciously sought prosecution of Carolyn
Binns.
</P>
<P>
   Binns, who worked in the layaway department at a Wal-Mart in
Monticello, was suspected by two store managers of stealing. One of
the managers called police, and Binns was charged with theft in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, however, a prosecutor dropped the charges,
apparently because of insufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
   A jury awarded her $750,000 in compensatory damages and $2
million in punitive damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
