<HEADLINE> US Soldier Flees Custody in Korea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- An American soldier charged with
killing a South Korean woman fled a military compound hours before
he was to go on trial, the U.S. military command in Seoul said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''For now, we can say that he is no longer under custody,'' said
Kim Yong-kyu, a command spokesman, adding that he did not have any
other details.
</P>
<P>
   But South Korean officials said they were notified by U.S.
military investigators that Spc. Christopher K. McCarthy fled the
U.S. military command in Seoul early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   YTN, an all-news cable television network, said authorities
discovered that McCarthy was missing after he was allowed to meet
with his lawyers inside the main U.S. military compound in central
Seoul. His trial was to start later in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old soldier from Concord, N.H. was charged with the
beating death of a 31-year-old bar waitress, identified by police
only by her surname, Kim, in Seoul on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy was arrested three days later and told investigators
that he hit the woman because she refused to have sex with him.
</P>
