<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina President Triumphs  </HEADLINE>
By OSCAR SERRAT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- When he took office in December,
President Fernando De la Rua inherited an economic tableau that was
anything but appealing: Unemployment hovered in double digits and a
recession kept deepening.
</P>
<P>
   But De la Rua publicly celebrated one of the biggest political
triumphs of his young administration Thursday as he toasted Senate
passage of a bill to alter the country's rigid labor laws in a bid
to spur job and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Some labor leaders, however, said the bill will only inflict
pain on workers and do little to boost the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The vote late Wednesday was a hard-fought victory for a
president whose top priority during four months of office has been
rescuing South America's second-largest economy from the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a triumph for democratic institutions,'' an ebullient
De la Rua said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill calls for extending the trial period of new hires and
lowering employer payroll contributions for new workers. The
government says that will boost wage flexibility and create more
jobs while reducing the cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   Labor reform is considered a centerpiece of De la Rua's moves
toward a long-term recovery and Argentine economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   He went up against dissident labor leaders to claim his victory.
And in the end, the bill was passed after De la Rua's ruling
center-left party compromised with foes to include a clause barring
companies from lowering salaries in collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of Congress approved the bill weeks ago and is
to reconcile the two versions. House approval is expected.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua defended the bill, saying Thursday that it would not
harm workers. ''It's for the good of all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-line labor leaders disagree. They have vowed to wage a
strike May 5 in protest of the legislation, which they claim would
hurt workers and do nothing to ease the country's 14 percent
unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will fight on behalf of hungry workers,'' Hugo Moyano, head
of a hard-line truckers' union, told protesters outside Congress
before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua has countered that it is vital for companies to have
more say over their own pay scales and other issues that had kept
certain foreign investors at bay. Critics have long claimed that
too much power still rests in the hands of national union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It is De la Rua's second major legislative victory.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after taking office, he pushed through a highly
unpopular tax hike which should help Argentina trim its federal
deficit by $2.5 billion -- from $7.1 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The early victories have comforted the International Monetary
Fund, which in February approved a $7.4 billion standby loan for
Argentina. The deficit-cutting package seemed to reassure the bond
markets, where Argentina routinely seeks financing.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, economists caution that the benefits of the labor
reform bill will not be felt for some time. ''This legislation is
not for the short term, it's a long-term strategy,'' said economic
analyst Esteban Fernadez Medrano.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's economic woes came fast upon the heels of the 1998
Asian financial crisis, and were only made worse after neighboring
Brazil devalued its currency last January.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian currency upheaval made Argentine goods more
expensive there, quickly dampening Argentina's chief export market.
But government officials talk of the recession just now showing
signs of ebbing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict Argentina's economy will grow 4 percent this
year, bouncing back after it slumped 3 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people say they doubt they will feel any benefits
from the president's reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are lots of workers in the street. ... I'm afraid of
losing my job,'' said 47-year-old factory worker Jorge Rosi, who
took part in demonstrations against the labor reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 0120 </TRAILER>
