<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Youth Urged To Buckle Up  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN PARROTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Citing studies showing low rates of seat belt use
among black youths, U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher called on
mayors to help get black children in their cities to buckle up.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study found that blacks in their teens and 20s are half
as likely to use automobile safety belts as whites and Hispanics in
the same age group.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, wearing seat belts saves lives,'' Satcher said
Thursday at the annual meeting of the National Conference of Black
Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   He told the city leaders and high school students that traffic
accidents are the leading cause of death for blacks age 15 and
under, and the second leading cause for those age 15 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   Comprehensive seat-belt use could save as many as 1,300 lives a
year, prevent 26,000 injuries and reduce costs to society by $2.6
billion, according to a 1999 study by Nashville-based Meharry
Medical College, where Satcher used to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk called the traffic deaths of black
teen-agers a ''silent epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These are lives and dollars thrown out the window because we
are too lazy, too arrogant or to hip to buckle up,'' said Kirk, who
leads a committee urging black mayors nationwide to launch public
awareness campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
