<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor Giuliani has prostate cancer  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said he would continue
his Senate race for the time being, despite being diagnosed with a
treatable form of prostate cancer, but said he would make a more
definitive statement in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no idea,'' he said when asked how the diagnosis would
affect the Senate race. ''I think in fairness to me, to the
Republican Party, to all of the parties and everybody else you need
some time to think about it. And I really need to know what the
course of treatment is going to be before I can evaluate. ... And
then, after I determine that, then I will figure out does it make
sense this year or doesn't it or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   He still plans campaign appearances in Saratoga today and in
Buffalo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing upbeat and energetic at a hastily arranged City Hall
news conference Thursday, Giuliani confirmed speculation by
reporters that started Wednesday evening when Giuliani was seen
entering Mount Sinai Hospital in Manhattan and leaving three hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was diagnosed yesterday,'' Giuliani, 55, told the packed
news conference surrounded by his top aides. ''It's a treatable
form of prostate cancer. It was diagnosed at an early stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had additional tests performed Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he got regular prostate checkups because his
father died at age 73 of prostate cancer in 1981. Giuliani, who
rarely speaks about personal matters to the media, said his own
cancer reminded him of his father's illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''It brings up very painful memories,'' he said. ''And, you
know, I miss my father every day of my life. And he's a very, very
important reason for why I'm standing here as the mayor of New York
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's Democratic rival for the Senate, Hillary Rodham
Clinton -- who was campaigning in the upstate village of Penn Yan --
spoke briefly by telephone with the mayor and wished him ''a speedy
and complete recovery,'' said Clinton spokeswoman Karen Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   Other well-wishers included friend and foe alike -- and ranged
from Gov. George Pataki to the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mayor and I certainly have political differences, but I
certainly wish no ill will or ill health on him,'' said Sharpton.
''My differences with him are social and political. I would hope he
would do what is best for his health and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, who had considered challenging Giuliani for the
GOP Senate nomination, issued a statement offering his prayers and
support, adding that health issues transcend politics. Through his
spokesman, Lazio declined to say whether he would enter the race if
Giuliani dropped out. The New York Senate primary is in September.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's wife, Donna Hanover, released a statement asking for
as much privacy for her husband as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very optimistic about Rudy's recovery,'' she said. ''We
have discussed this and I will be very supportive of him in dealing
with the choices he has to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate, a gland involved in semen production, is
the second most common type of cancer found in American men but
early detection greatly increases the chance of successful
treatment. About 179,300 men were diagnosed with the disease in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have survived prostate cancer are former Sen.
Bob Dole and New York Yankees manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Treatments include the radical prostatectomy -- the removal of
the prostate -- and radiation. Treatment of the cancer would almost
certainly require as much as several weeks away from City Hall and
off the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bad news is that it's cancer, the good news is that there
are lots of possible options, and it's going to take a while to
figure out which option is going to bring about a cure,'' said
Giuliani. ''Over the next week, maybe two weeks, maybe
two-and-a-half or three weeks, I'll figure out with my doctors what
the best form of treatment will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Catalona of Barnes-Jewish Hospital in St. Louis, who
removed Torre's cancerous prostate last year, said that with
surgery, a patient is typically in the hospital for three days.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're usually able to return to normal activities within a
few weeks,'' he said, ''but they're anemic and it takes 6 to 8
weeks or somewhat longer to build their blood count up.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Giuliani should be able to resume his mayoral
schedule after that and also run for Senate, Catalona replied:
''Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to his sometimes testiness with the press, Giuliani
smiled, laughed and joked during his announcement.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he would be nicer, he replied, ''No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he felt well, considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel great,'' he said. ''I can't say I feel absolutely
great. I had the biopsy yesterday, that creates a few pains that
you'd rather not have ... but I'm in very good health.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's schedule Thursday included a previously scheduled
meeting with Pataki at the governor's Manhattan office in which the
governor expressed his support and the two discussed city business,
said mayoral spokeswoman Sunny Mindel.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Kim Serafin said the campaign had
collected more than $10,000 on Thursday via its web site and
received about 1,000 E-mails. On a typical day, the campaign
receives some $2,000 and about 150 E-mails.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 0131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000428.0023 </DOCNO>
