<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prisoners in Virginia have hard time keeping up with Connecticutcases  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Connecticut inmates who have been shipped to Virginia
to ease
prison overcrowding say the move has made it harder to contact
their lawyers and move their court cases along.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a human rights group said it is seeking an in-depth
review of allegations of prisoner mistreatment, The Day of New
London, Conn. reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Wallens Ridge prison in Big Stone Gap, Va. is in a remote
Appalachian village, a 14-hour drive from Connecticut, making
travel for face-to-face consultations costly and time-consuming.
Consultation instead occurs by telephone and the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said many appeals are not being vigorously pursued, at
least not in a timely fashion, depriving their clients of the
constitutional right to be represented by effective counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even convicted murderers may have been falsely or unjustly
convicted,'' said Conrad Seifert, an Old Lyme lawyer who has served
as a state-appointed special public defender.
</P>
<P>
   ''The appeals process is important. The attorney doesn't work in
a vacuum. He needs to work with his client. Share information. All
that has been destroyed,'' Seifert said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly 500 Connecticut inmates sent to Virginia, 89 had
pending legal matters as of last week, the state public defender's
office said. Forty-nine of those inmates are pursuing direct
appeals of convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawyers and prisoners told The Day they did not want to
discuss cases with clients over the telephone, for fear Virginia
prison guards will listen in.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Traylor, spokesman for the Virginia corrections
department, said the Wallens Ridge staff considers lawyer-client
conversations confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's as private as it can be from a pay phone,'' Traylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the human rights group Amnesty International USA is
seeking an independent review of allegations of abuse in the
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''The consistent theme (in the complaints) is that there have
been beatings, an excessive use of electroshock equipment, and
regular psychological abuse,'' said Curt Goering, deputy executive
director of Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Goering said not all allegations are true and they can't be
accepted at face value. He added, however, that they can't be
proved or refuted until they are researched in depth.
</P>
<P>
   Traylor said the corrections department would respond to
detailed complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have raised allegations,'' Traylor said. ''We'd be glad
to address any of their specific concerns if they provide us with
specific information -- the names of the inmates, exactly what
happened, that kind of thing. But we will not respond to
allegations. We will respond to proof.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews and letters to The Day, some prisoners claimed
guards taunted them with racial and ethnic slurs, physically abused
them and threatened retaliation if the inmates made formal
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, at the request of the New Mexico attorney general, is
investigating allegations that inmates from that state have been
abused at Wallens Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut inmates and their relatives have submitted a stack
of letters and complaints to the FBI office in Richmond, in hopes
the FBI will formally investigate their claims.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Armstrong, Connecticut's corrections commissioner, said
he is satisfied that constitutional standards are being met in
Virginia. If he felt differently, he said, he would try to remove
the inmates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 0132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000428.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devil Rays 7, Angels 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Dave Martinez drove in three runs and
Dwight Gooden pitched five strong innings in his 400th career start
as the Tampa Bay Devil Rays beat the Anaheim Angels 7-3 Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden (2-0) allowed a run on four hits and struck out three in
his third start for the Devil Rays, who obtained the former NL Cy
Young winner from the Houston Astros on April 13 in a cash
transaction. The victory was the right-hander's second in his last
11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Castilla doubled with two out in the second against Ramon
Ortiz (1-2) and scored on the first of John Flaherty's three hits,
a bloop single inside the right field line.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams singled under the glove of third baseman Troy
Glaus with two out in the third, stole second and scored Tampa
Bay's second run on Martinez's double.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy led off the bottom of the third with his third
homer -- the fifth surrendered by Gooden in his first 17 innings
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays increased the margin to 3-1 in the fifth with the
help of Mo Vaughn's second error this season.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stocker led off with a single and Vaughn's wild throw to
first on a sacrifice bunt by Williams put runners at second and
third. Martinez followed with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Williams increased Tampa Bay's lead to 5-1 in the sixth with a
two-run bases-loaded single after Ortiz walked one batter and
reliever Al Levine walked two more. Greg Vaughn capped the inning
with an RBI single and Martinez completed the scoring in the eighth
with his second RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored their final two runs in the ninth off reliever
Roberto Hernandez on Scott Spiezio's RBI double and Darin Erstad's
RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who entered Thursday night's game with a major
league-leading .456 average, had three hits. It was Erstad's 15th
multi-hit game this month, the most by any major leaguer in April
since Dave Winfield's 15 multi-hit games in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's bunt hit followed a leadoff single by Gary DiSarcina,
and both advanced on a sacrifice by Kennedy. But the 35-year-old
Gooden, pitching these days on finesse and savvy instead of power,
reached back for some of his vintage magic and escaped the jam by
striking out Vaughn and Tim Salmon -- the latter with a 79-mph
breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Tampa Bay's power quartet of Vaughn, Castilla, Jose Canseco
and Fred McGriff -- who hit a combined 305 home runs over the
previous two seasons -- failed to homer for the 14th time in the
team's first 21 games. The Devil Rays are 2-5 when at least one of
them homers, and 6-8 when none of them do. ... Angels manager Mike
Scioscia hit a dramatic game-tying two-run homer against Gooden in
the ninth inning of Game 4 of the 1988 NL Championship Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
