<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers, Rowland agree on budget  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut residents will get a break
when they go clothes shopping and fill up their gas tanks under a
$12.3 billion budget deal reached between the governor and leading
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've come to conclusion, not only on the spending side of the
budget, but the tax side,'' Gov. John G. Rowland said Thursday. The
legislative session ends at midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting Rowland's proposal to enact a 7-cent gas tax cut
on July 1, leading Democrats have now agreed to it.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also includes a GOP-backed measure to have one
week-long sales tax exemptions on clothing priced up to $300.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats got something in return -- namely an increase on
clothing tax exemptions. Currently, clothing priced below $50 is
tax free. Democrats pushed that limit to $75.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never run into a tax cut I didn't like,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also includes $75 million in tax breaks to the state's
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Since the legislative session started in February, Senate
Democrats have railed against Rowland's plan to lower the gas tax.
They argued that such a slash would suck money out of the state's
fund for road and bridge repairs and fail to give drivers relief at
the pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ryan, Rowland's budget chief, insisted that would not
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats eventually softened their stance, suggesting last
month they would be willing to cut the tax 7 cents over three
years. They then proposed cutting the 32-cent tax to a quarter for
one year, with the understanding that it could be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ''The risk with the gas tax -- in addition to compromising the
transportation fund -- is that it's impossible to control how the
large oil companies ... are not pocketing the profits and not
passing the savings on to consumers,'' said Senate Majority Leader
George Jepsen, D-Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the gas tax cut say it would mean a savings of $85
to $140 a year for a family that drives 30,000 miles. In addition,
lowering the tax would keep Connecticut drivers from crossing state
lines to fill their tanks at cheaper prices, they say.
</P>
<P>
   While they've budged on the gas tax issue, Democratic leaders
resisted Rowland's pitch to give parents a tuition tax credit of up
to $500 if they send their school-age children to private school.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he predicts the credit plan will be passed as a
separate bill in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of bipartisan support for that,'' Rowland said.
''I think we'll have a vote on it, but it won't be part of the
negotiated settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jepsen said the plan doesn't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe there is support for tuition tax credits and
I'm personally and completely opposed to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the tax credits say they're too much like vouchers
that would drain money from public education.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also dropped a proposal to whittle adults out of the
state's HUSKY health care plan -- a program they had argued is too
costly and could have saved the state about $32 million. The
program was originally designed to provide health care for
uninsured children, but was expanded to include their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''The program will be implemented,'' said House Minority Leader
Robert Ward, R-Northfield.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget -- about $12.3 billion -- includes roughly $30
million of new spending and stays $50 million under the state's
mandatory spending cap.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's really where we wanted to be,'' Rowland said. In
February, Rowland said he wanted to keep spending $84 million below
the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland and lawmakers also want to use the state's surplus to
pay for one-time expenses and retire debt. As of April 1, the state
Comptroller estimated the surplus at $264.5 million. But that
estimate has been reduced to about $240 million, Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   About $20 million of the surplus is earmarked for a bailout of
deficit-plagued University of Connecticut Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are still negotiating a package of bonding projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
