<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecution of Woman Debated  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- At the age of 18, blood vessels
in Anne Marie DeGree's brain ruptured and she was left with the
social skills of a 6-year-old and a lifetime of psychiatric care.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside County prosecutors now want the 37-year-old woman to
spend time in jail for stealing a roll of Life Savers and a bottle
of Pepsi from a hospital gift shop and attacking a police officer
when he tried to take them away.
</P>
<P>
   DeGree allegedly took the items in March when she was being
treated for illnesses related to her brain injury. She has been
charged with felony burglary and felony assault on a peace officer
for trying to take the officer's gun and scratching his face. She
could get up to 25 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Although the DeGree family, mental health advocates, law
enforcement officials and prosecutors all agree a crime was
committed, they disagree on how to handle brain-injured defendants
who are not legally insane.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody could have been killed in this situation,'' said
Deputy District Attorney Richard Bentley. ''Just because you have a
brain injury doesn't give you a free pass. ... I can tell you I've
convicted two people of murder who had similar problems and were
given passes on their actions for more than 10 years -- until they
killed somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   California law does not allow a diminished capacity defense,
meaning DeGree cannot be considered legally insane because she does
not have a psychological diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've made remarkable advances in treating the mentally ill.
Medications to treat their illnesses,'' said Dr. Thomas
Hafemeister, a mental health law professor and psychologist. ''But
when you're talking about brain injury, you're talking about
something that is virtually untreatable.''
</P>
<P>
   DeGree's injury, according to her parents, causes wild
fluctuations in her behavior, ranging from a docile child to a
willful teen-ager. She also lacks impulse control, which causes her
to overeat and take things that don't belong to her.
</P>
<P>
   ''One minute she's like a 6-year-old. The next she can curse you
out like a Marine drill instructor,'' said her mother, Helen
DeGree.
</P>
<P>
   Since her injury, DeGree has lived in a psychiatric facility,
except for three months in a mental health board and care home. She
was removed from the home because of her behavior, including the
theft of candy from a store, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Bentley does not dispute claims that DeGree has the capacity of
a 6-year-old, but says her condition has no bearing on his
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   DeGree's attorney, Deputy Public Defender John Isaacs, argues
she was unable to form an intent to commit the crime because of her
condition. He said she also has been unable to help with her case.
</P>
<P>
   ''There really isn't an easy answer,'' he said. ''We're stuck
with an absurd law that doesn't take into account people in her
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   When DeGree was arrested, deputies were unaware of her mental
capacity, said Sgt. Perri Portales-Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   DeGree was jailed for more than two weeks before she was
released on $5,000 bail. She is being held at the University of
California, Irvine, Medical Center's psychiatric ward pending a
June hearing.
</P>
<P>
   While attorneys say they are discussing a plea bargain that
would reduce the charges to a misdemeanor, the family is lobbying
for a change in the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's not a criminal. She's brain-injured,'' said DeGree's
father, Otis DeGree. ''We just thought for sure when the district
attorney saw her medical file, he would throw the case out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
