<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airline Wants Reporters' Info  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK BARTELS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- American Airlines is seeking
information given to reporters after a fatal plane crash last
summer and also wants a judge to block the release of pretrial
testimony from witnesses in lawsuits against the company.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers Thursday, airline attorneys asked U.S. District
Judge Henry Woods to issue an order to plaintiffs' lawyers to
reveal what documents they have released to the media. They also
asked the judge to require the lawyers to reveal ''the manner in
which the materials were provided.''
</P>
<P>
   American's attorneys argued that disclosure of witness testimony
before trial could influence potential jurors and could harm the
airline's reputation. American said the statements also could be
''used in a misleading, inaccurate or one-sided manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Woods ruled that information equivalent to trade
secrets, such as training manuals, should be kept confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1420 touched down June 1 and ran off the end of the
Little Rock National Airport runway, breaking apart, catching fire
and killing 11, including the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent plaintiff's motion, Capt. Cecil Ewell,
American's chief pilot at the time of the crash, said he would
never try to land in stormy conditions like those when the plane
crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Ewell said in his deposition that most American Airlines pilots
would take the same position and ''only an idiot would attempt to
land in a thunderstorm.''
</P>
<P>
   American cited Ewell's comments in its filing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Capt. Ewell's brief statement, however, was taken completely
out of context,'' American said. The quote was from a lengthy
answer in which Ewell said he did not believe Flight 1420's crew
knowingly flew into the thunderstorm, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff's attorney David Rapoport said Thursday he expects
victims' lawyers would oppose the airline's requests.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like a company that is awfully frightened about
evidence that is being developed,'' Rapoport said. ''I have been
actively involved in litigating cases for close to 20 years and
have not seen a motion like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   American's motion says its purpose was ''not to keep the media
from obtaining facts about the accident.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
