<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Miss Saigon' Closing in December  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Miss Saigon,'' the long-running British
musical set against the backdrop of the Vietnam War, will close
Dec. 31, after a nearly 10-year run of 4,063 performances.
</P>
<P>
   Its final curtain will come six months after the June 25 closing
of ''Cats,'' another big British musical produced by Cameron
Mackintosh.
</P>
<P>
   ''Much as I will miss 'Saigon' at the Broadway Theater, I am
utterly thrilled at how long this serious musical has run both on
Broadway and in London,'' Mackintosh said Thursday. ''I have no
doubt that 'Miss Saigon' will continue to appear all over the
globe, even though she might be in a different frock.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Miss Saigon,'' starring Jonathan Pryce and Lea Salonga, opened
in New York on April 11, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Its arrival was marked by controversy. Actors Equity originally
denied Pryce, who created the role of the Engineer in the London
production, permission to play in New York. Equity wanted an Asian
actor in the role.
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh canceled the show, but changed his mind after Equity
reversed its decision.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, written by Alain Boublil and Claude-Michel
Schonberg, has grossed more than $264 million and been seen by more
than 5.9 million theatergoers. It is a love story between an
American soldier and a young Vietnamese woman. Both Pryce and
Salonga won Tony Awards for their performances. The long-running
London production closed last October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
