<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comic Revisits Kent St. Shootings  </HEADLINE>
By AMY BETH GRAVES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENT, Ohio (AP) -- Chuck Ayers still shakes whenever he remembers
that it could have been him.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the line of fire just minutes before National Guard
troops shot at anti-Vietnam War protesters 30 years ago at Kent
State University.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings on May 4, 1970, killed four students and wounded
nine. Ayers, then a 22-year-old student, took pictures of the
protests for a photography class. He ducked into a campus building
just before the gunfire broke out.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as those times are to revisit, Ayers has decided to
talk about the shootings through his work as the illustrator for
the nationally syndicated comic strip ''Crankshaft.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sort of overwhelming for me,'' Ayers said. ''I'd always
been on the edges of it and suddenly with the strip out there, I'm
in the middle of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The strip, written by 1969 Kent State graduate Tom Batiuk, is
featuring a monthlong series about the shootings leading up to the
30th anniversary. The artists hope to educate young people about
the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Batiuk said the comic tries not to place blame for the
shootings; he wants readers could draw their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just trying to spotlight a particular aspect of our human
nature,'' Batiuk said. ''I tried to turn it into an engaging
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Next Thursday, Ayers plans to bring his 13-year-old daughter to
Kent State for a commemorative candlelight march.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll walk her through the campus and tell her the story
whether she wants to hear it or not,'' he said. ''This is hard for
me because she'll never fully understand the feelings of the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the first time since the shootings that all of
the students who were wounded will be on campus together. They will
meet with the mothers of the four slain students -- Allison Krause,
Jeffrey Miller, Sandra Scheuer and William Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   In the comic series, the character Pam describes her memories of
being a Kent State student and photographing the events leading up
to the shootings. The story is told while Pam walks through the
campus with her opinionated father, Crankshaft, and her two
children.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel it's pretty good at capturing the three generations. I
think the way it's playing out is absolutely fabulous,'' said Carol
Cartwright, Kent State president.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright was a 28-year-old teacher at Penn State University
when she heard about the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was one of those heart-stopping moments when you're
absolutely drawn to the news to find out what happened,'' she said.
''It goes through your mind that it can't possibly be true, it
can't come to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lewis, a Kent State sociology professor who witnessed the
shootings, said he anticipates a renewed interest in the event
because ''Crankshaft'' is printed in more than 320 newspapers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cartoons are read by youngsters. I anticipate young people
asking 'Did this really happen this way?''' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The comic strip touched Alan Canfora so much that he sent copies
to the family of the slain students.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a very moving commentary of the tragic event of
May 4, 1970,'' said Canfora, who was shot in the wrist that day.
''I think it's a very rare thing that a cartoon strip reveals such
sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   ------=-
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Crankshaft: http://www.uexpress.com/ups/comics/cs
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 0138 </TRAILER>
