<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemalan News Photographer Killed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A Guatemalan newspaper photographer was
shot and killed Thursday during violent street protests against bus
fare increases in which three other people reportedly died.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Martinez, 37, who was covering the weeklong protests for
the Guatemala City newspaper Prensa Libre, was killed when a
private security guard fired at students allegedly looting a
business, said Prensa Libre's news editor, Conrado Monroy.
</P>
<P>
   Two other men died of unspecified injuries at San Juan de Dios
General Hospital, a hospital public relations employee said. The
Radio Sonora station also said a woman shot alongside Martinez had
died of her wounds.
</P>
<P>
   President Alfonso Portillo, in an address to the nation, said he
lamented Martinez' death and set a deadline of noon Friday for
privately owned bus companies to roll back the fare increases or
face a government takeover of their lines.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier reports had indicated that 18 people, including two
other journalists, were wounded in the hours-long protests on
Thursday, said Fernanda Castejon, spokeswoman for Portillo. Several
received gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Among the wounded was Alexander Garcia, a cameraman for
Guatemala's Channel 7 television station, who suffered gunshot
wounds to his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Security guard Gustavo Garcia Rosales fired seven times into the
crowd with a 12-gauge shotgun, National Civil Police spokesman
Faustino Sanchez said. Another guard, Luis Fernando Ramirez, fired
a 9 mm pistol. Both were arrested after hundreds of protesters and
others gathered outside the mall to demand the guards be handed
over to them.
</P>
<P>
   The guard was part of a security detail employed at a local
shopping mall which the protesters apparently were trying to loot.
Other guards also apparently fired their weapons during the
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of protesters and others gathered outside the mall
after the shooting to demand that the guard be handed over to them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hundreds of riot police, backed up by a vehicle
equipped with a water cannon, were dispatched to the downtown area
to try to control the protests.
</P>
<P>
   The protests broke out after the government ignored demands by
university students in Guatemala City for a cancellation of a
recent fare increase of 25 to 36 percent in public transportation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 0142 </TRAILER>
