<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Families Evacuated in S. Carolina  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Police blocked off streets and
evacuated residents after an explosion Thursday at an ice company
plant released ammonia gas. At least two people were taken to
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were unsure what caused the blast at the Triangle
Ice Co., which was reported at about 9:30 p.m. Police said ammonia
is used as a coolant in machinery that makes ice.
</P>
<P>
   Two people -- a police officer and a resident -- were taken to
area hospitals Thursday night after being overcome by fumes, Mayor
Keith Summey said. The police officer was treated and released. The
mayor did not know the other victim's condition.
</P>
<P>
   Summey said residents were cleared from a mobile home park, with
officers going door-to-door.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy fog-like cloud could be seen about midnight coming up
from behind the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things seem to be settling down,'' said City Councilman Kurt
Taylor, who lives near the plant. ''People are just going to go in
and do the forensics, see what happened and try to get things
capped off. I'm not concerned at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
