<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Killed in Southern Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Guerrillas attacked military outposts in
southern Lebanon on Friday, killing four Israeli-allied militiamen
and wounding three others, Lebanese security officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas carried out an early morning raid on the Aramta
outpost, one of several crossing points linking the
Israeli-occupied zone in southern Lebanon with the rest of the
country, the officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   An explosion destroyed the outpost, killing four members of the
South Lebanon Army, a militia paid and armed by Israel to help its
troops patrol the border zone.
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports on the cause of the explosion.
Security officials said guerrillas infiltrated the position and
planted explosives. Others said a car bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack,
which escalated tensions in southern Lebanon amid efforts to smooth
Israel's troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon by July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the attack, which came amid a series of
hit-and-run raids by guerrillas, Israeli warplanes raided suspected
guerrilla hideouts in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese security officials said two Israeli jets fired two
missiles near Rihan, just south of Aramta. Black smoke billowed
from the area. There was no immediate word of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese guerrillas are believed to use the area to infiltrate
the occupied zone and attack Israeli troops and allied militiamen.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli military confirmed the air raid and said all planes
returned safely to the base.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah group said its guerrillas ''scored
direct hits'' with rockets and mortars on the edge of the occupied
zone in Aramta. It was not clear whether that included the
explosion at the Aramta outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli gunners also fired artillery at suspected guerrilla
positions on the outskirts of the market town of Nabatiyeh to the
southwest, the officials said. There was no immediate word on
casualties from the shelling.
</P>
<P>
   In another statement issued in Nabatiyeh, Hezbollah claimed
rocket attacks on Dabshe, Tohra and Sweida, a cluster of hilly
positions manned by Israeli and SLA militiamen. It did not give
details.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese officials confirmed the attacks and said they had no
reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war to oust the 1,500 Israeli
soldiers and 2,500 Israeli-backed militiamen controlling the
occupied zone, which Israel intends to vacate by July. Israel set
up the zone in 1985 to shield its northern territory from
cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
