<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Webber, Kings Struggle Offensively  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Chris Webber shot from inside and outside,
but the result was the same. Not much was falling for him or the
rest of the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   And you can't beat the Los Angeles Lakers if you aren't scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Webber had 22 points on 8 of 28 field-goal shooting in the
Kings' 113-89 loss to the Lakers on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''This loss hasn't sunk in. I hate to lose,'' Webber said. ''We
have to raise our level and now we get the home court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings return home for Game 3 Sunday trailing 2-0 in the
best-of-five first-round playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to go to him, but it's just not Chris,'' Kings
coach Rick Adelman said. ''We have to have other people really get
involved and do some things so the whole load is not on his
shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this season, the Kings had trouble scoring
against a team they beat once in four regular-season meetings. In
three of those games, including the one victory, the Kings scored
more than 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did not play very well offensively and that probably
surprised me the most because we've been able to score against this
team,'' Adelman said. ''They shut us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber had a career playoff high 28 points despite foul trouble
in Sacramento's 117-107 loss in Game 1 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he logged a grueling 41 minutes, the most of any
Kings player, and picked up just one foul. Webber also had 12
rebounds and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got to find a way to get him inside a little bit more where
he can take it to them. I really think he has the advantage
there,'' Adelman said. ''I don't worry about Chris. He's been the
rock for us for two years and he had a tough night shooting, but
he'll respond Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any time Webber or the rest of the Kings try to go
inside, they find Shaquille O'Neal waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a big body and a big presence down there, but you still
have to be able to have the confidence to go in at him,'' Corliss
Williamson said. ''We got him a couple fouls early in the game and
we kind of got away from that. We have to continue to take it to
him and hopefully he can get in foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were expecting the same Kings that scored in triple
digits against them during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know they had their expectations of coming and giving us a
game,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ''We were set up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kobe Bryant had a career playoff high 32 points and the
Lakers ran away after the Kings got within two points with 7{
minutes left in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento scored just three points the rest of the quarter and
trailed 56-41 at halftime. Webber had a shot blocked by Robert
Horry, then Jason Williams was blocked by O'Neal as the Lakers
restored their double-digit lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''You work on Shaq and A.C. Green and Horry are slipping in and
getting rebounds,'' Webber said.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of being down 2-0 was obvious in a subdued Kings
dressing room, where players hurried to change and leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is it. It's not like we have a seven-game series or
something. We have to win,'' Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think guys are going to come out and try to put it all on
the line, which we should have been doing the past two games.
Hopefully, we'll all respond and come back hard Sunday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
