<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Town officials call for congressional investigation of Pequotrecognition process  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LEDYARD, Conn. (AP) -- The mayor of Ledyard and the first
selectman of North Stonington are calling for a congressional
investigation into the process by which the Mashantucket Pequot
tribe was granted federal recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The Pequots received federal recognition in 1983 through a
Special Act of Congress. That allowed them to establish a
reservation and enter into a gambling compact with the state.
</P>
<P>
   They now operate a multibillion-dollar empire that includes the
Foxwoods Resort Casino, which opened in 1992 and is the world's
largest casino.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the reservation's neighboring towns on Thursday
told The Day of New London that a federal investigation is
warranted because of new information uncovered by author Jeff
Benedict and contained in his book ''Without Reservation: The
Making of America's Most Powerful Indian Tribe and Foxwoods, the
World's Largest Casino.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Benedict claims the present-day Mashantuckets have
no verifiable Pequot ancestry. It claims that some members,
specifically the family of former tribal chairman Skip Hayward,
have a thin blood relationship to the historic Narragansetts.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict claims that when the U.S. Congress bypassed the Bureau
of Indian Affairs to recognize the Mashantuckets and put an end to
the tribe's land claims Congress never investigated whether the
contemporary tribe descends from the historic Pequots.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the least we can do is ask for an investigation by
Congress,'' said Ledyard Mayor Wesley Johnson. ''They need to look
at this. They were deceived by the Mashantuckets.''
</P>
<P>
   North Stonington First Selectman Nicholas H. Mullane agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a well-researched book,'' said Mullane. ''It's
amazing, when you put all the pieces together, from start to
finish, what you come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mashantucket Pequots were not prepared to comment on the
book Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tribe is reviewing the book. Until that is completed, well
have nothing to say,'' said Bruce MacDonald, the tribe's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Preston, First Selectman Robert Congdon said he was
about halfway through the book, and found it interesting, but not
startling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've heard a lot of this before. We cried foul from early
on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congdon said his ''gut'' instinct is that Congress should look
into the tribe's origins and the establishment of its reservation,
but he is not ready to call for an investigation at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to address the book with our legal counsel in
Washington,'' he said. ''I'd want to talk about what actions there
are, if any.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a gaming compact between the Pequots and the state,
Connecticut receives 25 percent of the slot earnings at Foxwoods.
In March that was $16.2 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 0300 </TRAILER>
