<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury convicts former Wall Street executive in insider tradingscandal  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An X-rated movie actress will vigorously defend
herself despite the conviction of a former top Wall Street
executive accused of feeding her inside information on stocks, her
lawyer says.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Howard Shapiro, said Kathryn Gannon remains in
Canada, at least temporarily out of the reach of an indictment
bearing her name in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said he was disappointed with Thursday's conviction of
James McDermott Jr., the executive, and codefendant Anthony
Pomponio of all but one of eight counts in an indictment charging
conspiracy and securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even if it were correct, however, it does not follow that
Kathryn Gannon is guilty of the charges brought against her.
Indeed, she is not and she intends to contest them vigorously,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said the Department of Justice must decide whether it
will pursue plans to extradite Gannon, who is a Canadian citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're taking it one step at a time. I expect her to eventually
appear in a courtroom somewhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, former chief executive officer at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP;
Woods, held his head high as the jury forewoman notified the court
of the conviction. McDermott was a frequent guest on financial
programs in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He had appeared relaxed throughout a trial that featured
repeated references to his extramarital affair with Gannon, who
performs in X-rated movies under the name ''Marylin Star.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood set sentencing for July 17 on
charges that could bring up to 10 years in prison for McDermott,
48, of Briarcliff Manor, and Pomponio, 45, of North Caldwell, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The judge had directed before the trial that Gannon would only
be referred to as an actress, a model and a dancer who sometimes
goes by the stage name ''Marylin Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Two jurors who declined to identify themselves said outside
court that they did not know Gannon was a porn star and that it
would not have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   One male juror, though, smiled slightly and added, ''We didn't
think she was the Queen of England.''
</P>
<P>
   Gannon, the star of features including ''Fantasies of Marylin,''
''Pumped,'' ''The Violation of Marylin Star'' and ''Sins of the
Flesh,'' does not have any business in the United States since she
has quit the X-rated movie business, Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said McDermott and Pomponio were each having an
extramarital affair with Gannon. The men did not meet each other
until their arrests, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged McDermott gave Gannon secret information
about six stocks, allowing her to buy bank stocks that were about
to skyrocket in value after public announcements of mergers.
</P>
<P>
   She was accused of giving the information to Pomponio, the owner
of a New Jersey quartz- and glass-cutting company who met Gannon at
an adult trade show in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Pomponio and Gannon, 30, who has a home in Miami, Fla.,
allegedly made $170,000 in illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged McDermott, a $4 million-a-year executive,
gave Gannon more than $150,000 to gamble with in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, McDermott's lawyer, Denis McInerney, referred
to his client as a ''rocket scientist on bank stocks'' and admitted
that McDermott gave Gannon tips on stocks -- but only before he
learned the stocks involved merger deals. McDermott and McInerney
declined to comment after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   In final remarks to the jury before deliberations, Assistant
U.S. Attorney Alex Young Oh questioned whether McDermott's motives
could be considered innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you think that's how it really happened?'' Oh asked. ''Come
on. She was the actress, dancer and model. He was the stud stock
picker.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was something more to this scheme than just the money.
Maybe McDermott was trying to impress her. This is a way for him to
show her what he did. Maybe it was a macho thing,'' Oh said.
</P>
<P>
   Pomponio's lawyer, Thomas Dunn, said he would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   He said his client was ''pretty devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I really got to know the man and I really didn't buy the
government's case. I don't believe he did anything wrong,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   John G. Duffy, president of McDermott's former firm, said
business had not been affected by the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there is any way to describe it other than a
personal tragedy,'' Duffy told The New York Times. ''The guy had it
all and threw it all away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
