<DOCNO> APW20000428.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albert Pirro says Westchester DA is victim of smear  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Westchester District Attorney Jeanine
Pirro is still just a suburban prosecutor because of a federal
smear campaign, her much-investigated husband says.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Clinton administration's investigative tactics into
campaigns that are being run by Republicans'' have derailed Mrs.
Pirro's career, Albert Pirro said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody knows that my wife could have been and should have
been a statewide candidate for political office by now,'' Pirro
said at a news conference. ''The only thing that has held her back
is the fact that her husband ... has been subjected to constant
spotlight, scrutiny and criticism for business transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White had no comment, spokesman Herb
Haddad said.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro, one of the state's top lobbyists and a major
Republican fund-raiser, spoke the day after prosecutors alleged
that a loan taken out by Jeanine Pirro in 1993, ostensibly to buy a
$40,000 Mercedes, was ''an empty financial transaction, a sham''
used by her husband to cover up tax fraud. Albert Pirro said the
allegation was ''evidence of the prosecution's campaign to smear
the Westchester district attorney and to derail her career.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pirro, Westchester County's biggest vote-getter, a national
TV commentator and a veteran of People magazine's ''50 Most
Beautiful People'' list, has never been charged in the case. She
will not comment until the case is concluded, said spokeswoman Anne
Marie Corbalis.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is scheduled to begin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pirro has often been mentioned for higher office, but her
husband's refusal to divulge information about his business, a
paternity suit against him, a fruitless bribery investigation and
the tax case have been roadblocks to her career.
</P>
<P>
   The tax case alleges that Albert Pirro and his brother Anthony,
who was his accountant, conspired to hide about $1 million in
Albert Pirro's income by masking personal expenses as business
deductions. Albert Pirro says he has paid all the back taxes and
blames his brother for bad tax returns. His brother blames him.
</P>
<P>
   Though the indictment alleges that many of the expenses were
family-oriented, like vacations, baby sitters, toys and veterinary
expenses, the alleged loan arrangement is the closest connection so
far between the district attorney and her husband's tax case.
</P>
<P>
   The new court papers say that Albert Pirro, in the name of one
of his many companies, leased a 1989 Mercedes-Benz for his wife in
late 1988. The lease payments were fraudulently deducted as
business expenses through 1992, although the car was used by Mrs.
Pirro, then a county judge, ''for personal purposes,'' the papers
say.
</P>
<P>
   She took out a $41,000 loan in January 1993 and paid her
husband's company $39,470 from her personal account. However, the
prosecution says, the company made the payments on Mrs. Pirro's
loan and paid it off entirely in November 1993, the month she was
elected district attorney. It then sold the car to a dealership for
$32,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''The loan taken by Jeanine Pirro was an empty financial
transaction, a sham intended to make it look like Jeanine Pirro had
purchased the vehicle ... and was responsible for the payments,''
the papers say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 0341 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000428.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sentencing for killer mom delayed, judge to consider abuse impact  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) -- LeRoy Leubner came to court wanting to see
his ex-wife sent to jail for burning down her house with the
couple's 13-year-old autistic son inside.
</P>
<P>
   He was pleased, though, that Cayuga County Judge Peter Corning
instead adjourned the sentencing and agreed to hear evidence of
domestic abuse regarding Michelle Davis, who claims she killed her
son to stop him from raping and abusing her.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' attorney asked for the last-minute adjournment so Corning
could consider whether Davis was responsible for her actions
because of the alleged abuse she suffered. If Davis' case meets the
criteria under the state's domestic abuse laws, she could receive a
significantly lighter sentence, including immediate probation.
</P>
<P>
   Leubner said Davis made up the rape allegations to obtain
leniency. He said his son, although big at 5-foot-7, 155 pounds,
was not violent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Danny was convicted of a crime and has never had a chance to
defend himself. None of this is true and a hearing will give us a
chance to challenge her lies,'' Leubner said outside the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   First-degree manslaughter carries a maximum penalty of 25 years
but it was expected Davis was going to receive a term of between
three to five years Thursday. Leubner is confident the hearing will
undermine Davis' story and convince the judge she should receive a
longer sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''She deserves to spend a lot more time in jail for what she
did. If we have to wait a little longer to see that happen, we can
wait,'' Leubner said
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors at one time considered bringing death
penalty charges against the 37-year-old Davis, she was allowed to
plead guilty in March to first-degree manslaughter and use an
''affirmative defense,'' which holds that she suffered from
''extreme emotional disturbance'' the night of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Davis admitted using a candle and nail polish remover to start a
fire in her Fleming home last Sept. 4, killing her 13-year-old son,
Daniel Leubner, who was asleep on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   Her plea came several days after a closed four-day hearing on
whether to suppress her statement as evidence. It was later
revealed for the first time that in her statement, Davis alleged
her son had raped her and beaten her on several occasions,
including the night of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they investigated Davis' claim and found no evidence
to back up her allegation of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Corning will hold a hearing in late May or early June. The judge
rejected a proposal from Davis' lawyers to use a transcript of the
closed hearing instead of calling back witnesses to testify.
Defense attorneys said they could have their case ready by next
Wednesday if they were permitted ot use the transcript as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney James Vargason opposed using testimony from
the closed hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't cross-examine a transcript,'' Vargason said after
court.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney David Elkovitch said testimony would focus on
the effects of post-traumatic stress syndrome and rape trauma
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Davis remains free on bail pending her sentencing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
