<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 39; Dow Down 65  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today, with
technology shares rising for the second straight day while
blue-chip stocks came under selling pressure amid concerns over
rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq
composite index was up 39.30 at 3,731.87. The Dow Jones industrial
average was down 65.46 at 10,822.64.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was down 2.07 at 1,462.85.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were led by a rally semiconductor shares.
Intel gained 2 11/16 to 128, Broadcom rose 3\ to 174 and PMC-Sierra
jumped 9 5/16 to 189 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   But the gains in the high-tech sector couldn't prop up the
broader market, which was weighed down by fears of rising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that Americans' incomes rose
last month even faster than spending, something that hasn't
happened since October.
</P>
<P>
   But although people made more money last month, they didn't put
significantly more away in savings. The report showed that personal
savings rate -- savings as a percentage of after-tax income -- only
rose slightly to 0.4 percent in March from a record low of 0.2
percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   That provided another sign that the economy continues to grow at
a brisk pace, another factor for the Federal Reserve to consider at
their policy-making meeting on May 16. Most economists expect the
Fed to raise interest rates for the sixth time since June as they
attempt to keep inflationary pressures under control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market has a governor on it right now ... it's called the
Fed meeting next month,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of
market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ''Until
that meeting, there will be a lid on the upside of this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 129.95 million
shares, down from Thursday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index up 4.23 at 498.81.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.25 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 2.09 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 2.31 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
2.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
