<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Body of kidnapped consultant found strangled, burned in NJ swamp  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A New Jersey man could face the death
penalty in Kentucky for kidnapping a British computer consultant
who was found dead in a New Jersey swamp with marks indicating he
had been strangled and set afire.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe the suspect, Gregory J. Marcinski,
impersonated an FBI agent to kidnap Paul Jeffrey Gale because Gale
was dating Marcinski's former lover.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski, 23, of Brick, has been held without bail since April
20, three days after Gale was reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   Gale's shirtless body was found about 2 a.m. Thursday in a
shallow grave two miles from Marcinski's residence, said FBI
Special Agent Garey S. Chin. It bore ''ligature markings'' on the
neck and burn marks from a flammable liquid, Chin said.
</P>
<P>
   The body was found after Marcinski's housemate, Preston C. Foray
Jr., was arrested Wednesday night and gave agents the location, the
FBI said in a court filing. Foray, 21, admitted helping Marcinski
hide the body, the document said.
</P>
<P>
   Medical examiners suspect the victim died of strangulation, but
a final determination and positive identification might not be made
until next week, FBI Special Agent Sandra Carroll, a spokeswoman
for the Newark office, said today.
</P>
<P>
   The body was ''burnt beyond facial recognition,'' leaving
medical examiners to seek Gale's dental records and DNA from his
twin brother in their efforts to confirm his identity, Carroll
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gale, 28, who lived in Naples, Fla., was awakened by Marcinski
and kidnapped April 17 from his hotel room in Florence, Ky., but
investigators do not yet know where he was killed, Chin said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski told Foray that he killed the man after driving around
with him for about an hour, Foray told agents, according to papers
filed Thursday by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ''The understanding, at this point, is that it occurred
somewhere between Kentucky and New Jersey. The exact point is
unknown,'' said Linda Tally Smith, an assistant commonwealth
attorney for Boone County, Ky. Regardless of the location, Kentucky
can charge Marcinski with murder because the crime originated
there, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky is awaiting autopsy results and other information
before deciding whether to charge Marcinski with murder, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will probably become a capital case, but we're still
looking at it,'' Smith said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Marcinski is being held in the Monmouth County, N.J.,
jail awaiting extradition to Kentucky on state kidnapping charges
and a federal charge of impersonating an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Foray, who lived at the home of Marcinski's grandmother, does
not face Kentucky charges, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Foray told agents on Wednesday that when he saw Marcinski on
April 17, Marcinski disclosed the kidnapping and showed him the
body in the trunk of Marcinski's grandmother's Buick, according to
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Foray spoke softly and kept his head bowed during a brief
appearance before U.S. Magistrate John Hughes in Trenton on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes set bail at $1 million, but said he would release Foray
on $90,000 in property bonds from his parents on the condition that
he live and work with his father in Point Pleasant and wear an
electronic monitoring device.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the judge ordered Foray to spend Thursday night
in protective custody at the Monmouth County Jail, where Marcinski
is also being held.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Michael E. Wilbert told the judge his client is
''despondent,'' and said Foray could face a ''catastrophic result''
in jail without protective custody. He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Foray faces up to 15 years in federal prison if found guilty of
accessory after the fact of a kidnapping, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Treby Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski, a volunteer emergency medical technician, flashed an
EMT badge and computer-generated FBI credentials to gain access to
Gale's room at the Holiday Inn in Florence, a city across the Ohio
River from Cincinnati, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Gale recently lived in Mount Laurel, N.J., where he worked as a
computer programmer for TRW Integrated Supply. He was working for
TRW in Kentucky this month as a consultant in the merger of two
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Marcinski became enraged that Gale had been
dating his ex-girlfriend, Darla Guidie, and drove the Buick 800
miles to Kentucky to confront Gale.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski identified himself as Special Agent ''Trimble'' and
handcuffed Gale before placing him in the front seat of the Buick
in the early morning hours of April 17, authorities have said.
</P>
<P>
   Guidie told the FBI that Marcinski made the fake identification
on his computer and ''bragged that he had gotten the format for the
phony FBI credentials off of the Internet,'' according to court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   She had a restraining order against Marcinski, said John Mercun,
the executive assistant prosecutor for Ocean County, where Brick is
located.
</P>
<P>
   Marcinski, a member of the Community First Aid Squad and a
self-employed computer technician, was also arrested last August
when another ex-girlfriend told police he assaulted her and grabbed
her new boyfriend by the neck, pushing him to the floor, the Asbury
Park Press of Neptune reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
