<HEADLINE> Dow Down 118; Nasdaq Up 42  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology shares
rising for the second straight day while blue-chip stocks came
under selling pressure amid concerns over rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite
index was up 42.15 at 3,816.18. The Dow Jones industrial average
was down 118.51 at 10,769.59.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was down 10.91 at 1,454.01.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in technology stocks were led by a rally semiconductor
shares. Intel gained 1 15/16 to 127\, Broadcom rose 7\ to 178 and
PMC-Sierra jumped 8 1/8 to 190}, all on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   But the gains in the high-tech sector couldn't prop up the
broader market, which was weighed down by fears of rising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that Americans' incomes rose
last month even faster than spending, something that hasn't
happened since October.
</P>
<P>
   But although people made more money, they didn't put
significantly more away in savings. The report showed that personal
savings rate -- savings as a percentage of after-tax income -- only
rose slightly to 0.4 percent in March from a record low of 0.2
percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   That provided another sign that the economy continues to grow at
a brisk pace, another factor for the Federal Reserve to consider at
their policy-making meeting on May 16. Most economists expect the
Fed to raise interest rates for the sixth time since June as they
attempt to keep inflationary pressures under control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market has a governor on it right now ... it's called the
Fed meeting next month,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of
