<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ninth livery driver this year killed on the job  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A livery cab driver was fatally shot outside a
Brooklyn home early this morning, becoming the ninth driver killed
on the job this year.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, whose name was withheld pending notification of his
family, was pronounced dead on arrival, said Brookdale Hospital
spokesman Malcolm E. Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old driver had been shot once in the back of the
head, Kafka said.
</P>
<P>
   The man was shot in his cab at 3:55 a.m. outside of 110 Elton
St. in the Highland Park section. There was no immediate arrest.
The driver did not have a bulletproof partition in his green
Lincoln Town Car, and police say he had picked up two passengers
who hailed him on the street, a practice the police commissioner
has said is dangerous and against taxi commission rules.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, livery driver Jose Olivares, 35, was fatally shot in
the head during a botched robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rash of shootings recalled the early '90s, when
livery cab drivers were under siege. In 1992, cabbies were killed
at the rate of nearly one per week -- a total of 45 slayings, the
highest ever.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, in March and April 1990, seven livery drivers were
killed in six weeks, prompting scores of drivers to quit or switch
to day shifts. Six of the slayings took place in the Bronx; one was
in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven livery drivers were killed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Livery cab drivers often support their families by working in
underserved areas of the city, and tend to get their customers
through telephone calls to dispatchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 1123 </TRAILER>
