<HEADLINE> Winds Drive Ariz. Forest Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOBE, Ariz. (AP) -- Winds and low humidity were no help to
firefighters battling the season's first major wildfire that had
scorched more than 1,800 acres in the Tonto National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters struggling over steep terrain were pulled away from
the front lines Thursday as winds gusting to 25 mph fanned the
flames. Gusts of up to 40 mph were expected today.
</P>
<P>
   ''That really heightens our concern,'' forest spokesman Jim
Payne said. ''Those winds mean that fire has the capacity to spread
even more.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately known what sparked the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   A ranch and other buildings as well as archaeological sites and
the habitat of an endangered Mexican spotted owl were threatened,
Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire began about 3 p.m. Wednesday near Coon Creek and
quickly raged through dry underbrush and trees in the remote Sierra
Ancha Wilderness northeast of Phoenix, the U.S. Forest Service said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, officials evacuated a dozen people who were
camping, working at a nearby ranch and staffing a forest lookout on
Aztec Peak. A state highway also was temporarily closed, Payne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, a wildfire ultimately burned over 65,000 acres
in the same general area of the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Globe is about 75 miles east of Phoenix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
