<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Workers Set To Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Some 82,000 private sector workers were set
to strike next week after union members on Friday overwhelmingly
rejected the pay deal their leaders had negotiated with employers.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was a defeat for the leaders of the main trade union
confederation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the leaders agreed to a settlement with the
Confederation of Norwegian Business and Industry that included a
pay increase of 3.5 percent to 4 percent and a fifth week of
vacation starting in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   More than 64 percent of the 146,000 union members who voted
rejected the deal. The wage increase was criticized as too meager.
In addition, many workers already have five weeks of vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the groundswell of opposition was the central
bank's interest rate recent increase of 0.25 percent in interest
rates. Workers said the increase would annul the entire pay raise
by raising mortgage costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The majority for 'no' is surprisingly large,'' the labor
confederation's vice chairman Jan Balstad said.
</P>
<P>
   The employers' group had no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   About 82,000 workers were set to begin striking Wednesday,
starting with hotels in 10 cities, many ferries and product
delivery services, which threatened to leave empty shelves in many
grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Norway's two main tabloid newspapers planned to cease
publishing, most construction work was to be halted and the state
liquor store chain would be forced to close.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no solution, the strike will gradually be stepped up
to involve more businesses, and some observers said it could last
for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The unions said they planned to leave key sectors like the
offshore oil and gas industry, the metal industry and mass
transportation unaffected for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Labor confederation leader Yngve Haagensen and leaders of many
of the 17 individual federations earlier this week urged their
223,000 members to vote for the deal but said they would lead a
strike if the rank and file rejected the agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
