<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor Giuliani has prostate cancer  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, showing a rare public
soft side, thanked New Yorkers for their get well wishes a day
after revealing that he has prostate cancer that could curtail his
Senate run against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very, very nice and very indicative of what the city of
New York is all about,'' Giuliani said today during a brief City
Hall news conference. ''The people of New York City sort of have a
reputation for being sort of tough and have a reputation for being
kind of cynical, but the reality is that they are the most generous
and the most loving in the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''Regardless of political differences, we all stick
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the well-wishers today was Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, who called and then put a political rival, Jerusalem Mayor
Ehud Olmert on the line as well. Likely Republican Presidential
nominee George W. Bush and former Sen. Bob Dole, himself a prostate
cancer survivor, also sent their best wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, 55, reiterated that he would continue his Senate race
for the time being. He said he would likely halve his campaign
schedule in upcoming weeks, but will attend events in Saratoga
tonight and Buffalo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said more tests, taken Thursday, revealed that his
cancer was limited to his prostate.
</P>
<P>
   In Giuliani's otherwise business-as-usual mode, his campaign
announced today that it is beginning a massive direct mail campaign
and that it had also completed a large radio and television ''ad
buy.'' The ads are to begin airing in May.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday how his diagnosis would affect the Senate race,
he replied, ''I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think in fairness to me, to the Republican Party, to all of
the parties and everybody else you need some time to think about
it. And I really need to know what the course of treatment is going
to be before I can evaluate,'' he said. ''And then, after I
determine that, then I will figure out does it make sense this year
or doesn't it or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he also appeared upbeat and energetic as he
confirmed speculation that he has a ''treatable form of prostate
cancer'' that was ''diagnosed at an early stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he got regular prostate checkups because his
father died at age 73 of prostate cancer in 1981. Giuliani, who
rarely speaks about personal matters to the media, said his own
cancer reminded him of his father's illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''It brings up very painful memories,'' he said. ''And, you
know, I miss my father every day of my life. And he's a very, very
important reason for why I'm standing here as the mayor of New York
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, campaigning upstate on Thursday, spoke briefly by
telephone with the mayor and wished him ''a speedy and complete
recovery,'' said her spokeswoman, Karen Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   Other well-wishers included friend and foe alike -- and ranged
from Gov. George Pataki to the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, who had considered challenging Giuliani for the
GOP Senate nomination, issued a statement offering his prayers and
support, adding that health issues transcend politics. Through his
spokesman, Lazio declined to say whether he would enter the race if
Giuliani dropped out. The New York Senate primary is in September.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's wife, Donna Hanover, released a statement asking for
as much privacy for her husband as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very optimistic about Rudy's recovery,'' she said. ''We
have discussed this and I will be very supportive of him in dealing
with the choices he has to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate, a gland involved in semen production, is
the second most common type of cancer found in American men but
early detection greatly increases the chance of successful
treatment. About 179,300 men were diagnosed with the disease in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Treatments include the radical prostatectomy -- the removal of
the prostate -- and radiation. ''Over the next week, maybe two
weeks, maybe 2{ or three weeks, I'll figure out with my doctors
what the best form of treatment will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Catalona of Barnes-Jewish Hospital in St. Louis, who
removed the cancerous prostate of Yankee manager Joe Torre last
year, said that with surgery, a patient is typically in the
hospital for three days.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're usually able to return to normal activities within a
few weeks,'' he said, ''but they're anemic and it takes 6 to 8
weeks or somewhat longer to build their blood count up.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Giuliani should be able to resume his mayoral
schedule after that and also run for Senate, Catalona replied:
''Absolutely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 1205 </TRAILER>
