<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Bounce Back  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices rebounded today in early
dealings on the Chicago Board of Trade, a day after getting
pummeled in a weather-related selloff.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for mostly dry weather in the Midwest this weekend
supported corn and soybeans. Both crops remain vulnerable to
subnormal soil dryness despite a spate of recent rains.
</P>
<P>
   No heavy rains are expected until next weekend, and traders said
it was too early to deal contracts based on those forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat also stabilized after the selloff, although
market-watchers said gains would be limited by the start of harvest
and generally favorable conditions for both the winter wheat crop
and for spring planting.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose 1\ cent to $2.55\ a bushel; July
corn rose \ cent to $2.34{ a bushel; July oats rose } cent to $1.23
a bushel; July soybeans rose { cent to $5.45{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures were lower in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .23 cent to 69.17 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 84.27 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .05 cent to 77 cents a pound; May frozen pork bellies fell .22
cent to 99.70 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
