<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Pilots To Get On-Board Meals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Hoping to eliminate growling stomachs in the
cockpit, Delta Air Lines plans to make meals available to pilots on
flights where food is served.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said the program, which it is starting voluntarily, will
cost $3 million to $5 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's pilots have no contractual provision for in-flight
meals. They get money to buy food at airports to bring aboard, but
long lines and quick connections often make that impossible.
</P>
<P>
   On international flights, the pilots typically eat airline food.
But on domestic flights, extra meals are first offered to flight
attendants -- leaving many pilots hungry on long trips.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes we get food, and sometimes we don't,'' said Delta
Capt. Andy Deane, a spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association,
the union that represents Delta's 9,200 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and the union are negotiating a new contract, which
becomes amendable next month. Deane said the pilots plan to make
the food provision mandatory in the contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
