<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Fla. Lawmaker Gets 5 Years  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE WILSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- An ousted state senator was sentenced to the
maximum five years in federal prison for his role in a $2 million
Medicare fraud scheme.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Alan Gold on Friday rejected a two-year
sentence recommended in a plea bargain, citing Alberto Gutman's
''callous disregard'' of the public trust and five years of lies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most astounding, while engaged in his obstruction he even
chaired the Florida Senate's Criminal Justice Committee,'' Gold
wrote in a 35-page order rejecting Gutman's attempt to pull out of
his plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman, a Republican lawmaker for 15 years, also was fined
$50,000, ordered to pay $98,175 restitution and placed on probation
for three years after prison.
</P>
<P>
   Winning re-election from a largely working-class Hispanic
district even under indictment, he resigned from the Florida Senate
last fall as part of the plea bargain and would have faced removal
from office had he not.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman's lawyers alleged prosecutors broke terms of the plea
agreement, but said Gutman would report to prison next month while
an appeal is pursued.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Marci, were indicted in 1998 along with 23
others in a $15 million fraud investigation of home health care
administrator Mederi of Dade County Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it was the largest Medicare fraud uncovered
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Others who were forced out of office during a series of
corruption investigations in Miami included two Miami-Dade County
commissioners, two city commissioners and a city manager.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman pleaded guilty to felony conspiracy for helping set up
two home-health care companies that never did any legitimate
business, used voter lists to get names of purported patients and
collected $843,648 from Medicare. A third company set up by a
codefendant generated $1.2 million in false billings.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gutman earlier pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor and was
sentenced to six months of house arrest, $15,000 restitution and
three years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   Codefendant Maricela Maury, an informant whom Gutman's defense
painted as a more pivotal participant, was sentenced Thursday to a
year on probation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
