<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Original Buffalo wing sauce going Japanese  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Eighteen tons of hot goods from Buffalo are
winging their way to Japan. Not hot as in stolen. Hot as in, hot.
</P>
<P>
   The bar that invented Buffalo-style chicken wings shipped 1,500
cartons of its hot sauce to Tokyo-based ISM Co. on Thursday. The
company plans to work with one of the world's largest advertising
agencies to turn Japanese taste buds on to Buffalo's most famous
culinary contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The shipment is the biggest order ever landed by Mar-K Ltd., the
Buffalo company that manufactures, bottles and distributes Frank &AMP;
Teressa's Original Anchor Bar Buffalo Wing Sauce. Owner Joanne
Kaminski said the Japanese distributor is already talking about
placing an order for 36 tons in June.
</P>
<P>
   After that, orders will be based on how well the fiery sauce
sells in a country where most dishes have traditionally been milder
than even the tamest Anchor Bar flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big hurdle, because Buffalo wing sauce is a brand-new
item in Japan,'' Kaminski told The Buffalo News. ''But the sauce
has two things going for it: It's American and it's original, and
both of these factors are regarded highly in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mas Ishihara, owner of ISM, is a former Rochester resident who
developed a taste for hot wings on a visit to Buffalo and then
bantered with Kaminski on the Internet about bringing wings to his
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Mar-K has filled many small orders for customers all over the
Orient but Kaminski said this will be the first large-scale push to
market Buffalo chicken wings in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   She was somewhat encouraged after participating in Foodex Japan
2000 in March.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of older, more traditional Japanese people were tasting
the wings and saying things like, 'Agh, horrible.' They thought it
was just too hot and spicy. But the younger people were ecstatic.
They love the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Arun Jain, chairman of the marketing department at the
University at Buffalo School of Management, said the sauce may
succeed based on the changing palates of many Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ''They seem to be moving from blander food to more spicy
things,'' said Jain, who has traveled in Japan. ''I see it with a
lot of Japanese students who come here to study.''
</P>
<P>
   Jain encouraged marketers to work closely with restaurants on
developing creative uses for the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why couldn't you use it with shrimp or even fried fish?'' he
said. ''If you can get the creative juices flowing in Japanese
restaurants and homes, this could really take off.''
</P>
<P>
   All three varieties of the Anchor Bar sauce will be marketed in
Japan -- original, hotter and suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had real reservations about the 'suicidal' label and even
let Mas know that we could rename it,'' Kaminski said. ''But he
said, 'Oh, no. We think it's very funny.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 1307 </TRAILER>
