<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Taps Aide To Run Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush has selected
longtime friend Don Evans as chairman of his Republican
presidential campaign, signaling his pleasure with the team of
Texas confidants who helped launch his White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign announced the appointment today.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don is a good man and a great friend,'' Bush said in a
statement distributed by his campaign. ''He is an experienced chief
executive and someone that I trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who has led Bush's record-breaking fund-raising effort,
said, ''I am honored to be able to serve America in this sort of
way.'' He is an oil and gas businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to all of America learning what I already knew,
and that is this is a man you can trust, an extraordinary leader, a
man who cares about all Americans. If you love America, you're a
friend of George Bush's,'' Evans said in a telephone interview with
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   He and the rest of Bush's political team are in Washington for a
series of political and fund-raising meetings to prepare for the
Republican National Convention in August and the fall campaign
against Democrat nominee-in-waiting Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement formalizes a role Evans has filled for Bush
since the first days of the governor's presidential campaign.
Though Evans' official job was chief fund-raiser, he has been the
de facto chief executive officer of Bush's political operation.
</P>
<P>
   Naming Evans chairman leaves no doubt that Bush has dismissed
the grumbling in some GOP circles that he needs to expand his inner
circle beyond the close-knit band of aides from Texas. The
complaints subsided as Bush solidified his standing in recent polls
and formed advisory committees loaded with Washington operatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Evans have known each other for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is not a surprise; aides said last week Evans
was virtually certain to get the job, and he was introduced in
Washington meetings this week as the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said a general chairman may join the campaign in the fall
to serve as an authoritative voice for Bush in media interviews.
Evans, however, would have more influence as the campaign's CEO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
