<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deere To Cut 300 Jobs at Iowa Plant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOLINE, Ill. (AP) -- Deere &AMP; Co. plans to cut about 300 jobs by
phasing out engine production at a plant in Dubuque, Iowa, over the
next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Deere expects to cut the jobs through normal attrition, and
officials do not foresee any layoffs, according to a company
statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, all John Deere Dubuque Works employees will help
manufacture construction equipment at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The engine operations jobs cut at the Dubuque plant will move to
plants in either Waterloo, Iowa, or Torreon, Mexico, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 300 jobs represent about 20 percent of the plant's current
work force.
</P>
</TEXT>
