<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman on Friday ordered
state Human Services officials to eventually close the beleaguered
Greystone Park Psychiatric Hospital in Parsippany.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the hospital is no longer ''functioning in a manner
that is perceived as safe.'' The governor wanted an immediate
assessment of every patient to identify those who can receive
alternative care.
</P>
<P>
   State Human Services Commissioner Michele K. Guhl said it may
take as long as three years to move all of Greystone's patients.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued earlier this month found the hospital's 610
patients were crowded into bedrooms and living in unsanitary
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's decision comes on the heels of a sexual assault and
other incidents at the hospital, which is more than 100 years old.
</P>
<P>
   A leading state Democratic critic earlier this week called on
the hospital's chief executive officer to resign after a
21-year-old male patient was charged with sexually assaulting a
19-year-old mildly retarded female patient in an elevator of the
hospital's main administration building.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's order also follows the October escape of a
civilly committed sex offender, the arrest of four Greystone
employees for assaulting and illegally restraining another patient
in March, and an investigation into at least a dozen employees
failing to report a suicide attempt last year.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said there continues to be a need for a long-term
psychiatric facility in northern New Jersey. But she said many of
the patients can be treated in smaller facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, we have the unique opportunity to take a hospital that
was built in the 1800s and replace it with more appropriate, more
humane facilities for people with mental illness,'' Guhl said in a
statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
