<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Finds Croatia Human Remains  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- U.N. investigators found the remains of
about 10 people at a site near the central town of Gospic, where
dozens were believed slain and buried by Croats during the 1991
war, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After three weeks of digging, forensics examiners ''have
recovered some human remains'' in the village of Obradovic Varos,
said Steve Chambers, an official with the U.N. war crimes tribunal
in The Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe there are 10 human remains'' that were unearthed
there, he said, adding that the exact number of bodies would be
known after pathological examinations next week in the capital,
Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers spoke to reporters in Gospic after the court's
examiners finished their work in Obradovic Varos.
</P>
<P>
   Between 60 and 120 people -- mostly Serbs, but also dissenting
Croats -- disappeared in late 1991 and were presumed killed and
buried at several locations near Gospic, 60 miles southwest of
Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed that Serbs, who took up arms in 1991 to
oppose Croatia's independence from Yugoslavia, committed the
majority of war crimes in the fighting that followed. But human
rights groups said they believe Croats also killed Serb civilians
in Gospic and several other places.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's new, pro-Western government allowed the tribunal to
investigate in Gospic, unlike the previous government of the late
President Franjo Tudjman, which claimed Croats did not commit war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Three former military officials told tribunal investigators
about Gospic in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The three blamed wartime military commanders in Gospic -- Gen.
Mirko Norac and Col. Tihomir Oreskovic -- for orchestrating the
murderous campaign. They also said former top government officials,
including Tudjman and the late Defense Minister Gojko Susak, knew
about the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Norac, Oreskovic and former government officials have denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   A Croatian investigative team also participated in the
exhumation. Reporters were not allowed near the site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1335 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
