<DOCNO> APW20000428.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deep Israel Lebanon Pullback Cited  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Eager to secure international backing for its
planned withdrawal from Lebanon, Israel suggested Friday that it
would meet a U.N. demand to redeploy behind a 1923 colonial
boundary, the deepest possible pullback.
</P>
<P>
   Special U.N. envoy Terje Roed-Larsen met with Israel's army
chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, and top commanders to discuss
the line to which Israel would withdraw. Cartographers attended the
session at the Israeli Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Roed-Larsen, who began a Mideast fact-finding tour on Thursday,
has told Israel it should pull back to the boundary drawn by
Britain and France when they carved up the Middle East in 1923,
Israeli and U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Roed-Larsen issued
a statement Friday noting that U.N. resolution 425 calls for Israel
to withdraw to the 1923 line.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thus far, there seems to be no disagreement on this issue,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has not said how far he is
willing to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The 1923 line is the only internationally recognized boundary
between Israel and Lebanon and was reaffirmed in a 1949 armistice
agreement, U.N. officials said. Israel and Lebanon, still
officially at war, don't have a mutually agreed border.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 1950s, Israel built a fence marking its version
of the border, which was fairly close to the 1923 boundary,
although in some places the fence deviated from the line for
topographical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Israel moved the border northward by up to a few
hundred yards following attacks on border towns. Israeli map
experts estimate that the total area in dispute is no more than 1.2
square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Israel does not expect difficulties in reaching agreement with
the United Nations on the line to which Israel's troops must
withdraw, an Israeli official said Friday, hinting that Israel was
open to the U.N. demand for a withdrawal to the 1923 line. The
official spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have said they would recognize the United
Nations as the final arbiter in disputes over the border
demarcation.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has sought U.N. backing for its withdrawal since it has
been unable to negotiate the pullback with the Lebanese government.
After the pullback, U.N. peacekeepers, who now serve as a buffer
between the Israeli occupation zone in south Lebanon and the rest
of Lebanon, would redeploy along the border.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel accepts the 1923 demarcation line as its boundary with
Lebanon, this could set a precedent for Israeli-Syrian peace talks,
which have been deadlocked for two months over a border dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has indicated it is willing to return all of the Golan
Heights, captured in the 1967 Mideast war, to Syria and draw the
new border based on the 1923 demarcations. However, Syria has
insisted that it also be given land it had captured in border
skirmishes between 1949 and 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has refused to do so, saying Syria had no claim to these
areas.
</P>
<P>
   When Barak pledged in his 1999 election campaign that he would
withdraw from Lebanon by July 2000, he was still optimistic that he
could reach an agreement with Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Israeli-Syrian talks broke down over the border
issue, and Israel was forced to make plans for a unilateral
withdrawal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1336 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000428.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
