<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Human Rights Meeting Ends  </HEADLINE>
By CLARE NULLIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- After a six-week session which climaxed in
surprisingly strong criticism of Russian violations in Chechnya,
the U.N. Human Rights Commission ended Friday with a plea for the
most basic right of all: that to life.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot allow human beings to die in large numbers before
our very eyes,'' U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights Mary
Robinson said in an appeal for more international action against
the drought in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plight of millions of people at risk must impel the search
for peace and security, for respect for human rights, and for the
expression of international solidarity,'' Robinson told the
53-nation commission's closing session.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is the top U.N. human rights watchdog. Its
meetings often bog down in differences between developing countries
wanting more emphasis on economic rights and the United States and
Europe striving for better protection of civil and political
liberties.
</P>
<P>
   This year was no different, and the commission extended its
growing list of themes by appointing new investigators on the right
to food and to adequate housing.
</P>
<P>
   Activists like Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch took
heart from a landmark decision to appoint a special U.N. envoy to
monitor the treatment of human rights defenders -- a move previously
blocked by Cuba and some developing country allies.
</P>
<P>
   A report presented to the meeting said that human rights
activists suffered repression in some 60 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is shameful that those who seek to promote and to help
protect human rights themselves so often become the victims,''
Robinson said. ''I have been deeply troubled by the fears expressed
to me by some non-governmental representatives. As one woman put to
me: 'Coming here may have made us targets at home,''' the former
Irish president added.
</P>
<P>
   Russia became the first permanent member of the U.N. Security
Council to suffer a formal rebuke. In a 25-7 vote, the commission
criticized Moscow for ''disproportionate and indiscriminate use of
Russian military force, including attacks against civilians'' in
the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, put forward by the EU, urged Moscow to set up a
commission of inquiry and allow in special U.N. investigators.
There were 19 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless the Russian government moves swiftly on these
proposals, the skepticism of the international community and
supporters of human rights inside Russia can only mount,'' said
U.S. delegation leaders Harold Hongju Koh and Nancy Rubin in a
statement after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities -- which snubbed Robinson during a recent
visit to the region -- denounced the U.N. move and said it wouldn't
be bound by its decision. Moscow sent ground troops into Chechnya
in September, following weeks of airstrikes, after Chechnya-based
Islamic militants invaded neighboring Dagestan in August.
</P>
<P>
   For the 10th straight year at the commission, Beijing used its
economic and political muscle among developing countries to block
U.S.-led attempts to censure Chinese repression. Washington's
campaign was also weakened by EU's refusal to co-sponsor the text,
as France in particular was worried about future business deals.
</P>
<P>
   The commission reiterated its annual criticism of violations in
Iran, Iraq, Sudan, Myanmar, Congo and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of Cuba -- also a yearly ritual -- provoked the most
forceful response outside the U.N. debating chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 200,000 demonstrators joined government-sponsored protests
in Cuba against the U.N. vote. The Havana government scrapped a
planned visit by EU leaders to protest Europe's compliance with the
perceived U.S. conspiracy and dropped plans to join an EU aid and
trade pact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
