<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises in European Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar pushed the euro to a new low today
and was higher against most other major currencies in European
trading. Gold prices were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   The euro fell as low as 90.30 cents in early trading in London,
its lowest level since the currency began trading in January 1999.
Its previous low was 90.59 cents set Thursday in New York trading.
</P>
<P>
   The currency of 11 European nations was quoted at 90.84 cents
late in the day in London, down from 91.07 cents here late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates compared with late Thursday included 107.86
Japanese yen, up from 106.26; 1.7245 Swiss francs, down from
1.7250, and 1.4810 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4788. The British
pound was quoted at $1.5570, down from $1.5747.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York, the euro was worth 90.92 cents
and the British pound was quoted at $1.5554. The dollar was quoted
at 108.07 Japanese yen and 1.7212 Swiss francs.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.1519 German marks, up
from 2.1464; 7.2178 French francs, up from 7.2012; 2.4249 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.4193, and 2,130.58 Italian lire, up from
2,125.67.
</P>
<P>
   Gold closed in London at $274.60 per troy ounce, down from
$275.50 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In Zurich the bid was $274.05, down from $275.30.
</P>
<P>
   Gold rose 20 cents in Hong Kong to close at $276.25.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $4.96 per troy ounce, up from $4.93.
</P>
</TEXT>
