<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti Slavery Group Honors Tutu  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- The Rev. Desmond Tutu, who has urged the
United States to come to terms with its history of slavery, has
been honored by a group named for the early anti-slavery movement.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu will be the second recipient of the National Underground
Railroad Freedom Center's human rights award. The first was civil
rights activist Rosa Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, 69, a Nobel laureate and former Anglican archbishop of
Cape Town, South Africa, will be presented the International
Freedom Conductor Award on Aug. 5, Freedom Center officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''As South Africa tore off the burdensome shackles of apartheid,
Desmond Tutu has been in the forefront of efforts to replace evil
with goodness, hypocrisy with truth, violence with peace,'' said
federal Judge Nathaniel Jones, co-chairman of the center's board of
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Tutu won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1984 for his efforts to
dismantle apartheid in South Africa. He is completing a two-year
stay as a visiting professor of theology at Emory University in
Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
