<HEADLINE> China Tries To Stop Antiques Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Mainland Chinese officials said Friday they
were trying to block Christie's and Sotheby's from auctioning off
treasures looted from an imperial palace in Beijing 140 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at China's State Bureau of Cultural Relics said on
condition of anonymity that they had taken measures to stop the
sale of the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   They declined to elaborate while awaiting a reply from the
auction houses.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's spokeswoman Victoria Cheung said Friday that the
auction house was aware of the views of mainland officials, but
declined to say whether Christie's would pull the items from
auction.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Rochell, Sotheby's managing director for China and South
East Asia, said talks were under way and he hoped to reach
agreement before Tuesday's auction.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say if the items would be removed from the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items that British and French troops looted from Yuan
Ming Yuan in 1860, during what has been called the second Opium
War, was a hexagonal ceramic vase featured on the cover of a
Sotheby's catalog for an auction next week, China's state-run
newspaper Economic Daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It was commissioned by the Qing Dynasty emperor Qianlong in
1743, the report said. Yuan Ming Yuan is also known as the Old
Summer Palace.
</P>
<P>
   The two houses' catalogs also include three bronze sculptures
from a water clock that included the heads of the 12 animals of the
Chinese zodiac.
</P>
<P>
   They were also stolen from the palace, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's and Sotheby's plan to auction the pieces, along with
other Chinese ceramics and works of art, in Hong Kong on Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
