<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Permanent Chechnya Force OKd  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Russia said Friday it has formed an army
division for permanent duty in Chechnya, where rebels are still
mounting attacks despite government claims that they are being
defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said the 42nd division was ready
for deployment, the Interfax news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not say how large the division was, but the
military has said about 25,000 Russian troops would be in Chechnya
for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev said stationing the division in Chechnya was the next
step in bringing the eight-month military campaign to an end,
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Russian claims that the rebels are verging on defeat,
the militants are hanging on, staging regular attacks on Russian
posts.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Russia may be in for a drawn-out guerrilla war in
Chechnya. Russian troops, relying on a lopsided advantage in
firepower, swept over the northern lowlands after invading in
September. But rebels have proved difficult to rout from their
hideouts in the southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Federal forces in Chechnya stepped up search and destroy
operations Friday in the south, where rebels are becoming more
active, the military command told Interfax.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rebel scouts and saboteurs in small groups are attacking army
convoys, roadblocks and federal positions, resorting to hit-and-run
tactics,'' the command's press service said.
</P>
<P>
   It said there were eight attacks on Russian positions Thursday
in the Nozhai-Yurt, Vedeno and Shatoi districts in southern and
eastern Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels near Vedeno deep in the mountains fired Grad rockets, an
unusual use of such heavy weaponry, Interfax reported, citing
military officials.
</P>
<P>
   The 9{-foot-long missiles caused no injuries and Interfax cited
an official as saying they apparently had been set off from
makeshift facilities rather than from the mobile launchers used by
Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   ''The efficiency of this technique is nearly zero,'' Interfax
quoted the unidentified official as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The military command said federal troops located and attacked
six rebel bases Thursday. It said 10 rebels were killed and two
were captured. The rest escaped, the command said, according to
Interfax. The casualty figures could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian air force sharply scaled back its bombing of
suspected rebel bases in the Argun and Vedeno gorges Friday, flying
just two missions over the past 24 hours compared to 70 sorties the
day before, press service said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The extremist bases, camps and fortified posts which had been
discovered in the course of the anti-terrorist operation were wiped
out'' in the earlier air raids, the press service said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on the Russian convoys and positions followed a lull
that Russia had said showed the rebels were fragmented and nearing
collapse. Russian President Vladimir Putin on Thursday reiterated
the claim that the rebels were disorganized and losing control.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent ground troops into Chechnya in September, following
weeks of airstrikes, after Chechnya-based Islamic militants invaded
neighboring Dagestan in August. The rebels also are blamed in a
series of apartment bombings in Russia that killed about 300 people
in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1441 </TRAILER>
