<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alchemy Halts Rover Talks With BMW  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE STANLEY, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Rover workers celebrated Friday when a venture
capital firm failed in its bid to acquire the troubled auto group,
but industry analysts warned that any reprieve from drastic layoffs
could be brief.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's BMW, which owns Rover, said it might close down the
money-losing car business altogether if it can't find a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic reversal, Alchemy Partners announced that it had
called off talks aimed at a Rover takeover. Alchemy was believed
close to clinching a buyout, but said differences arose late
Thursday that compelled it to terminate discussions with BMW.
</P>
<P>
   BMW confirmed the two companies broke off negotiations due to
their inability to agree on conditions of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''BMW Group will now pursue alternative routes to bring to an
end its involvement in Rover Car Operations. Those routes include
the sale of Rover Car Operations or its closure,'' the company said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A closure of Rover's flagship Longbridge plant in central
England -- and the resulting loss of at least 8,500 jobs -- would
fulfill employees' worst fears.
</P>
<P>
   ''BMW wants out. That's what it's all about -- to escape the
losses,'' said Garel Rhys, director of the center for automotive
industry research at Cardiff University Business School. ''Even if
getting out means closure, it's either that or the destruction of
BMW itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The German carmaker said the impasse would not affect a plan to
sell its successful Land Rover operations to Ford Motor Co. Ford
has agreed to buy the four-wheel-drive business for $2.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of Alchemy's unspecified bid offers unexpected hope
for a government-backed consortium that was patching together a
rival offer for Rover. The consortium, led by former Rover chief
executive John Towers, was widely seen as having insufficient time
to prepare a viable proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having suggested that it wanted to reach an agreement on
Rover by next week, BMW said Friday that it would postpone making a
decision until as late as the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Chinn, a spokesman for the Longbridge factory, said workers
there were ecstatic to hear of the collapse of Alchemy's takeover
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's absolutely superb news,'' said Longbridge employee Terry
Reilly. ''We have always said Alchemy was bad news for this plant --
they are asset strippers who intended to sell off the best bits and
leave people out of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Alchemy had indicated it would need to lay off several thousand
employees. The Towers consortium has said it would eliminate far
fewer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rhys said that jubilation at Longbridge and at British
companies that supply parts for Rover cars was premature.
</P>
<P>
   The Towers consortium still has only a month to inspect Rover's
accounts, prepare a formal proposal to its financial backers and
secure the funding needed to buy and operate the car business.
</P>
<P>
   ''A month is going to be a pretty tight schedule for all that,''
Rhys said.
</P>
<P>
   Any company or group of investors planning to make an
alternative bid for Rover would be even more hard-pressed to meet
BMW's new deadline for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to see who else is in the picture,'' said Gilly
Filsner, an analyst at the London-based automotive consultancy
Ludvigsen Associates.
</P>
<P>
   BMW decided last month to sell Rover after trying for six years
to restore it to profitability. Its abrupt withdrawal sparked
fierce criticism of the British government for what many people
perceived as its mishandling of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   BMW blamed much of its failure to stem losses at Rover on the
strength of the pound, which makes it more expensive to build cars
in Britain for sale in continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Filsner noted that BMW had proven its ability in the past to
sell cars priced in marks, at a time when the German currency also
was strong.
</P>
<P>
   ''If BMW was incapable of making a go of Rover,'' she asked,
''how can someone without that kind of experience come in and be
successful with a high-volume business?''
</P>
<P>
   The failure of BMW and Alchemy to agree on terms of a sale
leaves the German company in a difficult position.
</P>
<P>
   BMW on Thursday dismissed the Towers consortium's offer as
''financially not secured,'' suggesting the consortium lacked the
funds needed to operate Rover. Now, BMW has no deal for an asset it
wants badly to dump.
</P>
<P>
   Investors punished the company for its failure to strike a deal
with Alchemy, driving BMW's share price down 2.3 percent from
Thursday to $26.85 at the close of trading in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   With investors demanding action and no viable buyer yet in
sight, BMW may find itself forced to close Rover's passenger car
business to shore up its share price and protect itself from an
unwanted takeover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1455 </TRAILER>
