<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Friday, April 28, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Breakup Plan To Be Filed
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The proposals of the Justice Department and 19
states for punishing Microsoft for breaking the antitrust laws will
be submitted to a federal judge after the market closes today. All
the parties reportedly propose that the software giant be split
into two competing companies forbidden to reunite for at least 10
years. U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson after ruled
April 3 that Microsoft repeatedly broke federal antitrust laws
intended to maintain fair competition by using its monopoly power
in computer operating systems to crush rivals. Microsoft stock was
down 11/16 at 69 in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   EU Opens Nintendo Price-Fix Probe
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Commission today opened an
investigation into possible price-fixing by Nintendo and seven
video game distributors. The Commission has been looking into
whether these companies divided up the market for Nintendo video
game systems like the ''NES'' model and the portable ''Game Boy''
in order to keep prices artificially high. ''The Commission
believes that the companies concerned participated in a cartel-like
arrangement with the aim of partitioning the European single
market,'' the agency said in a statement. Officials in Nintendo's
offices in the Netherlands and Germany were unavailable for comment
late today.
</P>
<P>
   Personal Income Rises 0.7 Percent
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' incomes, spending and savings were
all up in March, the Commerce Department said today. Personal
income -- wages, interest and government benefits -- rose 0.7
percent, a bit more than expected. Spending was up 0.5 percent. And
the savings rate -- savings as a percentage of after-tax income --
rose to 0.4 percent from a record low of 0.2 percent the month
before. March was the first month since last October that income
had grown faster than spending.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Drops 130; Nasdaq Up 96
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with semiconductor
shares leading a surge in the technology sector. ''I think that
aggressive investors think that the selloff has hit the bottom with
technology stocks, and it is safe to stick your toe back in the
water,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist at Edward
Jones of St. Louis. But gains in high-tech stocks couldn't prop up
the broader market, which again faced interest-rate concerns. Just
before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were down 130.92 at
10,757.18. On the NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,500-1,349. The
Nasdaq was up 96.37 at 3,870.40.
</P>
