<P>
   Buffett To Take Blame at Meeting
</P>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Billionaire Warren Buffett will be able to
tell shareholders in person this weekend what he already has said
in print -- his company had its worst year ever and he blames
himself for the performance. This weekend's annual meeting is
expected to attract 12,000 investors and followers of Buffett, one
of the world's richest men, who has made the gatherings a
circus-like event. Berkshire's earnings dropped 42 percent in 1999,
to $1.6 billion from $2.8 billion the year before. Berkshire's
stock, the most expensive on the New York Stock Exchange, fell 20
percent last year. At the same time, the stock market soared.
Berkshire Hathaway's Class A stock was up $500 at $59,900 a share
this afternoon on the New York Stock Exchange, but almost 24
percent below the 52-week high of $78,600.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Pilots To Get On-Board Meals
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines plans to make meals available to
pilots on flights where food is served. The carrier says the
program, which it is starting voluntarily, will cost $3 million to
$5 million annually. Delta's pilots have no contractual provision
for in-flight meals. They get money to buy food at airports to
bring aboard, but long lines and quick connections often make that
impossible. On international flights, the pilots typically eat
airline food. But on domestic flights, extra meals are first
offered to flight attendants -- leaving many pilots hungry on long
trips.
</P>
<P>
   TWA To End U.S. Getaway Packages
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Financially struggling Trans World Airlines
plans to change the way it sells vacation packages to leisure
travelers. TWA said today that effective May 31 it will suspend
sales of its Getaway vacation packages in the United States. It
will continue to sell packages through other channels, including
its European Getaway operation and an enhanced Web site the airline
plans to begin this summer. TWA lost $76.1 million in the first
quarter and $353.4 million last year. The airline has not had an
annual profit since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Artisoft Selling Network Unit
</P>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Software maker Artisoft Inc. has agreed to
sell its network software unit to a French company, the company's
chairman and acting CEO said. Michael Downey said yesterday the
deal with Prologue Software Group should be completed in the next
few weeks but declined to discuss details of the cash purchase.
Prologue is a subsidiary of Compagnie des Machines Bull, a
Louvecinnes, France-based data processing, office automation and
telephone technology company that reported revenue of $4.1 billion
last year. Artisoft, which moved its headquarters to Cambridge,
Mass., last year, also said yesterday it lost $3.5 million or 23
cents per diluted share in its fiscal 2000 third quarter ended
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ABC TV Names Callahan President
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Robert F. Callahan, ABC's president of
broadcasting since February 1999, has been placed in charge of the
ABC Television Network. Callahan, who had led Walt Disney Co.'s
radio and television stations division, was appointed yesterday as
president of the newly named ABC Broadcast Group. He is now in
charge of the network's news, entertainment, daytime and late-night
divisions as well as its affiliate relations and sales and
marketing units. He will still oversee Disney's radio and
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless Down a Fraction
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of the new AT&AMP;T Wireless Group were up [
at 31 13/16 this afternoon after its strong debut yesterday. Its
first day's performance provided further encouragement for jittery
investors, though not quite distracting them from their
preoccupation with inflation and interest rates. A day after AT&AMP;T
pulled off the biggest initial public offering in U.S. history in a
market with sudden disdain for IPOs, investors wasted no time in
embracing the wireless ''tracking'' stock as it hit the open
market.
</P>
<P>
   Alchemy Calls Off Talks With BMW
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The venture capital firm that was expected to
acquire the troubled Rover automaking group from Germany's BMW has
called off the deal, and BMW warned today that it might close Rover
if it cannot find a buyer. Alchemy Partners, which was believed
close to clinching a buyout of Rover's money-losing car business,
said differences arose late yesterday that compelled it to
terminate discussions with BMW. BMW confirmed that the two
companies have broken off negotiations, due to their inability to
agree on certain unspecified conditions of the sale.
</P>
