<HEADLINE> Arrest Made in Berlin Wall Shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- A former East German secret police colonel wanted
in Germany for the deaths of four people killed trying to flee over
the Berlin Wall has been arrested on the Spanish island of Gran
Canaria, Berlin police said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Walter Schulze, 52, had been charged with four
counts of manslaughter in shootings at the wall between November
1985 and 1989, including the last person killed there during a Feb.
5, 1989, flight attempt.
</P>
<P>
   A police statement said that Schulze had turned to running
brothels after the fall of East Germany and that he had contact
with the underworld.
</P>
<P>
   He was to appear at his court trial in October 1988, but
disappeared with his Latvian-born wife in the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Police issued an international arrest warrant in February and
after a three-month search a special Spanish police group arrested
him Thursday in Gran Canaria, one of the Canary Islands, a police
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   A request for his extradition was being prepared, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
