<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 116; Nasdaq Up 91  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology shares
rising for the second straight day while blue-chip stocks came
under selling pressure amid concerns over rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was up 91.96 at 3,865.99. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 116.34 at 10,771.76.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 8.37 at 1,456.55.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in technology stocks was led by a rally in
semiconductor shares. Intel gained 2 11/16 to 128, Applied
Materials rose 2 15/16 to 103 1/4 and PMC-Sierra jumped 13 9/16 to
196 3/16, all on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that aggressive investors think that the selloff has
hit the bottom with technology stocks, and it is safe to stick your
toe back in the water,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief market
strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But the gains in the high-tech sector couldn't prop up the
broader market, which was weighed down by fears of rising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that Americans' incomes rose
last month even faster than spending, something that hasn't
happened since October.
</P>
<P>
   But although people made more money, they didn't put
significantly more away in savings. The report showed that the
personal savings rate -- savings as a percentage of after-tax income
-- rose only slightly to 0.4 percent in March from a record low of
0.2 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   That provided another sign that the economy continues to grow at
a brisk pace, which the Federal Reserve will likely consider at its
policy-making meeting on May 16. Most economists expect the Fed to
raise interest rates for the sixth time since June as they attempt
to keep inflationary pressures under control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market has a governor on it right now ... it's called the
Fed meeting next month,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of
market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ''Until
that meeting, there will be a lid on the upside of this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Fears of higher interest rates pushed financial services stocks
down. American Express dropped 3 to 152 and J.P. Morgan was off 3
at 128 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Merck was off 3 1/16 to 68 7/16 after financial news station
CNBC reported that the company may face safety questions from the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration about its painkiller Vioxx.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based music service MP3.com tainted the technology
sector, falling 39 percent after a judge found the company liable
for infringing the copyrights of the Recording Industry Association
of America. MP3's products make it possible to download music over
the Internet. Shares fell 4{ to 7[.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 738.90 million
shares, down from 896.28 million shares on Thursday. On the Nasdaq,
advancers were ahead by an 11-to-8 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 10.05 at 504.63.
</P>
<P>
   ------
