<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vargas Llosa Defends Trujillo Book  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Mario Vargas Llosa
spent months researching his new novel about the late Dominican
dictator Rafael Trujillo -- and found, 39 years after Trujillo's
death, a society still haunted by his long dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Vargas Llosa has been in Santo Domingo both promoting
and defending his new novel, ''La Fiesta del Chivo'' (''The Goat's
Party''). He says the book, a work of historical fiction,
represents the ''human truth'' of the dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a version that many Dominicans, still struggling to
solidify their democracy, aren't comfortable with. The book has
left many in this Caribbean nation of 8 million feeling a little
exposed, a little embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo governed the Dominican Republic from 1930 until 1961,
when he was assassinated by a few conspirators. In that era, many
Dominicans acquiesced to the dictatorship in order to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ''The iron curtain that we have covered ourselves with for
decades has been broken,'' said Carlos Francisco Elias, a literary
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo's legacy was a series of authoritarian administrations,
fraudulent elections and a culture that reveres strongmen --
including Joaquin Balaguer, a Trujillo aide who led the country on
and off and at 93 is running again for president in May elections.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting here for the first time since the book was published,
Vargas Llosa told a crowd of more than 800 that everything in the
novel either ''happened or could have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peruvian author said it pained him to learn that the family
of Antonio de la Maza, one of the men who assassinated Trujillo,
was unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I have admiration for any of the characters that figure in
the novel, it is for the seven men who waited for Trujillo on the
highway to San Cristobal and killed him there,'' Vargas Llosa said.
</P>
<P>
   De la Maza's relatives bought an advertisement in the newspaper
Hoy saying the novel would confuse younger generations who didn't
live through ''the system that asphyxiated us.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the conspirators have died.
</P>
<P>
   Historian and former U.S. Ambassador Bernardo Vega noted that
none of the assassins' families came to hear Vargas Llosa speak.
''The families are not happy with the book because he treats them
as humans who get drunk and cheat on their wives and have human
weaknesses, rather than as the heroes we read about in history
books,'' Vega said.
</P>
<P>
   In classic Vargas Llosa style, ''The Goat's Party'' moves back
and forth in time and place.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with the fictionalized memories of a woman whose
father had fallen out of favor with the regime and who offered her
to Trujillo to satisfy Trujillo's rumored passion for young girls.
</P>
<P>
   Her memories are superimposed on the story of the dictator's
assassins and Trujillo's final days. Scenes of the torture those
men suffered in prison afterward are mixed with a portrait of the
woman, Urania Cabral, visiting her father for the first time since
her encounter in Trujillo's bedroom 35 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas Llosa also devotes a good bit of the book to Balaguer,
describing how he managed to stay in power after Trujillo died. The
author said he portrayed Balaguer -- himself a prolific author -- as
cold and calculating because he came across that way in interviews
and in ''a good part of his works.''
</P>
<P>
   Releasing his own book Friday, a work of history called ''The
English Race,'' Balaguer praised Vargas Llosa's work as ''a good
novel ... (delivered) with great ease of style and a lot of
imagination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1521 </TRAILER>
