<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Assures Burundi's Army  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- Confident that Burundi's seven-year
civil war is near an end, former South African President Nelson
Mandela on Friday assured the Tutsi-led army that no peace
settlement would be possible without its support.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's first, whirlwind trip was meant to convince the army --
the real force in the tiny central African nation -- that their
concerns would be taken into account during peace negotiations in
Arusha, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, in their 20th month, ultimately should yield a
power-sharing agreement that would allow for the integration of
Hutu rebels into the army.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am confident that we are on the verge of a breakthrough,''
Mandela said before leaving the heavily-guarded capital, Bujumbura.
But ''if the army and the National Assembly are not with us, we
cannot bring peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The peace mediator brought along former Nigerian President Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar to explain to the officers how a series of
coups had ruined his own West African nation. Abubakar assumed
power in Nigeria in 1998 -- after dictator Gen. Sani Abacha died of
a heart attack -- and paved the way for multiparty elections that
were won by another former military leader, Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi's Hutu rebels have been battling the army since 1993 in
a fight that has left more than 200,000 people dead. Most
Burundians blame politicians and officers who refuse to relinquish
their tight grip on power to restore calm.
</P>
<P>
   ''I indicated that the defense force of Burundi is far ahead of
the thinking of the politicians,'' Mandela told reporters. ''They
support negotiations without reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela said he had listened to questions and concerns from the
High Army Council, although he said he did not agree with the men
on every point.
</P>
<P>
   One disagreement touched on integrating majority Hutus into the
army, Mandela said, and he warned against ''unilateral
integration'' outside the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it had already recruited and trained Hutu
soldiers and officers, and that Mandela's proposal for an ethnic
quota had largely been met.
</P>
<P>
   But the rebels have argued that only fighters from their ranks --
not just any Hutus -- should be eligible for integration.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to 121 legislators at the National Assembly, Mandela
promised to mobilize funds from international donors to develop
industry in Burundi and eradicate poverty, but only after peace
takes hold.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela briefly visited the Military Academy, where he promised
midlevel officers he would give them, and not their commanders,
priority during his next visit.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the same military facility in October 1993 that Tutsi
paratroopers assassinated Melchior Ndadaye, Burundi's first
democratically elected president and a Hutu, prompting Hutu
politicians to drum up support for the Hutu rebellion that has
engulfed the country in violence.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, the message was different. As Mandela walked onto
the academy's stage, a band struck up Bob Marley's anti-war song
called ''War'' to the rousing applause of the military men in the
hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
