<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Films Preserved for History Featured  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Great and small 20th century movies rescued
from destruction will be shown starting Saturday at the National
Gallery of Art as part of a preservation project to save ''orphan''
films.
</P>
<P>
   The offerings range from a one-minute ''Blacksmithing Scene''
made in 1893, the first film shown commercially in the United
States, to an 83-minute 1924 feature shot wholly in Alaska, ''The
Chechahcos.'' From World War II, there's a 10-minute
''Autobiography of a Jeep'' and a cartoon warning soldiers against
spies, with comic rhymes by noted children's author Dr. Seuss.
</P>
<P>
   ''Films made by the old nitrate process can't even be shown any
more-- it's against the fire laws,'' said Roger L. Mayer, chairman
of the National Film Preservation Foundation. ''After a while, they
just turn into jelly if they aren't transferred to safety film.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half the films made before 1951 have been lost, David
J. Francis told a preview audience at the National Gallery. He is
in charge of the world's largest collection of films at the Library
of Congress. The gallery will show 17 of them.
</P>
<P>
   James H. Billington, the Librarian of Congress, said Congress
recognized the importance of preserving old film in 1988 but did
not provide money to do it. One result, he explained, was the
foundation -- a public-private partnership which can collect
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation organized a White House Millennium Project called
''Treasures from American Archives'' that put together films and
collections of footage that go back as far as 1893. They provide a
panorama of the 20th century, the first to be recorded on camera
from its start.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Bill Ivey of the government's National Endowment for
the Arts said his agency had contributed $500,000 to the $1.5
million project and over the past 35 years had spent nearly $20
million on film preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer said the University of California at Los Angeles has
millions of feet of old newsreels, invaluable to historians, which
could decay unless money becomes available to save them. Now, he
said, big studios have come to see that old hits have commercial
value and every year are spending $5 million to $10 million a year
on preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't have to worry about 'Citizen Kane' or 'Gone with the
Wind' any more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to show that old films have commercial value even when
they were not hits, because of the vast appetite for material for
TV, the Internet and home videos. The ''Treasures'' project is
transferring 50 of them to a set of digital video disks (DVD's),
which can be used to show 10 1/2 hours of film. He said they will
be distributed free to libraries starting in September and sold to
the public for less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Performances at the National Gallery start at 2 p.m. Saturday
with ''The Chechahcos'' and a 1908 special-effects comedy called
''The Thieving Hand.'' It will be followed by a sample of short
films from the project on May 6, and performances of other old
films May 7, 13, 14, 20, 21, 27 and 28.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
