<HEADLINE> Stage Set for GOP Protests  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Protesters have agreed to drop their
free-speech lawsuit against the city and the stage has been set for
a week of noisy demonstrations at this summer's Republican national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Unity 2000 and city officials reached an agreement this week to
allow the group to use one of the downtown area's most heavily
traveled thoroughfares for a large rally on the eve of the July 31
to Aug. 3 convention, said city Solicitor Kenneth Trujillo.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 local and national activist groups, promoting
dozens of ''progressive'' causes, plan to attend the July 30 rally
on the Benjamin Franklin Parkway, which connects City Hall to the
Philadelphia Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Unity 2000 and a group organizing a smaller rally filed a
federal lawsuit earlier this month after the city refused to issue
a permit. The suit accused the city of trampling on the protesters'
free-speech rights by giving the Republicans first dibs on prime
public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're happy that the process is over,'' Unity 2000 leader
Michael Morrill said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement hinges on the approval of Philadelphia 2000, the
host committee that controls the sites for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement required both sides to give ground. The
protesters agreed to scale back the event from nine to seven hours
and abandoned plans to march on Market Street and around City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the city agreed to provide a stage and sound system,
portable toilets, medical services and security at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.unity2000.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.2000gop.com/convention
</P>
</TEXT>
