<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Riot Kills 26 in Colombia  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Rioting that broke out after an inmate's
mutilated body was found stuffed in a prison sewer pipe led to 26
deaths before the unrest ended Friday, the worst bloodletting in
Colombia's violent prison system.
</P>
<P>
   The melee between paramilitary fighters and common criminals at
Bogota's El Modelo federal prison marked the swift collapse of a
much-touted nonviolence pact signed by inmates at the crumbling
facility just two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Romulo Gonzalez, whose job includes prison
oversight, labeled the latest killings the product of ''40 years of
government neglect'' of Colombia's corrupt, anarchic and
overcrowded jails.
</P>
<P>
   The rioting broke out Thursday after guards found the body of a
missing inmate -- said to be a jailed paramilitary member -- chopped
to pieces in a garbage bag inside a sewer pipe, police operations
director Gen. Alfonso Arellano said.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery led to retaliation killings that tapered off early
Friday between jailed rightist militia members and inmates in
another cellblock housing convicted murderers, armed robbers and
kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   Gun bursts and loud explosions were heard throughout the night
as officials mulled their options and inmates' families flocked to
the prison in search of news.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of anxious mothers, wives and girlfriends pressed at
riot police barricades outside the jail Friday morning as officials
were slow to release the names of the dead and 18 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had considered a police raid during the melee but
ultimately negotiated with gang leaders to lay down their weapons,
Gen. Arellano said. The inmates held hostages and had cut
electricity inside the jail, making a pitch-dark assault risky.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dead were shot in the head at close range, Arellano
added. Officials confiscated guns, grenades and caches of
ammunition, and transferred 42 inmates to other facilities.
</P>
<P>
   El Modelo, housing 5,000 inmates in quarters meant for only
1,800, was the site of a rare ''peace pact'' signed Feb. 29 between
rival factions, including militia fighters, jailed rebels and
common criminals.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony attended by top officials, the gangs then turned
over weapons and pledged a six-month reprieve in the jail's almost
daily violence.
</P>
<P>
   Gangleaders expressed hope that their pact, which followed a
December clash that left 12 inmates dead, would be an inspiration
to current peace talks to end Colombia's nearly 36-year civil
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But prisons director Fabio Campos acknowledged Friday that the
groups had only turned over a few of their arms, and that underpaid
guards continue to allow escapes and easy access to weapons in
return for bribes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Naturally, there's corruption,'' Campos, a retired police
general and the eighth person to hold his post in just two years,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Campos pledged a weapons search and a crackdown on corrupt
guards at El Modelo but admitted there were no easy short-term
answers to a prison crisis in which nearly 500 inmates have been
killed since 1997 and more than twice that number have escaped.
</P>
<P>
   A major U.S. drug suspect wanted in the United States escaped
from Bogota's other federal prison, La Picota, in March after
allegedly bribing guards to smuggle him out in an old mattress.
</P>
<P>
   Campos said the government expected to build four new,
state-of-the-art federal prisons in addition to one opening in
June, and had plans to hire more guards and raise their salaries,
he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
