<HEADLINE> Pink Plastic Flamingos Elicit Fine  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) -- When Doug Henry bought a pair of pink
flamingos at an antique market for $15, he thought he'd found a
real bargain and great yard art.
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors in the Towne Park subdivision didn't agree. Now
that bargain could end up costing Henry thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the subdivision's homeowners association began fining
Henry $25 a day for violating its rules prohibiting unapproved lawn
decorations. By the time Henry and his wife, Ellen, sold their
house, the fine had reached $3,400.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a lot of money for two little flamingos,'' said Ellen
Henry.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said they didn't learn about the fine until last
month, when the association placed a lien on their house and
attorneys handling the sale withheld $3,400 in escrow. If someone
had just asked, the couple would have moved the plastic birds, Doug
Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners association spokesman George Nowack said the group
sent the couple two certified letters explaining the fine, but both
came back as undeliverable.
</P>
<P>
   Now if the two sides don't reach a settlement, a judge might
have to decide who gets the $3,400 in escrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
