<DOCNO> APW20000428.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New owners say Vernon Downs is harness racing's greatest hope  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VERNON, N.Y. (AP) -- A new paint job. A new owner. A new lease on
life. Officials at Vernon Downs are looking ahead with optimism
that they can resurrect the once-proud harness track.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered racing track opened its 2000 season Friday
night. Racing fans will see state-of-the-art improvements and a
more fan friendly schedule as Vernon Downs attempts to rebound
after losing more than $3 million over the last four years, said
John Signorelli, who put together a local investment to purchase
controlling interest of the track in September.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've spent close to a million dollars to give this place a
new facelift. Now we wait to see if our work resonates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''For us to grow into what we want, we'll need this summer to be
successful,'' said Signorelli.
</P>
<P>
   The track begins its 104-date schedule in the midst of a
renovation project some would say goes against logic, considering
the health of New York's harness racing industry, which has been in
steady decline since the state-run off-track betting system was
initiated in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   A new 7/8-mile track is under construction, the jewel in a
$750,000 face-lift that also features improved corporate luxury
boxes, dining facilities and a more user-friendly simulcasting
area.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first phase of a vision Signorelli has for the 300
acres the track sits on in a scenic valley in the heart of Oneida
County farm country, about 30 miles east of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Signorelli also would like to develop a possible equine park to
train young horses, build a dude ranch with horse riding trails,
add an RV park and an amphitheater as well as a show-horse
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Special events such as professional wrestling, rock concerts, a
jazz festival and an AMA Grand National Dirt Track Championship
have been scheduled at the Downs during this season. Attracting
younger crowds is also part of Signorelli's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The blend of events works for creating long-term customers,''
Signorelli said. ''You can't create harness racing fans overnight,
but if you get them out here for the special events, maybe they'll
return for a night of harness racing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a vision, a plan,'' Signorelli said. ''Whether it will
work or not, only God knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Signorelli knows, though, that harness racing remains the key to
the equation. His vision will die unless he can develop a solid
following to a track that attracted an average of at least 3,000
fans a night from its 1953 opening through 1981, but hasn't
averaged 2,000 since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The financially ailing track was perilously close to shutting
down before Signorelli's group came to the rescue. Last year, the
average attendance (1,334) and on-track handle ($103,280) were the
lowest ever.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for confidence beyond the cosmetic, Signorelli
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took over in September, Signorelli has reached an
unprecedented two-year agreement with Vernon's horsemen that
replaces traditional revenue percentages with guaranteed purses and
corporate profit-sharing. And, already there have been 785 request
for stalls, up from 450 last season, evidence that the horsemen
believe a turnaround is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the season, which started in March last year and featured
many fan-unfriendly midweek dates, has been moved back a month and
will focus on weekends. That should help attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no doubt we're trying to buck a statewide trend
here,'' Signorelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is New York's greatest hope for a harness racing
renaissance,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
