<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Examines Gambling Impact  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A central question in the national debate over
legalized gambling -- whether its economic benefits outweigh its
social costs -- cannot be answered with information currently
available, according to a federal study released this week.
</P>
<P>
   Using Atlantic City, N.J., as its case study, the General
Accounting Office found ample statistics on jobs created and taxes
paid by the casino industry but little definitive information on
the downside of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ''While data on family problems, crime and suicide are
available, tracking systems generally do not collect data on the
causes of these incidents, so they cannot be linked to gambling,''
reported the GAO, the investigatory arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO did the study at the request of Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va.,
a gambling opponent.
</P>
<P>
   To a large degree, it follows the path previously covered by the
National Gambling Impact Study Commission, which released a report
last year after two years of work.
</P>
<P>
   Like the commission, the GAO found anecdotal reports linking
compulsive gambling with domestic violence, child abuse and
divorce, but no way to establish or measure the connection.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO wrote: ''We found no conclusive evidence on whether or
not gambling caused increased social problems in Atlantic City.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO visited and spoke to officials in Atlantic City,
Atlantic County and New Jersey's capital, Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   It reported that domestic violence incidents, child abuse,
divorce, single-parent families and suicide ''increased in some of
the years after casinos began operating and decreased in other
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter appended to the GAO report, New Jersey Casino
Control Commission Chairman James Hurley wrote, ''We clearly
believe that the positive impacts that casinos have generated far
outweigh the perceived negative impacts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay James, who chaired the national commission on gambling,
wrote that the GAO study should ''serve as a further reminder that
additional research must be undertaken at the federal, state and
local level'' to gauge the social costs of legalized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO is working on a separate study, also requested by Wolf,
focusing on the economic and social effects of so-called
''convenience gambling,'' such as slot machines and video poker
terminals located in neighborhood bars or stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
