<HEADLINE> Elian Senate Hearings Postponed  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate Judiciary Committee said Friday it
was postponing a hearing scheduled for Wednesday to examine the
legal implications of the federal raid on the Miami home of Elian
Gonzalez's relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was put off to an undetermined date after the
Justice Department informed the committee it could not meet a
Friday deadline to supply all documents related to the surveillance
of the home, the possibility of weapons in the home, the obtaining
of search warrants and the conduct of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ''About 5 p.m. Thursday, we received an extensive document
request from the committee asking for documents by Friday,''
Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said. ''We began working
as hard as we can to compile all the documents sought by the
committee. Many of them are located in Miami and other outlying
offices, and we will continue to work with the committee to get
them what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thursday letter from Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of
the Judiciary Committee, to Attorney General Janet Reno gave the
department 24 hours to turn over all documents ''related to (1)
surveillance of the Miami home, including but not limited to the
possibility of weapons in that home; (2) seeking and obtaining the
search warrant and the arrest warrant; (3) the decision to enter
the home and the means of entry, and (4) the conduct of the
operation of entering the home, seizing the boy, and taking him to
Maryland, including but not limited to any tactical plan or rules
of engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats have generally been critical of the
proposed hearing, characterizing it as the latest GOP attack on
Reno's Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''The courts are the proper forum within which to look at all
these matters, not the Congress. I think it's politicized, I think
it's wrong and I think it could be very damaging,'' Senate
Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This can serve as the first step of a graceful exit strategy
for hearings that were a mistake in the first place,'' said Sen.
Patrick Leahy of Vermont, Judiciary's top Democrat. ''The American
public resents investigations that are increasingly political and
one-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department seized Elian April 22 and reunited him
with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez. The pair, along with Elian's
stepmother, Nersy, and his baby half brother, Hianny, are staying a
secluded retreat on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs taken Thursday show Elian playing baseball with his
father, romping with a dog and smiling with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans, meanwhile, kept up their criticism of
the operation to wrest Elian from his Miami relatives and return
him to his father. House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, accused
the administration of ''character assassination designed to
discredit'' Elian's Miami family.
</P>
<P>
   ''As it turns out, Elian was in no danger with his Miami family
until the Justice Department entered their home with guns drawn,''
said DeLay, who has referred to the federal agents conducting the
operation as ''jackbooted thugs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
