<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Trophy Art To Be Returned  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW KRAMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Art pieces looted from Germany and Russia --
including parts of Peter the Great's famed Amber Room -- are
returning home in a historic swap, although hundreds of thousands
of other items still await repatriation.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange ends half a century of obscurity for the artworks
and opens them to public viewing. But they are only a fraction of
the vast cultural booty both Russia and Germany scooped up during
and after World War II, and the dispute over so-called ''trophy
art'' continues to weigh on the countries' otherwise warm
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Culture Minister Mikhail Shvydkoi said Friday that the
exchange meant that ''for the first time ever, works of art that
were illegally taken away from Russia, are being given back,'' the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   However, talks have not resolved ownership disputes for most of
the more than 1 million cultural valuables Germany claims Soviets
troops took -- paintings, rare books, coins and other items such as
church windows. Russia in turn raises the issue of compensation for
an estimated several hundred thousand items destroyed or lost
during Nazi occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides pillaged, but since Germany lost it was forced to
surrender its loot to the victors.
</P>
<P>
   Long only rumored to exist, the Soviet Union's vast cache of
looted masterpieces was confirmed by Russia only in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The artworks lay for decades in secret repositories at Soviet
museums while the government denied any knowledge of them.
</P>
<P>
   The works include pieces by Van Gogh, Degas, Renoir, El Greco,
Goya, Manet, Daumier, Veronese, Tintoretto, Cranach and more.
Complicating ownership claims, some items were looted twice, first
by the Nazis from occupied countries and then by the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most controversial items is the Trojan gold excavated
in Turkey in 1873 by German archaeologist Heinrich Schliemann, who
believed that it once belonged to the king of the ancient city of
Troy. The items are on display at Moscow's Pushkin museum.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian law bans repatriating looted art in most cases as
Russians see the treasures as compensation for lost and destroyed
cultural treasures. The Amber Room tops Russia's list of
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The room's walls were plated in 1,300 square feet of resplendent
amber mosaics, placed by mirrors and windows to glow a rich
golden-brown color. The room was a gift to Peter the Great from
Frederick William I of Prussia in 1716.
</P>
<P>
   Retreating Nazi troops hastily stripped the chamber in 1945 and
only fragments have been found.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Germany will formally hand over a mosaic called
''Sense of Smell and Touch'' depicting a scene of women frolicking
by a pool. The mosaic, along with a delicately-inlayed chest
formerly used by Russia's czars that will also be returned, were
discovered in private collections in 1997 in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Cultural Minister Michael Naumann was to present the
items to Russian President Vladimir Putin at the Amber Room's
original location in the Catherine Palace outside St. Petersburg on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bremen's Kunsthalle museum in turn received drawings and
watercolors by Henri Toulouse-Lautrec, Francisco Goya and dozens of
German artists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1624 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000428.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Dead in Suburban Pa. Shootings  </HEADLINE>
By TODD SPANGLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   McKEES ROCKS,PA. (AP) -- Three people were killed and at least
one wounded Friday in shootings at two suburban Pittsburgh shopping
centers and in two nearby communities. A suspect was in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Two people were shot to death at a Chinese restaurant at the
Plaza at Robinson Town Centre in McKees Rocks. A third person was
shot and killed at a martial arts school in a Monaca shopping plaza
about 18 miles northwest of McKees Rocks, said a Beaver County
dispatcher who would not give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Township police in nearby Carnegie said a third person was
wounded at an undisclosed location there. Gunfire was also reported
in Mount Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Vinh Truong, a cook at the Ya Fei Chinese Cuisine restaurant in
McKees Rocks, said his brother-in-law was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Truong was in the kitchen when an employee ran from the front of
the restaurant, telling everyone to escape. Instead, he left the
kitchen and saw his brother-in-law on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see my brother Tony on the floor,'' said Truong, who did not
give the man's full name. ''I tell everybody 'Somebody shot
Tony.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Beaver County dispatcher said a suspect was arrested in
Ambridge, about 6 miles southeast of Monaca and 16 miles northwest
of Pittsburgh. No further details of the shootings or arrest were
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ross, a spokeswoman at Mercy Hospital in Pittsburgh, said
a 25-year-old man injured in Carnegie was in critical condition,
wounded in the upper back and neck.
</P>
</TEXT>
