<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Englewood couple sues to tear down mansion, build some affordablehousing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ENGLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) -- John and Laura Blackman live in a
turn-of-the-century, Mediterranean-style mansion with 11 bathrooms
and five fireplaces. And they're suing the city so they can tear it
down.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackmans, who have been trying to sell the mansion for a
year at a $5.2 million asking price, now want to convert the
4.7-acre estate into luxury town houses, with about 12 priced as
affordable housing, their lawyer says.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawsuit alleges that the city doesn't have enough
affordable housing to go around, a claim dismissed by officials as
an attempt to blackmail it into letting the couple divide their
land.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears as if this is an attempt at increasing the sales
price of their property,'' Englewood City Attorney William Rupp
told The Record of Hackensack in Friday's editions. ''There is no
intent here to philosophically provide low- and moderate-income
housing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blackmans have not filed an application to the city Planning
Board or Board of Adjustment yet for a development, but their
attorney, David Watkins, says the pair want to build 48 town
houses, each valued at $750,000 to $1 million. Twelve of the homes
would be sold for an average price of $89,920.
</P>
<P>
   If that plan fails, the Blackmans want to build 120 apartments,
with 18 at affordable prices, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said the couple turned to the courts last year to avoid
local boards that often put up roadblocks to such developments, and
to increase the value of their property.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're entitled to it based upon the fact that Englewood
never complied with the Fair Housing Act,'' Watkins said. ''It
forces the city of Englewood to come into the requirements of the
20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blackmans are entitled to sue over a shortage of fair
housing based on the Mount Laurel guidelines set by New Jersey
Supreme Court decisions in 1975 and 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings require every municipality in the state to provide a
fair share of low and moderately priced homes, and allows residents
to sue municipalities that don't offer their required share of
units.
</P>
<P>
   Englewood should have 223 low- or moderate-income homes,
according to the guidelines, and all the homes must have been built
since 1980. Englewood has 1,365 affordable housing units, 261 of
which have been built in the past decade, City Manager Robert
Benecke said. The city received an award last year from the U.S.
Housing and Urban Development agency for its efforts to provide
fair housing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents aren't happy about the Blackmans' plans, saying a
zoning change would ruin the neighborhood's character.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a case of extreme greed,'' said Eugenia Vogel,
co-president of the Englewood Homeowners Association. ''They want
to make a bundle of money by destroying our zoning laws. If this
subdivision is granted or any other subdivision is granted, anybody
who has an acre will build town houses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 1646 </TRAILER>
