<HEADLINE> ReliaStar Mulling Possible Takeover  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- ReliaStar Financial Corp., the country's
eighth-largest publicly held life insurance holding company,
confirmed Friday it is in talks to be acquired.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Minneapolis-based company refused to release
any details about the talks ''until a definitive agreement is
reached or the negotiations are terminated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones news service, citing unnamed people familiar with
the talks, reported that Dutch financial giant ING Group NV is
close to a deal to acquire ReliaStar in a deal that could be worth
as much as $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ReliaStar, which had revenues of $3 billion in 1999, has been
mentioned as a potential takeover target by several possible
suitors, including General Motors Corp. and Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The company's subsidiaries offer life insurance and annuities,
employee benefits products and services, retirement plans, life and
health reinsurance, mutual funds, and bank and trust products. It
has $38.4 billion in assets under management.
</P>
