<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Photographer Held for 3d Night  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Associated Press photographer Obed Zilwa
was detained for a third straight night Friday, even though his
lawyer said police admitted they had no evidence to link him to any
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Police had earlier said Zilwa was being held in connection with
the bombing of Zimbabwe's only independent daily. Zilwa has
repeatedly protested his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   International press organizations on Friday demanded Zilwa's
immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   The chief investigating officer had recommended earlier Friday
that Zilwa be released for lack of evidence, said Zilwa's attorney,
Jonathan Samkange.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Assistant Commissioner Emmanuel Chimwanda said he agreed
with the recommendation and would seek the authority to free Zilwa,
Samkange said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning from a meeting with his superiors, Chimwanda said
Zilwa would continue to be detained, and police investigators and
officials would meet in the morning to decide whether to charge him
in court Saturday or to release him, Samkange said.
</P>
<P>
   Chimwanda acknowledged that the continued detention was illegal
because Zilwa had been neither charged nor released within 48 hours
of his arrest, Samkange said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would have been different if they said, 'Your guy has
committed an offense, and we've got evidence against him,''
Samkange said. ''Now they've said, 'We don't have evidence against
him. He's innocent, but we don't have the power to release him.''
</P>
<P>
   Samkange said it was now up to South Africa's ambassador to push
for Zilwa's release.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a political decision now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The South African Embassy said the its government was protesting
the illegal detention at the highest levels.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said
journalists, as anyone, should be given due process.
</P>
<P>
   ''We obviously believe that reporters and photographers should
be allowed to do their job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Zilwa on Wednesday as he waited in the Harare
airport for his flight back to South Africa. He had been covering
the political violence in Zimbabwe for the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Zilwa, a South African citizen based in Cape
Town, matched a witness description of a person involved in a bomb
attack on The Daily News. No one was injured in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa was refusing to eat and sleep, Samkange said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am innocent, the police have told me I'm innocent, and I
should not be here at all,'' Samkange said Zilwa told him.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 South African journalists staged a protest outside the
Zimbabwe consulate in Cape Town on Wednesday afternoon, demanding
his immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   The South African Foreign Correspondent's Association and the
South African-based Freedom of Expression Institute have also
demanded Zilwa's release.
</P>
<P>
   Yves Sorokobi, Africa program coordinator for the New York-based
Committee to Protect Journalists, said that if Zilwa is not
released by Monday, the organization would work for his release.
</P>
<P>
   Nobel Prize winning author Nadine Gordimer issued a statement
calling the charges against Zilwa ''preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Western Cape chapter of the ruling African National Congress
said Zilwa's arrest ''boggles the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We know Obed as a dedicated and fearless journalist of
absolute integrity. His commitment to democracy and investigative
journalism are beyond question,'' wrote ANC provincial leader
Ebrahim Rasool. ''I cannot even begin to seriously consider his
involvement in the bombing of a newspaper's offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of the foreign press has increased in Zimbabwe recent
days. Last week, state-run television ran a story accusing the
international press corps of biased and alarmist reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the bombing, police said they were
suspicious that foreign journalists arrived at the scene so
quickly. Many of the journalists were staying at the nearby Meikles
Hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
