<HEADLINE> 'Nightly News' Rebroadcast on Hold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC said Friday that it has put on hold its
plans, announced only last week, to rebroadcast its ''Nightly
News'' program on the Pax television network each weeknight.
</P>
<P>
   NBC affiliates were upset about the idea, worrying that if
viewers could see the Tom Brokaw news report on another network an
hour later, many wouldn't watch it on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   NBC purchased a 32 percent stake in the family-friendly Pax
network last year and has started trying to get the two networks to
work together. Pax stations wanted to run an hour-long news block
at 7 p.m. each night that featured the Brokaw broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The rebroadcast was to begin next month on a test basis, then
start permanently in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   A delay in the rebroadcast would give NBC affiliates time to
work on joint sales agreements with Pax stations, NBC said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will enable potential future programming ideas to be seen
as opportunities and not threats,'' said Alan Frank, president of
the NBC affiliate board.
</P>
</TEXT>
