<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links Child Care, Less Crimes  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Children who attend quality day care are less
likely to commit crimes later in life, according to a report by law
enforcement groups unveiled Friday at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued by Fight Crime: Invest in Kids, a
700-member bipartisan coalition of police chiefs, sheriffs and
crime victims. Former police chiefs William Bratton of New York
City and Jerry Sanders of San Diego were among the authors.
</P>
<P>
   The report, a compilation of studies comparing children in and
out of day care programs in North Carolina and Chicago, found that
youths who spent their early years in quality child care were half
as likely to be arrested later. It involved 1,000 children who were
in day care at ages 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   The report called for increased government spending on day care
to ensure poor families have access, and better training and higher
salaries for child care workers, who on average are paid only about
half as much as parking lot attendants.
</P>
<P>
   ''Child care is not only a lifesaver for working families, it is
a crime-fighting strategy for our communities,'' first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton said at a ceremony announcing the study. ''For every
dollar we invest in child care we save $5 in crime costs down the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has made child care a key issue in her U.S. Senate
bid in New York, was joined at the White House by Sen. Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., and Rep. Benjamin Cardin, D-Md. They are pushing for
an additional $3 billion to create slots for another 950,000
children in Head Start and for block grants to expand early
education and child care for children under 5.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also is pushing a plan to provide tax breaks for
parents and employers that offer day care for workers' children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the report's authors, Dr. T. Berry Brazelton of Harvard
University, said the ''scientific research now proves the early
childhood development programs that help kids in so many other ways
are also our most powerful weapons in the fight against youth
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls released with the report found parents and police
overwhelmingly support child care and after-school activities.
</P>
<P>
   There was less agreement on whether children should be charged
as adults, kept in prisons or subjected to other increasingly
punitive measures. The polls found 17 percent of police chiefs
favor charging more juveniles as adults, compared with 12 percent
of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Fight Crime: Invest in Kids:
http://www.fightcrime.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
