<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Offers Education Plan  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Campaigning on George W. Bush's home turf,
Democrat Al Gore called Friday for withholding federal education
money from states that fail to improve student test scores and
redirecting the money to help some of the worst schools.
</P>
<P>
   The plan echoes one by the Texas governor, who has made
accountability the centerpiece of his education plan. But Bush, the
presumptive GOP presidential nominee, would redirect federal money
to vouchers that could be used to attend private schools --
something Gore opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to invest more and demand more -- not aim too low,
invest too little and drain resources away from public schools with
private school vouchers,'' Gore said in a speech to the National
Conference of Black Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore also would give bonuses to states that
improve test scores and reduce dropout rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I propose a plan with clear financial incentives for states
and school districts that successfully narrow the achievement gap --
and there will be clear financial consequences for those that
don't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With education at the top of voter concerns, Bush and Gore are
both campaigning hard on their plans for schools.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year, Gore has been touting an ambitious, $115
billion, 10-year plan to hire more teachers, triple the number of
charter schools, provide universal preschool and help build new
schools.
</P>
<P>
   That included a provision to identify and help fix failing
schools, but Friday's announcement offered considerably more detail
and suggested, for the first time, that federal education funding
should be tied to student performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp said Gore was taking a page from its plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to question a convert on the day of his
conversion, but we're glad Al Gore now agrees with Governor Bush's
proposal to hold schools accountable for results,'' said spokesman
Dan Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Gore plan, states that fail to improve test scores
would lose administrative money used to implement federal education
programs. That includes Title 1, an $8.6 billion program that helps
11 million poor students.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would redirect the money into a fund that failing schools
could tap to introduce new reforms as they work to turn themselves
around.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has campaigned on a host of traditionally Democratic
issues, has proposed a $13.5 billion, five-year education plan, far
more modest than Gore's proposal. Bush argues that the core of his
philosophy is accountability -- holding schools responsible for
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's plan includes harsher financial consequences for failing
schools. He would pull Title 1 money from individual schools that
fail to improve, giving the money over to parents in $1,500
vouchers that could be used for students to attend private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's plan outlined Friday, he would require states to
set standards and identify failing schools. If the schools do not
improve within two years, they would be closed then reopened under
new leadership.
</P>
<P>
   To help schools turn around, Gore offers $500 million per year
to pay for reform plans. He would also direct after-school money to
students at these schools and give the schools first crack at other
education funding.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush plan, beyond vouchers, breaks from other Republicans as
he calls for more, not less, federal spending -- though far less
than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would give families tax breaks to save for college,
vouchers to pay for after-school programs and rewards to schools
that improve test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Gore regularly criticizes these plans, saying there will be no
money to pay for them if he goes through with his proposed, $483
billion tax cut. ''He's already spent all the money,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush cites rising test scores in Texas, Gore said his
rival's state has below-average preschool enrollment and doesn't
have enough teachers to meet upcoming needs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's accountability plan also would:
</P>
<P>
   --Pay signing bonuses to attract new principals and teachers to
schools that are shut down and need to be reopened with new
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   --Measure progress based on the National Assessment of
Educational Progress, which many states already use.
</P>
<P>
   --Offer competitive grants for schools to enforce discipline and
anti-gun policies.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has proposed tying federal dollars to
school performance, and in 1994 Congress linked funding to
improvements in educating poor kids. So far, no states have had
money withheld.
</P>
<P>
   The National Conference of Black Mayors also invited Bush to
address the gathering but he declined, said Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk,
a Democrat. Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor had a
previously scheduled commitment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1712 </TRAILER>
