<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safety Agency Upgrades GM Probe  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal safety agency has upgraded its
investigation into some General Motors Corp. cars because of
possible ignition problems that could start a fire.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, in a monthly
report released Friday, said investigators will examine the
ignition on the Pontiac Grand Am, Buick Skylark and Oldsmobile
Achieva from model years 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 83 complaints about the problem, including three
injuries. Some drivers say when they turn the ignition, the car
will not start and then a fire ignites in the steering column.
</P>
<P>
   There are 699,617 of the vehicles on the road, the safety agency
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also upgraded its investigation into reported braking
problems on the 1995 model year GMC Jimmy, Chevrolet Blazer and
Chevy Suburban sport utility vehicles, Chevy Astro vans and Chevy
S10 and C/K pickups.
</P>
<P>
   The owners have complained that the exhaust gas recirculation
valve sticks open, resulting in loss of brake power and extended
stopping. The agency estimates there have been 32 crashes and 105
complaints -- but no injuries -- related to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   A GM spokesman said the company is cooperating in the
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA opens any safety investigation with a preliminary inquiry
in which the government and manufacturer exchange paperwork,
including any complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation then could be upgraded to an engineering
analysis, during which engineers study parts to see if they are
defective. An investigation eventually can lead to a recall.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also is upgrading these investigations:
</P>
<P>
   --1997-2000 Chevrolet Corvette; 127 complaints that seat belts
won't retract, making them unusable. There are about 85,880 of the
cars on the road.
</P>
<P>
   --1997-1999 Chevrolet Malibu; 42 complaints of overheating of the
stop and tail lights that may cause an outage. There are 520,777 of
the cars of the road.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also opened a preliminary investigation into Bell
Helmets USA's Star 1 model after a fatal motorcycle accident in
which the rider's helmet came off. An inspection showed the chin
strap had separated from the helmet shell.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
