<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Friday, April 28, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Urges Breakup of Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department, seeking a remedy last
used to dismember AT&AMP;T, asked a court today to split Microsoft into
two competing companies to shatter its monopoly over the system
that runs most personal computers. The government, joined by 19
states, asked that the giant software company be split into one
company to produce the Windows operating system and another to
handle other software applications, like spreadsheets and
databases. The government wants the companies to be barred from
reuniting for 10 years. The proposal was submitted to U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson after the close of financial markets
today. Jackson ruled April 3 that Microsoft repeatedly broke
federal antitrust laws intended to maintain fair competition by
using its monopoly power in computer operating systems to crush
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Gates Defends His Company
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft chairman Bill Gates had said before
today's filing that consumers will suffer if Microsoft is split up.
''We wouldn't have Windows today if it hadn't been for the Office
group and the Windows group working together,'' he said. Microsoft
spokesman Jim Cullinan said the recommendation to split the company
is ''like like telling McDonald's that it can only sell burgers,
not fries, and that it has to give away the recipe for its secret
sauce. We are confident that the appeals court will support
Microsoft's position,'' he added. Connecticut Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal, whose state was among 19 and the District of
Columbia to join in the suit, said, ''The most important thing is,
this is a very measured but responsible remedy.'' The judge is now
in the hands of the judge. Microsoft stock was down 1/16 at 69}
today.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Ends Down 154; Nasdaq Up 86
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell for a third straight
session today as investors worried about rising interest rates, but
technology shares continued their recovery and drove the Nasdaq
composite index higher. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
154.19 points to close at 10,733.91. The blue-chip index ended the
week down 110.14 points, or 1.0 percent. The Nasdaq composite rose
86.64 to close at 3,860.67. The index, which fell steeply earlier
this month, ended the week with a gain of 216.81 points, or 5.9
percent. Broader stock indicators were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   New York (AP) -- Financial Figures at the close:
