</P>
<P>
   Personal Income Rises 0.7 Percent
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' incomes, spending and savings were
all up in March, the Commerce Department said today. Personal
income -- wages, interest and government benefits -- rose 0.7
percent, a bit more than expected. Spending was up 0.5 percent. And
the savings rate -- savings as a percentage of after-tax income --
rose to 0.4 percent from a record low of 0.2 percent the month
before. March was the first month since last October that income
had grown faster than spending.
</P>
<P>
   U S West Reports Increased Profits
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- U S West reported today its first-quarter profits
rose 2.5 percent, topping Wall Street forecasts, as the local phone
company continued to post strong growth in wireless and Internet
services. The Denver-based Baby Bell, due to be acquired by Qwest
Communications International, earned $404 million or 79 cents a
share, through the first three months of the year, compared to 78
cents a share the year before. Revenues grew 6.6 percent to $3.38
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett To Take Blame at Meeting
</P>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Billionaire Warren Buffett will be able to
tell shareholders in person this weekend what he already has said
in print -- his company had its worst year ever and he blames
himself for the performance. This weekend's annual meeting is
expected to attract 12,000 investors and followers of Buffett, one
of the world's richest men, who has made the yearly gatherings a
circus-like event. Berkshire's earnings dropped 42 percent in 1999,
to $1.6 billion from $2.8 billion the year before. Berkshire's
stock, the most expensive on the New York Stock Exchange, fell 20
percent last year. At the same time, the stock market soared.
Berkshire Hathaway's Class A stock was up $500 at $59,900 a share
this afternoon on the New York Stock Exchange, but almost 24
percent below the 52-week high of $78,600.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna CEO Willing To Listen to Bids
</P>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Aetna Inc.'s new chairman told
disgruntled shareholders today that the nation's largest health
insurer is not for sale. But mindful of dissatisfaction with the
performance of Aetna stock, William H. Donaldson said he would
consider any meaningful offers. Rather than putting itself on the
market, Aetna is speeding to carry out plans announced in March to
split into two publicly traded companies: One for health care, the
other for financial services. The breakup is expected this summer.
Last month, Aetna rejected a $70-per-share, or $10 billion,
takeover offer from Wellpoint Health Networks and ING Group, saying
it was inadequate. That move perturbed some big shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Lyonnais Probe Adds Trichet
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The head of the Bank of France is being
investigated in connection with the travails of Credit Lyonnais, a
bank that lost billions before undergoing a costly government
bailout. Jean-Claude Trichet, who has been expected to succeed Wim
Duisenberg as head of the European Central Bank in 2002, is
suspected of disseminating false information to financial markets,
judicial sources said on condition of anonymity. Trichet served as
director of the French Treasury from 1987 to 1993, covering the
critical 1992-93 period of bank records being examined. Trichet
said he was ''profoundly surprised'' by the turn of events and that
he would place himself at the ''total disposition'' of the
investigating judge.
</P>
<P>
   Top Managers Leave Soros' Fund Co.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The top two managers at Soros Fund Management, a
$14 billion hedge fund company, are leaving in the wake of
double-digit declining performance this year. The departures of
Stan Druckenmiller, portfolio manager of the Quantum Fund, and Nick
Roditi, 54, portfolio manager of the Quota Fund, puts the future of
Soros' hedge fund empire up in the air. George Soros, 69, a
renowned investor and philanthropist, said today in a letter to
investors that he will convert the Quantum Fund to a ''lower
risk/lower reward operation'' and rename it the Quantum Endowment
Fund. He did not name a successor to Druckenmiller. The Quantum
Fund, which has assets of $8.24 billion, is down 22 percent this
year. The Quota Fund, which has $1.27 billion in assets, is down 32
percent this year. Soros said he plans to transfer the management
of the assets to another outside advisor.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Pulled on Mirabella Magazine
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mirabella magazine, geared toward intellectual
women who also want to keep up with the latest fashion trends,
apparently couldn't find enough readers fitting that description.
The magazine's parent company, Hachette Filipacchi, has announced
that the June/July issue will be Mirabella's last. The magazine was
founded by former Vogue editor Grace Mirabella, and was aimed at
women alienated by the glitz of magazines like Vogue and Harper's
Bazaar.
</P>
