<HEADLINE> Profit-Taking Hits Grain, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices finished mixed Friday on
the Chicago Board of Trade as profit-taking ahead of the weekend
reversed early gains.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans sank the most, declining after private forecasts showed
a potent storm system headed toward the Midwest in seven to 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   Corn prices fell to their lowest level in two and a half weeks,
pressured by soybeans and early corn planting.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat rebounded from the previous day's selloff, edging up
slightly amid continuing dryness in the winter wheat belt. But
gains were limited by the selloff in soybeans and corn.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose } cent to $2.54} a bushel; July
corn fell 2\ cents to $2.32 a bushel; July oats fell { cent to
$1.21} a bushel; July soybeans fell 5} cents to $5.39\ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures were lower.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .13 cent to 69.27 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle rose .50 cent to 84.82 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell .40 cent to 76.65 cents a pound; May pork bellies fell .37
cent to 99.55 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
