<DOCNO> APW20000428.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Hits New Low Versus Dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro slipped to another record low against
the dollar Friday as the U.S. currency staged a strong advance
against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   The euro fell as low as 90.30 cents in midday trading in London,
below its previous all-time low of 90.59 cents reached at midday
Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the single curency of 11 European nations recovered a bit to
finish at 90.92 cents in late dealings in New York, down from 91.01
cents in late dealings Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar gained nearly 2 yen against the Japanese yen, rising
to 108.18 Japanese yen from 106.36 yen late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. currency also rose to 1.4810 Canadian dollars from
1.4766 late Thursday but it fell to 1.7228 Swiss francs from
1.7272. The British pound fell to $1.5526 from $1.5753.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, launched in January 1999, sank to new lows on three of
the five trading days this week. Analysts say investors doubt that
European authorities can rally around a strategy that would
stimulate growth and make Europe a more attractive place to invest.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank's quarter percentage point increase in
interest rates on Thursday failed to spark enthusiasm for the
currency.
</P>
<P>
   But the dollar's most striking move Friday was its advance
against the Japanese yen, which has also been trading near record
highs against the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Anderson, financial economist for Fleet Bank in Boston,
said some the yen buying was by professionals in advance of a
series of Golden Week national holidays that will close the
financial markets in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   He said traders feel Japanese authorities ''are more bothered by
the euro's weakness than the U.S. is'' and would like to see the
euro strengthen.
</P>
<P>
   A strong yen versus the euro makes Japanese products more
expensive in Europe, dampening the Japanese export market.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1514 German
marks, up from 2.1476; 7.2155 French francs, up from 7.2028; and
2,129.88 Italian lire, up from 2,126.02.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1735 </TRAILER>
