<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ore. Teens Elect Bush in Mock Vote  </HEADLINE>
By TARA BURGHART, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- George W. Bush accepted the Republican
presidential nomination Friday -- from a mock convention put on by
Oregon teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor was nominated a day earlier by a 3-1 margin
over John McCain at the model convention, which is an Oregon
tradition that dates back to 1964. The students, mostly high
schoolers, play the parts of delegates, committee chairs and caucus
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting by telephone from Austin, Texas, Bush told the 2,000
students on the convention floor that he will ''run a campaign that
will lift our spirits.'' On education, he said schools should make
decisions at the local level and students should be provided with
standards they must meet before advancing.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, presidential candidates including Robert F.
Kennedy, Ronald Reagan, Bill Clinton, Jesse Jackson and Bush's
father have appeared in person at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Some students on Friday were disappointed that Bush didn't do
the same. Indeed, Tyler Warren, 18, of Hillsboro High School, said
he felt most of the presidential candidates this year were ignoring
the youth vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Bush had wanted to reach out to the younger generation of
voters, this could have been an important attempt to do that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the best convention style, after Bush hung up students
representing the Texas delegation gave him a standing ovation and
marched around the convention floor chanting his name and waving
signs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1804 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000428.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Dead in Suburban Pa. Shootings  </HEADLINE>
By TODD SPANGLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   McKEES ROCKS, Pa. (AP) -- A gunman opened fire in two suburban
Pittsburgh shopping centers Friday, killing three people, police
said. A man in custody was also suspected in a fourth person's
death, as well as shootings at two synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   Two people were fatally shot at a Chinese restaurant in McKees
Rocks, while another person was killed at a martial arts school in
Monaca, police said. A woman was found dead in her Mount Lebanon
home, and the shooter was suspected in her death, said Mount
Lebanon police Deputy Chief Henry Egal.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's cause of death had not been determined. She lived on
the same block as the unidentified suspect, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect also fired shots at two synagogues, but no one was
injured, police said. A swastika and the word ''Jew'' had been
sprayed on one synagogue, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Vinh Truong, a cook at the Ya Fei Chinese Cuisine restaurant at
the Plaza at Robinson Town Centre in McKees Rocks, said his
brother-in-law was one of the two shot there.
</P>
<P>
   Truong was in the kitchen when an employee ran from the front of
the restaurant, telling everyone to escape. Instead, he left the
kitchen and saw his brother-in-law on the floor
</P>
<P>
   ''I see my brother Tony on the floor,'' said Truong, who did not
give the man's full name. ''I tell everybody 'somebody shot
Tony.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Beaver County dispatcher said a suspect was arrested in
Ambridge, about 6 miles southeast of Monaca and 16 miles northwest
of Pittsburgh. No further details of the shootings or arrest were
available.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Township police in nearby Carnegie said another person was
wounded at an undisclosed location there. Linda Ross, a spokeswoman
at Mercy Hospital in Pittsburgh, said that the 25-year-old man was
in critical condition with a gunshot wound to the upper back and
neck region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1812 </TRAILER>
