<DOCNO> APW20000428.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidential Matching Funds Awarded  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John McCain's defunct presidential campaign
qualified for $3.4 million from taxpayers to help pay off its debts
as election officials tallied another round of matching funds
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission certified $5.4 million in
matching funds to seven presidential candidates, pushing the total
for the 2000 election to $54.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, qualified
for almost $1 million in the latest round, bringing his total to a
record $14.1 million. The numbers tend to climb each presidential
election year.
</P>
<P>
   At $14 million, McCain also surpassed the previous record of
$13.5 million set by GOP nominee Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The matching funds show McCain's fund-raising strength in the
battle for the GOP nomination. He suspended his campaign March 7,
ceding the contest to Texas Gov. George W. Bush, and reported $8.6
million in debts at the end of that month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive GOP nominee, didn't accept matching funds,
freeing him from the primary spending limits attached to the
taxpayers' money. He didn't need it: Bush has raised a record $80
million.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government matches the first $250 of each individual
contribution to a candidate who limits primary spending to $40.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials say they expect to qualify for about $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's former Democratic primary opponent, Bill Bradley, will
receive another $277,763, bringing his total to $12.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates certified for funds Friday were: Alan Keyes,
Republican, $359,608; Gary Bauer, a Republican who quit the race,
$68,423; Patrick Buchanan, Reform Party, $117,809; John Hagelin,
Natural Law Party, $234,910.
</P>
<P>
   Due to a shortage of funds, the Treasury is behind in making
payments. In all, the government now owes candidates about $16.3
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1814 </TRAILER>
