<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Faces U.S. Move To Amend ABM  </HEADLINE>
By JIM HEINTZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- With its conventional forces deteriorating and its
nuclear arsenal approaching obsolescence, Russia looks with anxiety
at moves to further undermine its military might -- which it
believes changing the ABM Treaty would do.
</P>
<P>
   There was no reaction from the Kremlin on Friday to the release
of new details about the United States' push to amend the pact, but
Russia has vehemently objected for months.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin has threatened that Russia could pull
out of all arms control pacts if the United States goes ahead with
building a missile defense system Russia says is disallowed under
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is likely to be at the center of President Clinton's
June 3-4 summit with Putin. Clinton has said of Putin that ''I
think the United States can do business with this man,'' and the
ABM dispute promises to test that view.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants Russia to agree to amending the treaty
to allow construction of such a system, which Washington says it
needs to protect the country against possible missile attacks by
''rogue'' nations such as North Korea and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Russia argues that the system would undermine the treaty's basic
philosophy: that nuclear states are unlikely to launch a missile
strike if they have no way of defending themselves against a
retaliatory barrage.
</P>
<P>
   The United States counters that its proposed system would be
designed to defend against only a few dozen missiles and could not
protect the country against an attack as large as Russia is capable
of launching.
</P>
<P>
   ''Strategic offensive forces give each side the certain ability
to carry out an annihilating attack ... Forces of this size can
easily penetrate a limited NMD (national missile defense) system of
the type the United States is now developing,'' says a U.S.
document published Friday by the Bulletin of Atomic Scientists and
confirmed by U.S. Ambassador James Collins.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia worries that the limited NMD system the United States
says it wants could easily be expanded and the U.S. proposal
suggests negotiations on further changes in the treaty should begin
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of the United States expanding its missile defenses
comes as Russia's nuclear capacities decline. The current Russian
arsenal of about 6,000 warheads could shrink to a few hundred in
the next decade, analysts say, because maintaining the old ones and
building new ones costs more than the cash-strapped government can
bear.
</P>
<P>
   Economics was a key argument behind Putin's recent successful
push for the Russian parliament to ratify the long-delayed START II
arms-reduction treaty. Proponents said trimming the nuclear arsenal
would enhance security.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's sense of security has plunged over the last decade as
the troubles of the underfunded conventional forces became known
and NATO expanded eastward.
</P>
<P>
   With his championing of START II and the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty, Putin has indicated a willingness to work with the
West as long as Russia negotiates from a position of strength. If
the United States pushes Russia into a corner on ABM, he may look
for a way to compromise without appearing to capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   The military has said its likely response to any breach of the
ABM treaty would be to fit multiple nuclear warheads to its new
Topol-M missiles. Topol-Ms currently carry just one warhead each,
in line with START II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
