<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, McCain To Meet May 9  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Setting aside differences, aides for George W.
Bush and John McCain agreed Friday on the broad outlines of an
agenda for a May 9 meeting between the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee and his vanquished rival.
</P>
<P>
   One day after McCain nearly scrapped the event in a dispute over
the agenda, Bush campaign manager Joe Allbaugh and McCain political
director John Weaver met for 45 minutes here and agreed to keep the
date a week from Tuesday in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda was said to include McCain's signature issue of
campaign finance overhaul along with military reform, Social
Security, education, health care, making the GOP more inclusive and
McCain's role in the fall campaign and the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a cordial, productive meeting and we agreed on an
agenda,'' Weaver said in a telephone interview minutes after the
session broke up. ''Senator McCain looks forward to a productive,
substantial meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate telephone interview, Allbaugh said, ''It was a
positive 45-minute meeting. We talked about a variety of issues and
the governor is looking forward to meeting Senator McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides were expected to discuss the topics in more detail before
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The session will be important to the political fortunes of both
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to unify the party and appeal to independent-minded
voters who flocked to McCain's campaign before he dropped out in
March. The Arizona senator, who still has presidential ambitions,
wants to show Republicans he is a party man.
</P>
<P>
   There are downsides for both men, too. Bush is unlikely to
emerge from the meeting with McCain's endorsement, which he needs
to help court independent voters. And McCain fears he could damage
his political maverick image if he unites with Bush at a meeting
that independent voters recognize as, in the words of one aide, ''a
political charade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush raised the stakes by taking the unusual step last week of
announcing that he would ask McCain whether he wants to be
considered a prospect for the vice presidential nomination. McCain
has said he doesn't want the job.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, has been under pressure from some Republicans who
think McCain's appeal is worth a major effort to get him on the
ticket. McCain and his advisers believed that Bush was turning the
meeting into a high-profile forum for the Arizona senator to take
himself out of the running.
</P>
<P>
   Their discomfort with that notion suggests that some top McCain
supporters want him to remain a vice presidential prospect. Some of
them say they suspect that McCain could be persuaded to serve on
the ticket if Bush waged a sincere campaign to do so.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's camp felt that Bush and his advisers were trying to
seek advantage in the meeting through news leaks. After threatening
to cancel or postpone the event Thursday, Weaver's previously
scheduled meeting with Allbaugh took on added importance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
