<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chris Rock's Comedic Magazine Debuts  </HEADLINE>
By CANDACE SMITH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the tradition of Harvard's Lampoon, the
first black satirical publication produced at a historically black
university made its long awaited debut Friday but its main backer,
Chris Rock, was absent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clean. It's colorful. It's well stapled. It's very
good,'' said Bill Stepheny, a New York-based record producer who is
co-founder of the 23-page, full color Illtop Journal.
</P>
<P>
   The first run, 20,000 copies, was produced and distributed by
students at Howard University, one of the nation's oldest
historically black colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine was conceived in 1998 by Rock who wants it to be a
training ground for African-American writers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a market where people of color are under represented
and nearly nonexistent in the creative behind-the-sences roles
(i.e. ''Friends''),'' writes Rock on page five of the magazine. ''I
hope that The Illtop Journal becomes a name that is synonymous with
producing some of the most talented young black comedy writers in
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepheny read a letter from Rock at a news conference where the
magazine was released.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have all worked very hard and I am so proud of our first
issue of the Illtop Journal,'' said Rock, who apologized for not
being on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Rock said he is making a movie ''to make some money to pay for
all of this again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore April Bush, 20, really liked the magazine. ''The name
is dope,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's also Rock's creation, a take on Howard's student
newspaper ''The Hilltop.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York native has appeared on several comedy shows,
including ''Saturday Night Live'' and ''In Living Color.'' He has
won three Emmy and two Grammy Awards, has appeared in several
movies, written a book and hosts his own HBO talk show.
</P>
<P>
   P. Kobina Yankah, the Journal's editor-in-chief, said Rock
brought energy to the publication. ''He's personally seen the
magazine, seen all the articles, sent feedback to us,'' Yankah
said.
</P>
<P>
   The staff was treated to a trip to New York last year to HBO's
''The Chris Rock Show'' where they got advice on their writing.
</P>
<P>
   The premier issue features a photo of a campus building with one
cartoon fraternity character initiating another with the slogan,
''Our Brutal Initiation into the World of Literary Humor.''
</P>
<P>
   The back page pictures two white characters dressed as court
jesters ready to initiate a black cartoon figure with wooden
paddles. The paddles carry the names of Illtop's counterparts at
Harvard and Stanford. Two representatives from those college humor
magazines welcomed the Illtop with a mallet, copies of the Lampoon,
a drinking mug and a framed sketch.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal contains humorous ads and articles on sex and
politics. There are articles like, ''White's student's guide to
howard u,'' and ''Texas Teen Looks Forward to Big Score.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an interview with comedian Paul Mooney and horoscopes,
but even they can't be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brown, one of the magazine's faculty advisers, said the
first two issues would be free, but after that ''We're looking for
sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   The students plan two issues a semester but Stepheny said:
''We'll take it as it comes. The success is that we got it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1831 </TRAILER>
