<HEADLINE> Friday's Commodities Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gold prices slid to a seven-month low Friday, pressured by the
dollar's continued strength and the imminent gold sale by the Swiss
National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, natural gas prices leaped higher and soybeans
fell.
</P>
<P>
   Gold has been mostly in the doldrums since last fall except for
a brief but explosive rally that pushed the price as high as
$326.90 a troy ounce in February.
</P>
<P>
   It had settled into a trading range around the $280s -- still
comfortably above the 20-year low of $255 reached last summer. But
the specter of upcoming central bank sales of gold in Europe has
driven buyers away, and the exodus from gold accelerated Friday
partly on word that the Swiss sale could begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss National Bank president Hans Meyer said the new currency
law freeing the Swiss franc from its gold reserves is to take
effect May 1, or Monday, and the bank will begin the sale of its
excess gold reserves ''as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   That will dump more gold into a market that already has abundant
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Gold for June delivery dipped $3.70 to $274.20 an ounce on the
Comex division of the New York Mercantile Exchange -- the lowest
price since September.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is difficult for investors or consumers to buy gold in the
face of certain knowledge that two major central banks will be
selling shortly,'' said Leonard Kaplan, chief bullion dealer for
LFG Bullion Services in Chicago, referring to the upcoming Swiss
and Bank of England sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''The natural human response is 'Well, let's wait and see what
happens.' This creates a shortage of buyers and gives sellers a
tremendous opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the dollar's seemingly unassailable might
discourages any flight into gold.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said the dollar's strength masks the fact that ''in 95
percent of the currencies of the world, gold is in a roaring bull
market. It is only in the dollar that gold has done very poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   On another trading floor of the New York Merc, natural gas
prices roared nearly 3 percent higher amid reports that warmer
weather in the southwestern and southcentral United States will
boost demand for supplemental cooling fuel.
</P>
<P>
   June natural gas rose 8.6 cents to $3.141 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   Other energy prices were mostly higher. June crude oil rose 32
cents to $25.74 a barrel, expiring May heating oil contracts fell
1.87 cents to 73.18 cents a gallon and May unleaded gasoline rose
0.21 cent to 82.59 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   In London, June Brent crude from the North Sea rose 13 cents to
$23.89 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans sank on the Chicago Board of Trade after a private
forecast said a potent storm system was headed toward the Midwest
next weekend. The long-term weather outlook halted a mild rally
that followed a big selloff on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains could alter the crop picture for this year, which so
far remains clouded by abnormally dry soil conditions.
</P>
<P>
   July soybeans fell 5} cents to $5.39\ a bushel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
