<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Inflation on the Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Consumer prices rose 10.2 percent in
April, boosting Ecuador's annual inflation rate to 88.9 percent,
economic officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador is trying to tame its inflation -- the highest in Latin
America -- by phasing out its currency, the sucre, and replacing it
with the U.S. dollar. April's annualized inflation rate is 8
percentage points higher than the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   President Gustavo Noboa's government has said the Andean nation
will end the year with inflation of no more than 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for school supplies, clothing and books at the start of
the new school year helped drive up the inflation rate, said German
Rojas, director of Ecuador's National Statistics Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause, he said, was an 80 percent hike in public
transportation fares, associated with the government's attempts to
cut spending.
</P>
<P>
   International lenders last month pledged a three-year dlrs 2
billion aid package to help finance the rebuilding of Ecuador's
shattered economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the conditions for the aid include cutting government
subsidies, which is expected to significantly increase the cost of
home cooking fuel, gasoline and other consumer items.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
