<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional EPA Director Suspended  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN GALLAGHER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency's
regional director in Denver was suspended Friday while he fights
allegations that he illegally helped raise money for a Montana
congressional candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Yellowtail was removed as head of EPA's Region 8, covering
Colorado, Utah, Wyoming, Montana, North Dakota and South Dakota.
Yellowtail will help his acting successor for 30 days, then will go
on unpaid leave from his $130,000-a-year job, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel this is serious enough that he needs to step aside,''
said W. Michael McCabe, EPA's acting deputy administrator in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowtail's staff said Friday he had gone to his ranch in
Montana, and is due back in the Denver office next week. A call
seeking comment from Yellowtail in Montana was not immediately
returned.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Office of Special Counsel accused Yellowtail of
breaking the law by signing his name to a 1998 letter seeking
campaign contributions for Robert ''Dusty'' Deschamps, a Democrat
who ran unsuccessfully for Montana's lone House seat.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowtail, 52, sought that seat in 1996 as a Democrat and lost
to Republican Rep. Rick Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law bans campaign activity by government workers.
Yellowtail has decided to defend himself through proceedings before
the Merit Systems Protection Board. The case could last six months
or more.
</P>
<P>
   The region overseen by Yellowtail has about 700 employees at
offices in Denver and Helena. Major projects include an ongoing
investigation into asbestos exposure from mining in northwestern
Montana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
