<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30-Year Treasury Bonds Gain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The price of 30-year Treasury bonds rose Friday,
reversing early losses, as blue-chip stocks fell. But shorter
maturities were mostly lower on inflation jitters.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark long-term Treasury rose 11/32 point, or $3.44 per
$1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, fell to 5.96 percent from 5.98 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the trading day, when long-term bonds were retreating,
yields briefly rose above 6 percent. The last time 30-year
Treasurys closed at or above 6 percent was March 20.
</P>
<P>
   Traders shifted money into bonds as blue-chip stocks fell. The
Dow Jones industrial average dropped 154.19 points to close at
10,733.91.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term notes were weighed down by inflation concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists believe the robust economy is rekindling
inflation. Traders fear the Federal Reserve will be even more
aggressive in trying to cool of growth. That could mean raising
interest rates by one-half percentage point, rather than a
quarter-point increase that had been expected at a May 16 meeting
of the central bank's policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation and rising rates erode the value of investments that
pay a fixed return, such as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the price of short-term notes fell 1/16 point to 3/32
point, according to Bridge Telerate, a financial information
service. Intermediate maturities were mixed, ranging from down 1/32
point to up 1/16 point.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.80 percent as the
discount jumped 0.07 percentage point from Thursday to 5.65
percent. Six-month yields were 6.10 percent as the discount rate
rose 0.05 point to 5.85 percent. One-year yields were 6.15 percent
as the discount rose 0.02 percentage point to 5.85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, slipped to 5.94 percent from 6 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose [ point to 94 7/16. The average yield
fell to 6.00 percent from 6.01 percent on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
