<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds FCC Phone Decision  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An appeals court Friday upheld a decision by
the Federal Communications Commission to free long-distance
companies from having to file with the agency federal tariffs
outlining their rates or service changes.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit
puts to rest a challenge by MCI WorldCom and others to the FCC's
1996 order doing away with the tariff requirement. The
long-distance companies filed suit, claiming that the commission
exceeded its authority in completely eliminating the tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman Bill Kennard called the decision a victory for
consumers and said it would force long-distance companies to better
inform their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''What long-distance companies ought to be doing is aggressively
advertising their prices on the Internet and in the media,''
Kennard said. ''Federal tariff filings can no longer be used as a
tool to keep prices higher than what a competitive marketplace
would require.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies had contended that without tariffs, they would
have to enter into some other contract with customers each time
rates or services were changed. That would make it harder for them
to offer new discount plans or promotions featuring free or cheap
calls, they argued. It would also incur additional costs to send
out mass mailings to individual consumers to inform them of each
rate change.
</P>
<P>
   By at least permitting the tariffs, long-distance companies said
they could hammer out individual contracts with large users but
file tariffs in instances when it made more sense -- such as when a
change affects millions of mass-market consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Companies said they would have to determine how the FCC order
would change their business practices. Because of the court
challenge, long-distance companies have continued to file tariff
information with the FCC since the 1996 order.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that the decision is unfortunate, but we look
forward to working with the FCC to ensure that the transition ...
is as smooth as possible for consumers,'' said MCI WorldCom
spokeswoman Julie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups had contended that the arrangement was letting
companies slip rate changes by customers. Critics added that the
tariff was used as a shield to avoid companies having to forge
individual contracts with users.
</P>
<P>
   The century-old doctrine allowed long-distance companies to
charge only the rates for services they had filed with the agency.
The tariff trumped all other agreements with customers, verbal or
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC also contended that the system was hindering full
competition, because companies can find out what their competitors
are charging through the publicly available tariffs. The commission
wanted to make the conditions that long-distance companies operate
in more like that of other unregulated industries.
</P>
<P>
   Citing portions of a 1996 telecommunications law, the commission
said that it had the authority to stop enforcing the tariff
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the court agreed. ''It was certainly reasonable to
move regulation in that direction even if it ostensibly raises
transaction costs for the carriers,'' the three-judge panel ruled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1920 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
