<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U S West Reports Increased Profits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- U S West reported Friday its first-quarter profits
rose 2.5 percent, topping Wall Street forecasts, as the local phone
company continued to post strong growth in wireless and Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver-based Baby Bell, due to be acquired by Qwest
Communications International, earned $404 million or 79 cents a
share, through the first three months of the year. That compared
with earnings of $394 million, or 78 cents a share, for the same
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues grew 6.6 percent to $3.38 billion from the year-ago
tally of $3.17 billion, led by a 167 percent jump in wireless
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, shares of U S
West rose 43} cents to $71.25.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our top-line growth figures show that we are hitting on all
cylinders through our growth initiatives and in our core
business,'' Sol Trujillo, chairman, president and chief executive
officer, said Friday. ''And much of that top-line success is
flowing to the bottom line, despite incurring
higher-than-anticipated dilution from our growth initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were pleased with the earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought it was certainly a strong effort by U S West. It
was a solid quarter in a lot of respects,'' said David Burkes,
telecommunications analyst with Hilliard Lyons. ''We think the
company appears to be moving toward the (Qwest) merger with strong
operating momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest results were hurt by $32 million in after-tax losses
and about $9 million in costs related to the merger agreement with
Qwest, an operator of a national fiber-optic network.
</P>
<P>
   The merger between the two companies recently won regulatory
clearance from the Federal Communications Commission, but still
needs to win approval from state regulators in Arizona, Minnesota,
Montana, Washington, Wyoming and Utah. Colorado and Iowa already
have approved the merger.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Qwest agreed to sell off its long-distance
operations in the states where U S West is the local telephone
monopoly. U S West cannot sell long distance in those markets until
it shows that they are open to competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
