<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor orders closure of beleaguered psychiatric hospital  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- After decades of problems, including
attacks on patients, patient suicides and overcrowding, Gov.
Christie Whitman ordered Friday that Greystone Park Psychiatric
Hospital be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the hospital in Parsippany is no longer
''functioning in a manner that is perceived as safe.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department of Human Services Commissioner Michele K. Guhl
said it may take as long as three years to move all of Greystone's
600-plus patients. The governor said all patients must be evaluated
to determine who can be moved into the community and who must be
institutionalized at another hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Details were sparse as to what, if anything, will replace the
124-year-old hospital that serves mentally ill residents of six
northern New Jersey counties.
</P>
<P>
   Guhl said a new, smaller facility may be built on the same site
in Morris County, or elsewhere in northern New Jersey, to serve
those who cannot be moved to less restrictive community group homes
or supervised apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ''The model of a sprawling big hospital .... is indeed a
dinosaur. It's over,'' she said. ''It's fair to say that Greystone
as we know it will not exist. While there may be a small
psychiatric hospital on those grounds, that's a maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Guhl said no single incident triggered the decision to close the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're exasperated, we're frustrated. I think we just reached a
cumulative level and we said, that's it, that's enough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes on the heels of a recent spate of disturbing
reports and incidents at Greystone. Last month, a report found the
hospital's patients were crowded into bedrooms and living in
unsanitary conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a male patient was charged with sexually
assaulting a mildly retarded female patient in an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's order also follows the October escape of a
civilly committed sex offender, the arrest of four Greystone
employees for allegedly assaulting and illegally restraining a
patient in March, and an investigation into at least a dozen
employees failing to report a suicide attempt last year.
</P>
<P>
   Guhl said Greystone, although as old and overcrowded as the
state's three other psychiatric institutions, has long bedeviled
state officials. A number of chief executive officers have been
hired and fired and new management techniques employed, but nothing
seemed to work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Greystone has had seemingly intractable problems for at least
20 years,'' the commissioner said. ''Something about Greystone has
eluded past administrations.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said a recent Supreme Court decision directing
states to move borderline patients out of institutionalized
settings also factored into the decision.
</P>
<P>
   But state Senate Democratic Leader Richard Codey, a longtime
watchdog for the mentally ill, said he opposed the move.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor is saying it's broke and she doesn't know how to
fix it and that's wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Codey said he would rather the Whitman administration improve
conditions at the hospital by supplying more funding, increasing
employee salaries and firing Chief Executive Officer Michael
Greenstein, under whose tenure some of the recent problems
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''He deserves to be fired because this happened on his watch.
He's clueless. He let those people down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guhl said she stands by Greystone's top man.
</P>
<P>
   ''I honestly believe this goes well beyond any one CEO,'' she
said. Guhl said she will retain Greenstein because she wants to
maintain stability at the institution during ''this very anxious
time.''
</P>
<P>
   While Greystone will eventually be phased out, state officials
said they will move forward with interim measures to improve the
level of care at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Those short term plans include hiring 40 new employees, reducing
the population by about 50 patients, and establishing new programs
for the remaining residents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state will hire mental health experts to evaluate
all remaining Greystone patients, as well as about 750 others in
other hospitals, with an eye toward moving many into community
settings.
</P>
<P>
   The Greystone patients who still require hospitalized care would
then be moved into newly available beds at other facilities or into
a new northern New Jersey hospital, the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
   Guhl said she has received assurances from Whitman that money
will be available for a new push toward community placement for the
mentally ill, although she declined to say how much.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said she would personally oppose privatizing
any new psychiatric hospital, but did not rule it out. She made no
guarantees that the hospital's 1,100 employees will retain their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   That was not good enough for Democratic critics of
privatization, who sought an ironclad promise that any new future
hospital would remain in state hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 1923 </TRAILER>
