<HEADLINE> Mexico Police Homicide Chief Killed  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Seven gunmen killed the police homicide chief
in northern Sinaloa state Friday, the fourth slaying of a top
Mexican law officer in two months.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants ambushed Williams Roman Garcia's car, spraying it
with bullets in an attack that appeared to be part of a wave of
drug-related violence as Mexico prepares for a presidential
election on July 2.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Roman Garcia by seven armed assailants occurred
only blocks from the homicide chief's home, the Sinaloa state
attorney general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The television network Televisa reported that at least one
person had been detained in connection with the attack, but
officials did not confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Garcia, who had been chief of homicide for about 10
months, was investigating the Sunday shooting deaths of two Federal
Preventative Police officers and already had witness descriptions
of the assailants, according to officials from the state attorney
general's office who spoke to The Associated Press, but asked not
to be named for fear of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Sinaloa Gov. Juan Millan told the government news agency Notimex
that the attackers in Sunday's shooting wore the insignia of the
Federal Judicial Police and that initial indications were that the
shooting happened during a confrontation between the two agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Sinaloa state, home to most of Mexico's major drug traffickers,
has seen at least 130 homicides this year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press 20 days before his
death, Roman Garcia said he had hit a wall in his attempt to
investigate the killings because the cases involved drug
trafficking, which is out of his area.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Garcia accused the federal judicial police, who are
responsible for investigating drug trafficking, of incompetence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
