<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General releases first update on State Police reforms  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The attorney general Friday released the
first report detailing reforms made in State Police operations
ordered after the state admitted that the practice of racial
profiling existed.
</P>
<P>
   But the court-mandated disclosure did not contain numbers of
minorities stopped by troopers or other related statistics that the
state must periodically make public.
</P>
<P>
   In its agreement with the U.S. Justice Department, the state
said it would provide the number of motor vehicle stops, each
driver's race, a reason for the stop and the actions taken by the
trooper.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said in Friday's report that the information is
being compiled and it will be released ''within the time period set
forth'' by the court.
</P>
<P>
   Progress reports on more than 100 other items identified by the
Justice Department were included in the materials offered by the
state. Under the terms of the agreement, New Jersey is to issue
four such reports a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been substantial reforms on a number of the areas
that were singled out in the consent decree,'' said First Assistant
Attorney General Paul Zoubek.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms should show both the judge overseeing the agreement
and the public that the state has taken the issues seriously,
Zoubek said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really have set forth a comprehensive method for dealing
with this issue and ensuring the public that we have made
changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Justice department agreed to the legal
settlement with the state, which included the appointment of an
independent civilian monitor, who will report to the U.S. District
Court in Trenton. The consent decree was one way for the state to
avoid a full-blown civil rights battle in open court, according to
federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities also required the state to expand the
so-called early warning system to be installed to track trooper
patrols with an eye toward detecting any troubling patterns, and to
implement the system within six months.
</P>
<P>
   The order also mandated the reports on the highway stops to be
made public every six months.
</P>
<P>
   Many reforms, including a revision of State Police protocols and
new diversity training for all troopers, were ordered before the
consent decree, Zoubek said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that training has been done personally by Col. Carson
Dunbar, the trooper's superintendent, Zoubek said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year two reports from the state attorney general documented
the practice of racial profiling of motorists and of racial
discrimination within the State Police ranks. Promised improvements
included new training and a new system for civilian complaints.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 1935 </TRAILER>
