<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Reached on Oil Pipeline  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Turkey, Azerbaijan and Georgia reached
agreement Friday on the legal framework for a 1,080-mile pipeline
to send Caspian Sea oil to the Mediterranean port of Ceyhan without
going through Russia or Iran.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced the accord, which builds on an
initial agreement signed in Istanbul, Turkey, last Nov. 18.
''Today's achievement completes this work and brings the pipeline
project a critical step closer to fruition,'' the president said in
a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   He said the next phase would be for companies in the United
States, Western Europe and Russia to work with Azerbaijan, Georgia,
Kazakhstan and Turkey to transform the legal documents into
commercial reality.
</P>
<P>
   The Baku-Tbilisi-Ceyhan pipeline, expected to cost $2.4 billion,
would carry oil from the rich fields of Azerbaijan through Georgia
to Ceyhan. The United States says the pipeline will help protect
global energy supplies by sending fuel through multiple routes
instead of a single chokepoint.
</P>
<P>
   Most Azerbaijani oil is exported through Russia. Much of the
Middle East's oil passes through the narrow Straits of Hormuz,
which separates Iran from the Arabian peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   For the Clinton administration, the accord is intended to draw
the oil rich region closer to the United States and Europe and
reduce Russian influence in the newly independent Central Asian
states.
</P>
<P>
   ''By this action, Azerbaijan, Georgia and Turkey have shown once
again their commitment to building regional cooperation, peaceful
relations and better lives for all their people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States is committed to the Baku-Tbilisi-Ceyhan
pipeline as a key part of our overall approach to Caspian energy
development,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to ensure access to world markets for the countries of
the region, while helping diversify sources of energy supply for
consumers in the United States and around the globe,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton witnessed the signing of the November agreement during a
visit to Istanbul for a meeting of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was the chief competitor for the U.S-backed deal and had
tried to persuade Azerbaijan to agree to a pipeline through Russia.
Iran had favored an oil swap deal in which Azerbaijani oil would be
sold in northern Iran and oil from fields in southern Iran would be
sold on Azerbaijan's behalf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 1953 </TRAILER>
