<HEADLINE> Man Gets 30 Years For Pyramid Scam  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A Syracuse businessman who crafted the biggest
pyramid scam in history was sent to prison for 30 years Friday by a
judge who had offered to cut the sentence by 10 years if his wife
relinquished her assets.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge John S. Martin sentenced the businessman,
Patrick Bennett, to one of the largest white-collar prison terms in
history ''because of the defendant's failure to turn over all the
assets under his control.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Bennett, who was not in court, still lives on a 100-acre
horse farm and still controls a hotel. The family also retains an
interest in the Vernon Downs racetrack near Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, 47, was convicted last June on 42 counts including
securities fraud and laundering at least $1 billion as he cheated
about 10,000 investors of $700 million since 1990. Many of the
victims were elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ''My husband would have gotten a kick out of this,'' 84-year-old
Roslyn Levine said as she leaned on a cane after the sentencing.
''But unfortunately it killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine said her husband suffered a heart attack reviewing
paperwork relating to the $400,000 he lost.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence was announced just after Bennett, wearing his blue
prison uniform, blasted the judge for giving him the unusual
ultimatum a month ago. Bennett said the judge wanted him to
acknowledge that all his assets, including the home where his wife
lives, resulted from fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''I took this as a threat,'' Bennett said. He said forcing a
defendant who continues to maintain his innocence that he committed
the fraud was ''illegal, unethical and un-American.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Bennett used his company to entice investors
from 46 states into leases for office equipment that sometimes had
been bought with cash or did not exist. The company filed for
bankruptcy in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims lived in New Jersey, New York, Florida,
Pennsylvania, Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   The judge called the sentence appropriate, especially after
Bennett himself admitted on the witness stand that there was a
massive fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''People who are living in poverty see Mrs. Bennett on a horse
farm on assets derived from this fraud,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said Bennett's ''obstinate fraudulent conduct alone''
would justify the 30-year sentence, especially since Bennett had
done nothing to relieve the massive damage to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Continued use of assets by Bennett's family is conduct
controlled by Bennett, he said. ''To do that is to continue that
fraud day after day after day,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the brief sentencing, several investors who
attended congratulated prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today I celebrate. Thank you so much,'' said Walter Danz, 62,
of Long Beach, N.Y. as he shook the hand of Assistant U.S. Attorney
Patrick Smith.
</P>
<P>
   He said he lost $22,000, a significant part of his retirement
money from his years with the Department of Homeless Services for
the city of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather lose the money and see him get that extra 10 years
in prison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the length of the sentence will hold up on appeal is
in question, lawyers on both sides concede.
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. Pinnisi, lawyer for Bennett, said his client would
appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
