<HEADLINE> Vicki Sue Robinson, 1970s disco diva, dies of cancer  </HEADLINE>
dthofons
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILTON, Conn. (AP) -- Vicki Sue Robinson, whose 1976 hit ''Turn
The Beat Around,'' was among the disco anthems of that dancing
decade, has died of cancer. She was 46.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson died at her home in Wilton on Thursday. Her husband of
10 years, Bill Good, was at her side, said publicist Faith Fusillo.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a talented person. She also was a very, very decent
person,'' Fusillo said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fusillo said Robinson had been ill for several months with a
variety of cancer that eventually spread to her lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was born in Harlem to interracial parents, who were
both performers. Her father, Bill Robinson, who was black, was a
Shakespearean actor. Her mother, Marian, a white folk singer,
performed under the name Jolly Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Sue Robinson's influences ranged from the blues of Dinah
Washington to the folk stylings of Pete Seeger. She made her
singing debut at age 6 with her mother at the Philadelphia Folk
Festival. As a teen-ager, she appeared on Broadway in ''Hair'' and
''Jesus Christ Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   When she hit the recording studio, she struck gold with ''Turn
The Beat Around,'' one of the biggest hits of the disco era. She
was nominated for a Grammy Award for best female vocalist and
earned a Billboard Award for the No. 1 pop album.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson joined in a disco revival in the last few years,
touring with K.C. and the Sunshine Band, The Village People and
Gloria Gaynor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all pretty devastated,'' said Felipe Rose, who plays the
Indian in the Village People. ''It's not just her talent and her
voice and her being a pioneer of disco, but when we saw her she was
always up, always bubbly, always there for other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson returned to the stage last year, starring in the
off-Broadway musical, ''Behind The Beat.'' Illness forced her to
leave the show in April 1999, said Fusillo.
</P>
<P>
   She also lent her voice to several jingles in television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   She performed benefit concerts for a number of charitable
causes, including Broadway Cares/Equity Fights, AIDS, the homeless
and the Gay Men's Health Crisis. She also participated in a
mentoring program for children in Connecticut schools.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her husband and mother. Her father died when
she was 19.
</P>
<P>
   A private memorial service will be held May 4 at the Unitarian
Church in Westport.
------
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family request in lieu of flowers donations may be
made to the New York-based God's Love We Deliver, which provides
meals to homebound AIDs patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-28-00 1955 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000428.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upbeat NY Mayor Hits Campaign Trail  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Buoyed by New Yorkers' get-well wishes, an
upbeat Mayor Rudolph Giuliani returned to City Hall and the Senate
campaign trail Friday, a day after revealing he has prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A Long Island congressman who has had designs on the race said
he had telephoned Giuliani to say he wouldn't challenge him.
Giuliani's campaign said the mayor's Senate bid was proceeding
''full speed ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to an evening event in Saratoga, Giuliani
appeared on a TV talk show and attended a public hearing as members
of his camp put a positive spin on the prospects for his Senate
race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief news conference, Giuliani offered his thanks to
everyone who had offered him support.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people of New York City sort of have a reputation for
being sort of tough and have a reputation for being kind of
cynical,'' he said. ''But the reality is that they are the most
generous and the most loving in the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance on CBS' ''Early Show,'' Giuliani said his
campaign schedule would be ''a little lighter. I'll eliminate half
the events, or something like that.'' A campaign spokeswoman later
said the mayor expected the downturn to last for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican Rep. Rick Lazio said he had telephoned the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him that if he were a candidate for the Senate I would
not run, I would not challenge him,'' Lazio said. He said he called
the mayor because he did not want Giuliani's political concerns to
interfere with his health. Lazio refused to say what he would do if
the mayor bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had been gearing up last year to run for the Senate seat
being vacated by retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and had
raised a little over $3 million before Gov. George Pataki asked him
to step aside. Lazio suspended his bid but refused to officially
end it.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover-Weiss said Friday
that ''the mayor was appreciative'' of Lazio's phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the campaign's moving full steam ahead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who phoned her get-well wishes to Giuliani on Thursday,
was back in Washington on Friday, unveiling a study showing that
children who spend their early years in quality day care are less
likely to be arrested down the road.
</P>
