<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, April 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Urges Breakup of Microsoft
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the largest trust-busting move since AT&AMP;T, the
government asked a federal court today to break software giant Microsoft into
two companies. If accepted by a federal judge, the proposal would bar Microsoft
officers and directors, including billionaire co-founder Bill Gates, from owning
stock in more than one of the new companies. Under the government proposal,
Microsoft would be split into rival companies. One would produce its Windows
operating software, the other company would handle other software applications,
such as word processing, spreadsheet and database programs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Fallout Disrupts Miami
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami police chief resigned today in the Elian gonzalez
furor a day after the mayor fired the city manager. Stepping down, Police Chief
William O'Brien lashed out at Mayor Joe Carollo, who had criticized him for
failing to notify the mayor about the federal raid to seize the 6-year-old Cuban
refugee. ''I refuse to be the chief of police in a city that has someone as
divisive and destructive as Joe Carollo as mayor,'' O'Brien said. O'Brien said
he didn't want to tip off the mayor to the Elian raid because the mayor is
Cuban-American and had openly sided with the Miami relatives.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
5 Dead in Suburban Pa. Shootings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   McKEES ROCKS, Pa. (AP) -- A white man opened fire in two suburban Pittsburgh
shopping centers today, killing five people and critically wounding a sixth in
what police called a racially motivated shooting spree. Richard Baumhamers, who
was taken into custody, also was suspected of firing shots in two synagogues.
Two of the dead, both Asian, were shot at a Chinese restaurant in McKees Rocks,
while a black man was killed at a martial arts school in Monaca. Two other
people, both Indian, were shot at an Indian grocery in Carnegie, and one died,
police and hospital officials said. A Jewish woman also was found dead in her
Mount Lebanon home, and Baumhammers was suspected in her death, police said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Zimbabwe Farm Violence Deal Made
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Leaders of white farmers in Zimbabwe reached
agreement Friday with representatives of armed black squatters to end violent
clashes caused by the forcible occupation of white-owned farms. According to the
deal, squatters would peaceably continue to occupy more than 1,000 white-owned
farms, said an official with the Commercial Farmers Union. They also agreed that
the farmers should be able to work the land without hindrance from the
occupiers, many of whom claim to be veterans of the bush war that led to
Zimbabwe's independence in 1980.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vietnam, McCain Trade Angry Words
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) -- John McCain, on a journey meant to heal old
wounds, said Friday the wrong side won the Vietnam War, adding to earlier
comments that accused the communists of torturing POWs. Irritated by McCain's
remarks about torture, Hanoi accused the United States of ''horrendous crimes.''
McCain is in Vietnam to mark the 25th anniversary of the war's end and to help
boost U.S. ties with its former enemy. But that has not kept the former Navy
pilot from sharply criticizing the communist government's conduct in the war,
during which he was shot down and spent 5{ years in a Vietnamese prison.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Rules Against MP3.com in Copyright Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge today ruled the Internet-based music service MP3.com
is liable for infringing the copyrights of the nation's major record companies
by offering music online without permission. The order by U.S. District Judge
Jed Rakoff was the first significant ruling challenging the San Diego-based
company, which offers a service intended to let users listen to music on the
MP3.com Web site from CDs they already own. Other lawsuits nationwide seek to
help define the rules of how music will be played on the Internet, a venue that
did not exist when the vast majority of records and compact discs in circulation
were produced.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 154; Nasdaq Up 86
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell for a third straight session today,
but technology shares continued their recovery and drove the Nasdaq composite
index higher. At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 154.19
points to 10,733.91. The Nasdaq composite rose 86.63 to close at 3,860.66.
Advancers led decliners 1,731-1,221 on the NYSE.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Whitey Ford Again Battling Cancer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hall of Fame pitcher Whitey Ford said he missed New York
Yankees spring training for the first time in 49 years because he was completing
radiation treatment for an undisclosed form of cancer. The 71-year-old former
Yankees ace underwent cancer surgery 5{ years ago. He said today that his latest
cancer was diagnosed in November. Ford had been in uniform Yankees spring
training as a player, coach or guest every year since 1951, when he was in the
military.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
