<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets With Man He Pardoned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton met Friday with Preston
King, the Georgia man he pardoned for draft evasion 39 years after
King fled to England.
</P>
<P>
   King, a political science professor at Lancaster University in
England, came to the White House and sat in on Clinton's taping of
his weekly radio address. He told reporters later that he expressed
his appreciation to Clinton for pardoning him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was delighted to go in and meet with him,'' King said. ''I
don't want to comment further on it, simply to say that I'm
grateful that this has been resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   King, 63, says he fled his hometown of Albany, Ga., in 1961
after his local draft board addressed him as ''Mr. Preston King''
before learning he was black and ''Preston'' after that. He was
given an 18-month sentence for draft evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pardoned King in February so he could return home for
the funeral of his brother, Clennon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
