<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: Pinochet Too Ill for Trial  </HEADLINE>
By EDUARDO GALLARDO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A lawyer for Gen. Augusto Pinochet said
Friday the ex-dictator is too ill to stand trial and isn't even
aware of the human rights charges he might have to face.
</P>
<P>
   ''The health condition of Gen. Pinochet does not allow a fair
trial for him,'' lawyer Ricardo Rivadeneira told the Santiago Court
of Appeals, which is deliberating whether the former dictator must
be stripped of his immunity and put on trial for scores of killings
that occurred after his bloody 1973 coup against Chile's elected
government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Doctors do not allow him any contact with his lawyers and I
myself have not been able to talk to him,'' Rivadeneira said in the
second day of hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The deliberation has focused on actions of the ''caravan of
death,'' a group of military officers who visited many of the
nation's jails conducting about 75 executions of political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecution lawyer, Carmen Hertz, asked the court to allow the
trial of Pinochet. Under Chile's constitution, the former dictator
holds the title of ''senator for life,'' which exempts him from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   So far, seven lawyers for the plaintiffs have addressed the 22
judges of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Another lawyer supporting a trial, Juan Bustos, said the abuses
by Pinochet's 1973-90 regime were ''crimes against mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivadeneira made a long legal statement but he emphasized
Pinochet's deteriorated health as a reason to suspend the legal
action against him.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Pinochet was released from a 16-month confinement
in London and allowed to return home after British doctors said he
was mentally and physically unfit to stand trial anywhere in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Rivadeneira admitted that Chile's law is different and it only
exempts from penal responsibility those who are diagnosed with
madness or dementia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not saying that Gen. Panoche is mad or demented, but
doctors have not allowed him to be informed of the situation,'' he
added. ''Under these conditions, no fair trial is possible as he
cannot defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivadeneira renewed the request to have the court order medical
tests before allowing the hearings on immunity to continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 2045 </TRAILER>
