<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan To Repay Part of IMF Loans  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pakistan has agreed to repay $55 million it
borrowed from the International Monetary Fund last year to resolve
an investigation into allegations the country lied about its fiscal
situation in order to obtain the loans, the agency said late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Aninat, an IMF deputy managing director, said in a
statement that the Pakistan will repay the loan by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan revealed in early April that the government of former
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had understated its budget deficits to
the IMF in order to continue qualifying for IMF support.
</P>
<P>
   Aninat said that the true figures showed that Pakistan's budget
deficit was 7.5 percent of the country's total gross domestic
product for the 1997-98 period, 2 percentage points higher than
initially claimed.
</P>
<P>
   He said IMF officials viewed the misleading budget data with
''serious concern.'' It was the third recent case in which the IMF
has found that member countries had misled the agency in order to
obtain loans. The other cases involved Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   But the IMF said it was pleased that the discrepancies were
brought to light by the current government. Gen. Pervez Musharraf
took over Pakistan's government in a coup last October.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf cited Pakistan's economic turmoil as a key reason for
the coup. The military regime has promised to work for resumption
of IMF loans as a way to revive the country's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Observing that the discrepancies in the fiscal data had been
discovered by the current authorities themselves and had
immediately been brought to the attention of the IMF staff, (IMF)
directors commended the current authorities for their prompt and
full cooperation with the staff in the data revision process,''
Aninat said in his statement.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF said it believed the government had taken the proper
''remedial action'' with the offer to repay $55 million of the
loans the IMF had extended to the country based on the inaccurate
data.
</P>
<P>
   The 182-nation lending agency said it hoped to send an IMF
mission to Pakistan ''in the near future'' to begin discussions on
resuming IMF loans.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF in 1998 awarded Pakistan a $1.6 billion emergency loan
package, to be released in installments, to help the country deal
with a severe financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That loan program was suspended last year while Sharif was still
in power because of an IMF finding that his administration was not
moving quickly enough to implement promised economic reforms. The
IMF loan conditions included broadening the tax base as a way to
increase revenues to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's economy, which is heavily dependent on foreign aid
and loans, was pushed to the brink of default on $32 billion in
foreign debt in 1998 when Western countries imposed sanctions to
punish the country for nuclear tests it conducted in May 1998 in
response to nuclear tests by neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
   The United States later eased sanctions it had imposed on both
countries, paving the way for the IMF bailout package for Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
