<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday, April 28, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Despite Plan, Microsoft May Still Dominate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Even if Microsoft is broken up, its products might continue
to dominate the market, even if they come from separate companies. Under a plan
submitted to a federal judge by the Justice Department and 17 states, Microsoft
would be divided into one company that would produce the Windows operating
system and another that would make software programs such as the Microsoft
Office suite of spreadsheet, word processing and other business applications.
The immediate impact of the remedies could come within months as computer
makers, no longer required to adhere to Microsoft's previous business practices,
begin making custom alterations to the way Windows is presented to the customer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miami Police Chief Resigns
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- A day after the Miami mayor fired the city manager, the police
chief resigned today amid the Elian Gonzalez furor. Stepping down, Police Chief
William O'Brien lashed out at Mayor Joe Carollo, who had criticized him for
failing to notify the mayor about the federal raid to seize the 6-year-old Cuban
refugee. "I refuse to be the chief of police in a city that has someone as
divisive and destructive as Joe Carollo as mayor," O'Brien said. O'Brien said he
didn't want to tip off the mayor to the Elian raid because the mayor is
Cuban-American and had openly sided with the Miami relatives.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
5 Dead in Suburban Pa. Shootings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   McKEES ROCKS, Pa. (AP) -- A white man opened fire in several Pittsburgh
communities today, killing five people and critically wounding a sixth in what
police called a racially motivated shooting spree. The man was taken into
custody. The shootings took place within a 20-mile range through suburbs
surrounding Pittsburgh during about an hour span this afternoon. The gunman
fatally shot a person of Indian descent at an Indian grocery store, two
employees at a Chinese restaurant and a black man at a martial arts school. A
Jewish woman who lived next door to the suspect's relatives was found dead in
her home. The suspect, Richard Baumhammers, 34, was jailed in Center Township
awaiting arraignment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Zimbabwe Farm Violence Deal Made
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Leaders of white farmers in Zimbabwe reached
agreement Friday with representatives of armed black squatters to end violent
clashes caused by the forcible occupation of white-owned farms. According to the
deal, squatters would peaceably continue to occupy more than 1,000 white-owned
farms, said an official with the Commercial Farmers Union. They also agreed that
the farmers should be able to work the land without hindrance from the
occupiers, many of whom claim to be veterans of the bush war that led to
Zimbabwe's independence in 1980.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Uncle Sam Wants Your Census Form
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Census officials say extra efforts of "enumerators" who
canvas neighborhoods looking for people who haven't filled out their census form
is crucial for an accurate count. While 65 percent of households nationally
mailed in their census forms, only 59 percent of Chicagoans and 58 percent of
New Yorkers returned theirs, and getting other big cities to return them is a
tall order. Census officials estimate 12.5 percent of American Indians on
reservations were missed in 1990, making them the most undercounted minority in
the nation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kellogg Altered Food Proposal Nixed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- Kellogg Co. shareholders overwhelmingly rejected
a proposal to force the cereal maker to stop using genetically altered crops,
despite claims from two groups of nuns that the crops are unsafe and put the
company at risk for lawsuits. Some 94 percent voted against the proposal.
Kellogg is in the process of removing genetically altered ingredients from its
products in Europe and Australia, where there has been increasing consumer
backlash over the safety over genetically altered crops. But the company has
declined to do the same in North America, citing a lack of consumer interest and
insufficient scientific evidence.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 154; Nasdaq Up 86
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell for a third straight session today,
but technology shares continued their recovery and drove the Nasdaq composite
index higher. At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 154.19
points to 10,733.91. The Nasdaq composite rose 86.63 to close at 3,860.66.
Advancers led decliners 1,731-1,221 on the NYSE.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Whitey Ford Again Battling Cancer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hall of Fame pitcher Whitey Ford said he missed New York
Yankees spring training for the first time in 49 years because he was completing
radiation treatment for an undisclosed form of cancer. The 71-year-old former
Yankees ace underwent cancer surgery 5 1/2 years ago. He said today that his
latest cancer was diagnosed in November. Ford had been in uniform Yankees spring
training as a player, coach or guest every year since 1951, when he was in the
military.
</P>
