<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Potential in UN Gets Boost  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The European Union has circulated its
terms for Israel's admission into a U.N. grouping of mostly
European countries -- a key step in efforts to boost Israel's
participation at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the terms, which were obtained Thursday, it
could still be years before Israel is allowed to sit on any U.N.
committees, such as the powerful Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is the only U.N. member state that isn't part of a
regional group, which prevents it from being nominated for
committee membership.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Israel has been lobbying the Western European and
Others Group for admission because it faced such political
opposition from what would be its natural regional group of Middle
Eastern and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   While backed by the United States in its campaign, Israel ran
into opposition from several European countries. Earlier this year,
however, Spain reversed its opposition and decided to back Israel's
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Several EU committees then followed suit, leading to a final set
of terms from the EU that was formally presented to the rest of the
so-called WEOG group at U.N. headquarters on Tuesday, western
diplomats said, speaking on conditions of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   According to a copy of the terms, the EU said it accepts
Israel's temporary membership of the WEOG group in New York, which
includes western European countries, Canada, the United States,
Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The terms say Israel couldn't seek nomination for any committee
for two years, and that it couldn't upset the rotation schedule for
committees that has already been worked out among the existing
members. That could prevent Israel from sitting on the Security
Council for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Calls seeking comment from the Israeli mission were unsuccessful
Thursday. The mission is closed for the Passover holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Antonio Monteiro of Portugal, which holds the
rotating EU presidency, wouldn't discuss the details of the EU
proposals he presented Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
