<HEADLINE> Form Black Panther's Settlement OKd  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal judge on Friday approved the $4.5
million settlement of a civil rights lawsuit by former Black
Panther Geronimo Pratt, who spent 25 years in prison before his
murder conviction was overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both the city of Los Angeles and the federal government
stepped up to the plate and reached a fair settlement,'' said
attorney Johnnie Cochran, who represented Pratt during nearly 30
years of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, 53, was convicted in 1972 of robbing and shooting to
death schoolteacher Caroline Olsen on a Santa Monica tennis court
in 1968. The conviction was overturned in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt always maintained he was framed by a government informant
because of his activities with the Black Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement approved by U.S. District Judge Christina
Snyder, the city will pay $2.75 million, which must be approved by
the city council, and the FBI will pay $1.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, a decorated Vietnam War veteran, lives in his hometown of
Morgan City, La., where he uses the name Geronimo ji Jaga.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a case about money,'' Cochran said. ''Geronimo was
never interested in things like money. He's interested in
justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
