<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget in turmoil over Adriaen's Landing impasse  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state budget was thrown into turmoil
Friday night when the Adriaen's Landing development plan hit an
impasse over labor issues and the project's main private backer
threatened to pull out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Pagani, a spokesman for Gov. John G. Rowland, said the
agreement reached Thursday between Rowland and legislative leaders
on a $12.3 billion budget was in limbo because of the clash.
</P>
<P>
   The House had been expected to approve the budget Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The budget is not going forward tomorrow,'' Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
   Pagani said the Rowland would not sign a declaration needed to
use the state's surplus as part of the budget. The surplus has been
woven into the budget deal.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland and leading lawmakers had agreed that a bill to sink
$455 million into the Adriaen's Landing project would be OK'd
before the budget would be voted on, Pagani said. The project was
set for a vote Friday. Bur Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin
Sullivan postponed the debate when some senators insisted the
development package include a guarantee that workers in the planned
hotel would be allowed to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterford Group -- the major investment group in the
Adriaen's Landing project-- planned to pull out of the deal if that
promise was made, Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Waterford Group will not be able to be a part of the
project,'' he said. ''And the result of that would be the collapse
of the (project).''
</P>
<P>
   The Adriaen's Landing plan includes a 700-room hotel, a
convention center, entertainment and retail space and nearly 400
housing units on Hartford's waterfront. Also part of the package is
a $90 million stadium in East Hartford for the University of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,400 construction jobs and more than 1,100 permanent jobs
are expected to be created.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel and Restaurant Employees Union, which is under the
umbrella of the AFL-CIO, has been lobbying for the guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot support in my district a project where over $700
million will be poured in and people making beds and cleaning
toilets are making $6 and $7 an hour,'' said Sen. John Fonfara,
D-Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Pagani said the deal already allows the workers to unionize, and
said the AFL-CIO was jockeying to make sure they would be the only
union to represent the employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''The leadership is going back on its word,'' he said.
''Everything was set to go until they caved into the AFL-CIO on
these unreasonable demands.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterford Group, which has developed the Mohegan Sun casino
in Montville and operates hotels in Mystic, New London and Norwich,
has said it will spend $20 million to build the hotel at Adriaen's
Landing.
</P>
<P>
   Fonfara and labor advocates said the company pays its hotel
workers about $10,000 a year less than the Goodwin Hotel in
Hartford and the Hartford Hilton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly must decide whether to sink about $455
million of public money into the project, which will cost more than
$771 million. The public funding portion of the project is
contingent on a commitment of $210 million in private financing.
Gov. John G. Rowland has said that threshold has been met.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin Sullivan said Democrats were
divided over promising union jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a basic concern that permeates the entire caucus about
the quality of jobs that will come with this project,'' said
Sullivan, D-West Hartford. ''There's a wide diversity of opinion as
to how best to come to that outcome and not sacrifice the
opportunity to get the jobs in the first place. At some point
there's either no jobs, or these jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he would vote for the spending plan without union
guarantees for the hotel workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If people who live in Hartford are not getting good paying
jobs, what's the point of this whole project,'' said Sen. Edith
Prague, D-Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader George Jepsen said both sides will have
to budge in order to save the project.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're at a classic impasse,'' said Jepsen, D-Stamford. ''I
wish the Wolmans would give in a little more, and I wish the unions
would give a little more flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans blamed Democrats for holding up the project,
which has been a major cause for Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   ''Republicans have always been accused of being insensitive to
the big cities,'' said Sen. Louis DeLuca, R-Woodbury. ''Here we
have a project that the governor wants to do for a city,
Republicans are ready and willing to support the governor to help
Hartford. The Democrats seem to have a problem with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
