<HEADLINE> Visitation Set in Switched Baby Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENA VISTA, Va. (AP) -- The biological mother of one of two
little girls switched at birth and sent home with the wrong
families was granted monthly visitation rights with her natural
daughter on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A court last month approved a custody agreement that leaves
4-year-olds Callie Conley and Rebecca Chittum with the families who
raised them and grants their biological relatives visitation
rights.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Juvenile and Domestic Relations Judge John Curry II
set a regular schedule for Paula Johnson, who has been raising
Callie, to see her natural daughter, Rebecca.
</P>
<P>
   According to the judge's schedule, Johnson will have Rebecca at
least one weekend per month and visitation during holidays will be
divided, said Mike Groot, an attorney for Rebecca's guardians,
Larry and Rosa Chittum.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also granted a visitation request by Rebecca's
biological father, Carlton Conley, but did not set a schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Callie and Rebecca were sent home with the wrong families
shortly after their births at the University of Virginia Medical
Center in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson learned of the mistake three years later when she sued
Conley for child support. The couple raising Rebecca, Whitney
Rogers and Kevin Chittum, died in a car crash before they learned
the truth. Their parents are now raising Rebecca.
</P>
<P>
   Groot said he was pleased with the judge's decisions, adding,
''The Chittums are committed to doing what's best for Rebecca.''
</P>
</TEXT>
