<HEADLINE> Pro-Israel Militiamen Die in Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By ZEINA KARAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon -- Guerrillas detonated a car bomb near an
outpost of a pro-Israeli militia Friday, killing three militiamen
in an attack that heightened tension in the run-up to Israel's
planned withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli military spokesman in Jerusalem said one militiaman
was killed and four others wounded, three seriously, and two other
militiamen were buried under the rubble of the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the SLA said the corpses of the two militiamen had
been recovered from the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   One guerrilla was killed in the attacks, Hezbollah said in a
statement issued in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle blast was one of several attacks by the Hezbollah
guerrillas on military positions in the Israeli-occupied zone,
Lebanese and Israeli security officials said. One soldier was flown
to Israel for treatment of wounds sustained in an attack, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel retaliated with a series of airstrikes on suspected
guerrilla hideouts in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese officials said there were seven air raids; Israeli
officials said there were four. The difference is thought to be
explained by warplanes hitting several targets on a single mission.
</P>
<P>
   The upsurge in hostilities came after a week of diplomatic
efforts aimed at smoothing Israel's expected July 7 troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In the bomb attack, the guerrillas, backed by rocket and machine
gun fire, drove a vehicle up to a position of the South Lebanon
Army militia in Aramta. The guerrillas detonated the vehicle's
explosives as they retreated, Lebanese security officials said.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli military spokesman in Jerusalem said one militiaman
was killed and four others wounded, three seriously, and two other
militiamen were buried under the rubble of the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah said its fighters teamed up with
another allied group, the Lebanese Resistance Brigades, to storm
the Aramta position and plant explosives. It did not refer to the
car bomb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
