<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Davis Attends Practice  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The Denver Broncos opened their three-day
mini-camp late Friday morning. Terrell Davis made a
much-anticipated entrance 90 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   It was the running back's first practice since undergoing major
knee surgery in October.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt nervous today and a lot of things went through my mind
when I was out there practicing,'' the six-year veteran said. ''But
once I got out there, I said I wasn't going to think about it, just
practice. I got a little fatigued toward the end, but it still felt
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Davis became only the fourth player in NFL history to
rush for 2,000 yards in a season. His 1999 season ended when he
tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee in the fourth
game.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was trying to tackle Victor Green of the New York Jets and
was injured when teammate Matt Lepsis crashed into his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a major goal for me, to come out and at least try and
test it out,'' said Davis who gained 211 yards on 67 carries last
season.
</P>
<P>
   He said his goal Friday was ''to come back and at least get
bumped around, get hit and see how it responded and it responded
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis warmed up with the team then joined the rest of the
running backs and wide receivers in a leisurely passing drill where
the first pass thrown his way, a 10-yarder over the middle from
rookie Jarious Jackson, sailed 10 yards beyond his reach.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the backs ran routine running plays that required tight,
quick cutback moves. Davis said he ran pain-free.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything went well and the way I wanted it to be,'' Davis
said. ''If I am out there, I might as well put myself through some
game-type situations rather than babying the knee, which wouldn't
do anything for me.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was just a test and I told myself that I was going to
take strides and the steps necessary in trying to come back and
this was just another major step that I took.''
</P>
<P>
   On one play, linebacker Bill Romanowski knocked Davis off his
feet. Davis bounced right up and exchanged comments with Romanowksi
before returning to the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's good. I didn't mind that,'' Davis said. ''I was a
little ticked off, but I had to keep my composure.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added that he has decided not to wear a protective knee
brace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made up my mind a long time ago that I didn't plan on
wearing a brace at all,'' Davis said. ''It restricts you from doing
things. It reminds you of the injury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 2124 </TRAILER>
