<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Appeal Court Upholds Senator Eric Berntson's Fraud Conviction
<TEXT>
<P>
   REGINA, Saskatchewan (AP) -- Senator Eric Berntson's fraud
conviction and one-year jail sentence have been upheld by
Saskatchewan's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   The split decision was released Friday by the Saskatchewan Court
of Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Berntson, 58, was found guilty in March 1999 of defrauding
Saskatchewan taxpayers when he was deputy premier in the
Conservative government of Grant Devine.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to a year in jail and ordered to pay back the
$42,000 in false claims he made on government expense allowances
from 1987 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ----
Federal AIDS-Prevention Pamphlet Condoning Injection Drugs Sparks
Debate
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The federal Health Department has sparked sharp
debate with a health pamphlet that appears to endorse injection
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just because we've made the choice that we don't want AIDS
doesn't mean the party's over,'' says the AIDS-prevention pamphlet,
which is being distributed at health clinics, schools and
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can still fool around with sex and have a great time. Still
shoot up if that's what we're into.''
</P>
<P>
   The pamphlet, which carries the logos of Health Canada and the
Canadian AIDS Society, provides detailed instructions for having
safe sex and cleaning needles.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Papadopoulos, executive director of the Toronto-based
Association of Local Public Health Agencies, said he was startled
by the wording of the pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   A Health Canada spokesman said the pamphlet doesn't condone such
behavior
</P>
<P>
   ''It's simply acknowledging it does occur,'' said Michael
Jacino, marketing adviser to the Canadian Strategy on HIV-AIDS at
Health Canada.
Fishermen Want Lobsters, Not Trouble, as Spring Season Opens
</P>
<P>
   BURNT CHURCH, New Brunswick (AP) -- Fishermen in northern New
Brunswick say they'll be looking for lobsters, not trouble, when
they set their traps today in Miramichi Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The lobster fishery opens in various parts of the Maritimes this
morning, but most of the attention will be focused on the Burnt
Church area on New Brunswick's northeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
   Native and non-native fishermen clashed here last fall after
members of the Burnt Church First Nation took advantage of a
Supreme Court of Canada decision that said the Mi'kmaq and Maliseet
people have a treaty right to earn a moderate living from fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Burnt Church reserve has turned down a deal from Ottawa for
an interim fisheries agreement that would impose federal
regulations in return for financial and training incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of an agreement, there's a feeling in Burnt
Church that the spring season will go well and there won't be any
confrontations.
Klein Daughter Reported Assault To Get Her Addict Husband Behind
Bars
</P>
<P>
   DRUMHELLER, Alberta (AP) -- A daughter of Alberta Premier Ralph
Klein says she made up an assault complaint against her husband
because she thought jail might keep him away from crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Klein-Marcia, 36, received a conditional discharge Friday
on a mischief charge that stemmed from the assault complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Provincial court Judge Gordon Clozza also ordered probation for
12 months, counseling and 100 hours of community service work. If
Klein-Marcia meets those conditions, she will have no criminal
record.
</P>
<P>
   Klein-Marcia sat silently in court while Crown prosecutor Sheila
Brown read from an agreed statement of facts in which the accused
said imprisonment might protect her husband from his cocaine
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   The judge warned that false accusations can undermine progress
being made in getting women to report domestic abuse but said he
understood Klein-Marcia acted out of desperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
