<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Gore Talks to Gay Rights Group  </HEADLINE>
By REBECCA SINDERBRAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tipper Gore told a gay rights advocacy group
Friday night that an administration headed by her husband would
''stand with you, and if necessary, fight with you.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to encourage all Americans to embrace gay and lesbian
children as their own and let them know they are loved, they are
respected, they are valued,'' said Mrs. Gore, wife of Vice
President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, Mrs. Gore urged passage of the Hate Crimes
Prevention Act and the Employment Nondiscrimination Act now before
Congress. Both measures include protection against those targeted
because of sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   She said that if elected ''my husband is committed to working
with you to explore how domestic partners can receive the legal and
economic benefits that other couples receive.''
</P>
<P>
   The line received hearty applause, though several audience
members noted that she stopped short of using the word
''marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paul Beeman, president of Parents, Families and Friends
of Lesbians and Gays, told Mrs. Gore that many in the audience
''realize that you're feeling a bit cramped in the home where you
live and might want to be making a move downtown soon.'' The
comment drew a standing ovation from the 900 or so people crammed
in the small hotel ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The group is holding its annual convention in the Washington
area on the eve of this weekend's Millennium March for gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''She'd make a great first lady,'' Sue Stewart, a PFLAG member
from Mountain View, Calif., said of Mrs. Gore. ''I'd vote for her --
I mean him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
