<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stolen Chamberlain Ball Yields $500K  </HEADLINE>
By MARV SCHNEIDER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Kerry Ryman was awakened from a sound sleep
Friday. His barber was calling to tell him the famed Wilt
Chamberlain basketball Ryman ran off with 38 years ago had been
sold at auction for $551,844.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the first I heard of it,'' Ryman said from his
apartment in Annville, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Leland's auction house refused to say who bought the ball used
by Chamberlain when he scored an NBA record 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a well-known figure out of the sports world,'' Leland's
spokesman Marty Appel said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryman, a 52-year-old crane operator, insisted he wasn't overly
interested to learn whether the ball had been sold.
</P>
<P>
   The price exceeded the rosiest of estimates by about $400,000.
Only two other pieces of sports memorabilia have sold at auction
for more -- Mark McGwire's 70th home run ball for $3.05 million and
a 1910 Honus Wagner card for $640,500.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just glad to have the thing out my hands,'' Ryman said.
</P>
<P>
   The record game in Hershey, Pa., was played on March 2, 1962.
Ryman said he shook Chamberlain's hand, grabbed the ball and outran
an arena security guard, scaling a fence during his getaway.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not something I'm proud of,'' Ryman said. ''I was 14 and
I made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   As Annville and environs awakened to radio reports of his big
score, Ryman's phone rang constantly. Not all calls were answered.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't congratulate someone for something they should not
have done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ball was sold officially at 3 a.m., the time set by Leland's
for closing the first half of its two-day sale of some 1,500 sports
memorabilia items.
</P>
<P>
   The auction was conducted by phone, fax and e-mail, all coming
in to the company's office in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Leland president Josh Evans had estimated the ball would go for
as much as $150,000. That figure was surpassed by midnight. By 1
a.m. the bidding was down to three serious contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was talk to one, put the others on hold, talk to another,
put the others on hold ... hold, talk, hold, talk,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   One bidder dropped out, then another, and finally one was left.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever did buy the ball has no worry about being caught with
stolen merchandise. Neither does Ryman. The statute of limitations
ran out in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain died last October, and when Ryman made off with the
ball, the 7-foot-1 center rejected an offer by a security guard who
wanted to go to Ryman's home to retrieve the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Ryman will wind up with less than $500,000. Leland's will
receive a 15 percent commission that totals $82,650 plus a
negotiable seller's fee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't feel the need to try to radically change my life,''
said Ryman, who makes about $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am content with my job and my life. I would have given the
ball to charity but I would never have been able to make sure the
money was actually put to good use. Now, I have direct control of
the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of it will go to charity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamberlain ball, by far, was the hit of the first day's
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Williams' uniform from 1941, when he batted .406, sold for
$120,097. A game-used Lou Gehrig cap went for $75,386.
</P>
<P>
   The ball that Mookie Wilson hit through Bill Buckner's legs in
Game 6 of the 1986 World Series, a part of actor Charlie Sheen's
collection, fetched $63,945. It was bought by Seth Swirsky, a
songwriter and author in Beverly Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that ball is one of the few pieces in sports history
that every single fan knows where they were when that play
happened,'' Swirsky said. ''It's a part of sports folklore.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I grew up in New York and love the Mets, and that helped,
too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth's last will and testament sold for $31,971, and his
1916 World Series award for $62,618. Prices include a 15 percent
buyer's premium.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the Chamberlain ball is not the most valuable in
terms of memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Michael Jordan's last shot before retiring,'' he said. ''That
ball is worth $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http:// www.lelands.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
