<HEADLINE> Tentative Deal in Janitors Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A tentative contract agreement was reached Friday
night that could end a 10-day strike by 4,500 janitors who work at
suburban office buildings, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Janitors will vote Monday on the proposal, details of which were
being withheld until the vote, said Ken Munz, spokesman for Local 1
of the Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   Barry White, a spokesman for the Suburban Contractors
Association, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout began April 18 with 500 workers leaving their
cleaning jobs. The so-called rolling strike added a few hundred
workers at a time over the last several days.
</P>
<P>
   The strikers, making $6.65 an hour, were asking for raises and
employer-paid family health insurance. Their old pact expired April
9.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of no new negotiations, the union had threatened to
set up picket lines at downtown buildings, with city janitors
agreeing to honor the lines.
</P>
<P>
   In separate talks, 5,500 downtown janitors ratified a new
contract April 18 after staging a one-night walkout. And in Los
Angeles, thousands of striking janitors approved a new contract
April 24, ending a three-week walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities also face walkouts. A union local in San Diego is
on strike and contracts in Oakland, Calif.; Silicon Valley, Calif.;
Cleveland and Seattle will expire within the next few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
