<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, April 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Urges Breakup of Microsoft
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government asked a federal court today to break
software giant Microsoft into two companies in the largest trust-busting move
since AT&AMP;T was carved into seven Baby Bells. If accepted by a federal judge, the
proposal would bar Microsoft officers and directors, including billionaire
co-founder Bill Gates, from owning stock in more than one of the new companies.
Under the government proposal, Microsoft would be split into rival companies.
One would produce its Windows operating software, the source of Microsoft's
monopoly power, according to a court filing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Five Dead in Suburban Pa. Shootings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   McKEES ROCKS, Pa. (AP) -- A white man opened fire in several Pittsburgh
communities today, killing five people and critically wounding a sixth in what
police called a racially motivated shooting spree. The man was taken into
custody. The shootings took place within a 20-mile range through suburbs
surrounding Pittsburgh during about an hour span this afternoon. The gunman
fatally shot a person of Indian descent at an Indian grocery store, two
employees at a Chinese restaurant and a black man at a martial arts school. A
Jewish woman who lived next door to the suspect's relatives was found dead in
her home. The suspect, Richard Baumhammers, 34, a lawyer, was charged with
criminal homicide and reckless endangerment. He was being held without bail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
INS Agent Defends Tactics of Elian Raid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Immigration and Naturalization Service agent who led the
raid to remove Elian Gonzalez defended the tactics today, saying force was
necessary given the presence of people who had ''vowed to prevent Elian's
recovery.'' ''This was the most challenging execution of a federal search
warrant,'' Agent James Goldman told The Associated Press. The agents worried
they'd be met by armed supporters of the Miami branch of the Gonzalez family.
Crowds had kept vigil outside the home, often swelling into the hundreds.
Federal investigators identified more than 20 people around the home as being
members of paramilitary groups, security companies, or ''individuals that had
vowed to prevent Elian's recovery by the federal government,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pro-Israel Militiamen Die in Lebanon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon -- Guerrillas detonated a car bomb near an outpost of a
pro-Israeli militia Friday, killing three militiamen in an attack that
heightened tension in the run-up to Israel's planned withdrawal from southern
Lebanon. An Israeli military spokesman in Jerusalem said one militiaman was
killed and four others wounded, three seriously, and two other militiamen were
buried under the rubble of the outpost. Late Friday, the SLA said the corpses of
the two militiamen had been recovered from the ruins. One guerrilla was killed
in the attacks, Hezbollah said in a statement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Backlash Casts Pall on Biotech Spuds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- One of the nation's largest potato processors is turning
away from genetically altered spuds, saying its fast-food customers don't want
them in their fryers. Idaho's J.R. Simplot Co. told its growers in Idaho and
North Dakota that, while it believes biotechnology is important for agriculture
and providing affordable food, it has to respect the preferences of the
fast-food chains it serves. Its largest customer is McDonald's. A spokesman said
less than 4 percent of the potatoes used in the McDonald's North American
restaurants come from genetically altered seed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Journalist Detained in Vietnam
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tucker Carlson, a reporter for the conservative magazine
The Weekly Standard and a CNN political commentator, was detained briefly by
Vietnamese authorities in Ho Chi Minh City, who questioned his travel documents,
a spokeswoman for the magazine said Friday. Carlson, 30, was part of a group of
reporters covering the Vietnam visit of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who was a
prisoner of war for over five years. A State Department spokesman said Friday
night that Vietnamese authorities had told them Carlson was free to leave the
country as soon as he arranged transportation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 154; Nasdaq Up 86
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell for a third straight session today,
but technology shares continued their recovery and drove the Nasdaq composite
index higher. At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 154.19
points to 10,733.91. The Nasdaq composite rose 86.63 to close at 3,860.66.
Advancers led decliners 1,731-1,221 on the NYSE.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pirates Beat Reds 2-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Kris Benson limited Cincinnati to five hits in eight
innings as the Pittsburgh Pirates beat the Reds 2-1 tonight. Benson (1-3) didn't
allow a hit until Benito Santiago singled with one out in the fifth. The
right-hander struck out six and walked three. Mike Williams got the final two
outs for his third save.
</P>
