<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upbeat Giuliani hits City Hall, campaign trail  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani told upstate voters Friday that he still ''wants to be
Senator'' but needs more time to make his decision in light of his
cancer diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be a senator because I was born in this state,
because I worked for the state,'' Giuliani told about 1000
supporters at a $50 a plate dinner in Saratoga Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was greeted with standing ovations and cheers at the
event hosted by the Saratoga County Women's Republican Club. It was
his first campaign appearance since he announced Thursday that he
was diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief question and answer session before the event,
Giuliani said he ''needs a little more than a day and a half''
before he could make any decision on the race against the first
lady.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I need the next week, 10 days, maybe two weeks, to figure out
the proper course of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to do that and than I'm going to make a decision and
whether I can or cannot campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who he would support if he decides not to run,
Giuliani said, ''I'm not going to get into that. I know who I don't
want to support.''
</P>
<P>
   During the speech, Giuliani told voters he's going to meet with
doctors in the upcoming weeks to determine a course of treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully I'll be able to do that and run and give you the
kind of candidate you deserve.'' Giuliani said, drawing a round of
applause.
</P>
<P>
   While not mentioning his opponent by name, Giuliani again
attacked the Clinton administration in his speech, charging the
president's decision to bomb Iraq late in 1998 over Saddam
Hussein's weapons inspection was a ''Clintonian'' victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clintonian words do not mean what they say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, also at the event,
said he's ''confident that (Giuliani) will do what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll have a lot of support,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saratoga Springs, Giuliani appeared on a national morning
talk show and attended a public hearing as members of his camp put
a positive spin on the prospects for his U.S. Senate race against
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief news conference, Giuliani offered his thanks to
everyone who had offered him support after his stunning
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people of New York City sort of have a reputation for
being sort of tough and have a reputation for being kind of
cynical,'' he said. ''But the reality is that they are the most
generous and the most loving in the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance on the CBS ''Early Show,'' Giuliani said his
campaign schedule would be ''a little lighter. I'll eliminate half
the events, or something like that.'' A campaign spokeswoman later
said the mayor expected the downturn to last for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The first cancellations were two speeches before lawyers' groups
scheduled for Monday -- one in Syracuse, the other in Rochester --
commemorating Law Day. Both were originally set up as part of
Giuliani's mayoral duties, not his Senate campaign, the spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani spokeswoman Sunny Mindel said the mayor needed time to
consult with physicians on the course of his treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A Saturday appearance in Buffalo was still on.
</P>
<P>
   State GOP Chairman William Powers, in an Albany radio interview,
said that he had spoken with the mayor and was convinced that
Giuliani would press on.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll rise to the occasion,'' Powers said. Giuliani's campaign
also announced the start of a massive direct mail campaign, and the
purchase of ad space on television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, the 55-year-old Giuliani received the gift of
get-well cannolis fresh from a Staten Island bakery. City
Councilman James Oddo, R-S.I., told Giuliani that ''my mother is
setting record laps on the rosary on your behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani took a bite of the cannoli and posed for pictures
during the public hearing. ''The cannolis look great,'' Giuliani
said. ''Cannolis cure everything.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, the mayor, who has received hundreds of
calls from well-wishers, returned many of those including one to
Yankees Manager JoeTorre, who had surgery for prostate cancer last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you hear the word cancer, it's frightening. It's still
frightening, but cancer is no longer a death sentence. That has to
be first and foremost in your mind,'' Torre said later during a
pre-game media availability at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He said the mayor seemed in good spirits, and that the only
advice Torre offered Giuliani was that he should listen to his
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mayor's other callers Friday were former Sen. Bob
Dole; Republican Presidential nominee George W. Bush; Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak; and Jerusalem Mayor Ehud Olmert.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who phoned her get-well wishes to Giuliani on Thursday,
was back in Washington on Friday, unveiling a study showing that
children who spend their early years in quality day care are less
likely to be arrested down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign spokesman also said Clinton has decided to join
Giuliani in courting support from the New York arm of the Reform
Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
