<HEADLINE> Soldier Said in US Custody in SKorea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korean police said Saturday they
have handed over to U.S. authorities an American soldier who was
captured after he fled hours before he was to go on trial for
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Spc. Christopher K. McCarthy, 21, of Concord, N.H., broke out of
U.S. military custody and fled from the U.S. military command in
Seoul on Friday before he was to appear in a South Korean court.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean police captured him eight hours later at Itaewon
near the U.S. military command. He was handed over to U.S.
authorities late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean television footage showed the American soldier,
handcuffed and wearing a jogging suit, sitting on a bench at a
South Korean police station. He looked nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Under an accord governing the treatment of 37,000 U.S. soldiers
stationed here, South Korean police are required to put U.S.
soldiers accused of crimes in U.S. custody pending trial.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy is charged with the beating death of a 31-year-old bar
waitress, identified by police only by her surname, Kim, in Seoul
on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested three days later and told investigators that he
hit the woman because she refused to have sex with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
