<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressBill Beckham:
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETORIT (AP) -- Bill Beckham, a longtime crusader for improving
education and race relations in Detroit, died Thursday of a
pulmonary embolism that led to cardiac arrest. He was 58.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Beckham was appointed by Mayor Dennis Archer to serve
on the city's seven-member school reform board. He also was
appointed president and chief executive officer of the Skillman
Foundation in Detroit, where he worked with groups to improve
relationships between children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   Before his position at Skillman, Beckham served as president of
the New Detroit Inc., a coalition created to promote better race
relations between city and suburbs after the 1967 riots.
</P>
<P>
   After college, Beckham worked as a staff assistant to the late
Democratic Sen. Phil Hart, oversaw the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission as a congressional staffer and later, as deputy mayor
under Coleman Young, monitored the reorganization of the police
department.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Beckham served in the Carter administration
as assistant secretary of Treasury and deputy secretary of
transportation. He also was vice president of Unisys Corp. before
returning to Detroit.
Ron Boland:
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Newspaperman Ron Boland, who helped
Rupert Murdoch build one of the world's largest media empires, died
Wednesday following a stroke. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Boland was editor of Adelaide's The Sunday Mail when Murdoch
inherited it and its sister publication, the daily tabloid the
News, in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   They were Murdoch's first papers, his training ground and the
starting point from which he built his global newspaper, satellite
television, film and book publishing company.
</P>
<P>
   Boland was managing editor at the News in 1960, when the
ambitious young Murdoch bought the Sydney Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two sons.
Jerzy Einhorn:
</P>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Jerzy Einhorn, who survived a Nazi
concentration camp and became a cancer specialist at a research
hospital in Sweden, died Friday of leukemia. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn revolutionized cancer care in Sweden as director of
Karolinska Hospital's radiotherapy department from 1967 until
retirement in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Einhorn helped develop regional cancer centers
that integrated treatment of all aspects of the disease. He also
worked on a political level to garner resources for cancer
treatment and research.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn, who was born in Czestochowa, Poland, was forced into a
Nazi concentration camp as a young man after Adolf Hitler's forces
occupied the country in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn wrote two books about his life, and worked to promote
the memory of the Holocaust and to fight the rise of neo-Nazism in
his adopted country.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn was on the board of many international cancer
organizations, and published many scientific works.
Robert C. Jeffrey:
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Robert C. Jeffrey, retired dean of the
University of Texas College of Communication, died Wednesday
following a lengthy illness. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Through his work as dean, Jeffrey secured $6 million from the
Houston Endowment Inc., which has provided money for conferences,
faculty development, endowed scholarships and fellowships.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the communication studies department honored Jeffrey
with a dinner to raise money for an endowed scholarship in his
name.
Brooks Lawrence:
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ohio (AP) -- Brooks Lawrence, who pitched for the
St. Louis Cardinals and Cincinnati Reds and worked in the Reds'
front office, died Thursday of cancer. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence was 69-62 with a 4.25 earned run average in two seasons
with the Cardinals (1954-55) and five with the Reds (1956-60).
</P>
<P>
   His best season was his first with Cincinnati, when he won 13
consecutive games and made the National League All-Star team. He
finished the year 19-10 with a 3.99 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring as a player, Lawrence worked 10 years at
International Harvester in Springfield and then spent 10 years
handling scouting, minor league player development, radio and
television work and season-ticket sales for the Reds.
Vicki Sue Robinson:
</P>
<P>
   WILTON, Conn. (AP) -- Vicki Sue Robinson, whose 1976 hit ''Turn
The Beat Around,'' was among the disco anthems of that dancing
decade, died Thursday of cancer. She was 46.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's influences ranged from the blues of Dinah Washington
to the folk stylings of Pete Seeger. She made her singing debut at
age 6 with her mother at the Philadelphia Folk Festival. As a
teen-ager, she appeared on Broadway in ''Hair'' and ''Jesus Christ
Superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   When she hit the recording studio, she struck gold with ''Turn
The Beat Around,'' one of the biggest hits of the disco era. She
was nominated for a Grammy Award for best female vocalist and
earned a Billboard Award for the No. 1 pop album.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson joined in a disco revival in the last few years,
touring with K.C. and the Sunshine Band, The Village People and
Gloria Gaynor.
Jim Rogers:
</P>
<P>
   CLAREMORE, Okla. (AP) -- Jim Rogers, the last surviving son of
cowboy humorist Will Rogers, died Friday of cancer. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rogers served as the family's representative on the official
Will Rogers Memorial Commission of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared in three of Will Rogers' feature films. He was a
cinema cowboy in three Hopalong Cassidy westerns, made Army
training films with Rod Cameron, and co-starred with Noah Beery Jr.
in ''Dudes are Pretty People,'' ''Calaboose,'' and ''Prairie
Chicken,'' all produced by Hal Roach Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
