<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, April 28, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Urges Breakup of Microsoft
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If accepted by a federal judge, a government proposal to
break Microsoft into two companies would bar Microsoft officers and directors,
including billionaire co-founder Bill Gates, from owning stock in more than one
of the new companies. The proposal today to split Microsoft into rival companies
was the largest trust-busting move since AT&AMP;T was carved into seven Baby Bells.
One company would produce its Windows operating software, the source of
Microsoft's monopoly power, according to a court filing. The other company would
handle other software applications, such as word processing, spreadsheet and
database programs
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Five Dead in Suburban Pa. Shootings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   McKEES ROCKS, Pa. (AP) -- In what police called a racially motivated shooting
spree, a white man opened fire in several Pittsburgh communities today, killing
five people and critically wounding a sixth. The shootings took place within a
20-mile range through suburbs surrounding Pittsburgh during about an hour span
this afternoon. The gunman fatally shot a person of Indian descent at an Indian
grocery store, two employees at a Chinese restaurant and a black man at a
martial arts school. A Jewish woman who lived next door to the suspect's
relatives was found dead in her home. The suspect, Richard Baumhammers, 34, a
lawyer, was charged with criminal homicide and reckless endangerment. He was
being held without bail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
INS Agent Defends Tactics of Elian Raid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Immigration and Naturalization Service agent who led the
raid to remove Elian Gonzalez defended the tactics today, saying force was
necessary given the presence of people who had ''vowed to prevent Elian's
recovery.'' ''This was the most challenging execution of a federal search
warrant,'' Agent James Goldman told The Associated Press. The agents worried
they'd be met by armed supporters of the Miami branch of the Gonzalez family.
Crowds had kept vigil outside the home, often swelling into the hundreds.
Federal investigators identified more than 20 people around the home as being
members of paramilitary groups, security companies, or ''individuals that had
vowed to prevent Elian's recovery by the federal government,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Wants Missile Treaty Changes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration has outlined to Russian
negotiators a two-phase program to defend the United States against missile
attack from Asia and later from the Middle East, a senior U.S. official said
today. Deployment of a limited defense, involving 100 launchers and improved
radar, is envisaged for 2005. North Korea, at this point, is considered the
mostly likely Asian country to attack U.S. targets. The second phase, involving
additional interceptors and radar and a second deployment site, would rely on an
orbiting satellite system that is not due to be completed before 2010, the
senior U.S. official told The Associated Press.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Execs Convicted in Bank Failure Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BLUEFIELD, W.Va. (AP) -- Two executives in one of the nation's biggest bank
failures were convicted today of obstructing a federal investigation into how
$515 million in assets vanished from the only bank in a West Virginia coal town.
Terry L. Church, former senior vice president of now-defunct First National Bank
of Keystone, and Michael H. Graham, a bank vice president and director, were
found guilty in a case that could cost the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. as
much as $750 million. Church was convicted of one count of conspiracy and two
counts of obstruction. Graham was convicted of one count of obstruction.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Journalist Detained in Vietnam
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tucker Carlson, a reporter for the conservative magazine
The Weekly Standard and a CNN political commentator, was detained briefly by
Vietnamese authorities in Ho Chi Minh City, who questioned his travel documents,
a spokeswoman for the magazine said today. Carlson, 30, was part of a group of
reporters covering the Vietnam visit of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who was a
prisoner of war for over five years. A State Department spokesman said tonight
that Vietnamese authorities had told them Carlson was free to leave the country
as soon as he arranged transportation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 154; Nasdaq Up 86
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell for a third straight session today,
but technology shares continued their recovery and drove the Nasdaq composite
index higher. At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 154.19
points to 10,733.91. The Nasdaq composite rose 86.63 to close at 3,860.66.
Advancers led decliners 1,731-1,221 on the NYSE.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Astros Defeat Brewers 7-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Chris Holt pitched a one-hitter, allowing only a
second-inning single to Ron Belliard, for his first career complete game as the
Houston Astros beat the Milwaukee Brewers 7-0 tonight. Holt did not allow a
runner to reach second base in his first shutout. Belliard's hit was clean to
center field.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
