<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Reached in Janitors Strike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Striking suburban janitors unanimously approved a
contract agreement with building contractors Friday night that
ended a ten-day walkout, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give janitors a $1.35 per hour raise over three
years and family health insurance in the third year.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you compare that to what we had before we struck, we see
it as a great victory,'' said Ken Munz, a spokesman for Local 1 of
the Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials planned to hold the ratification vote Monday but
later decided to press ahead. The janitors will head back to work
Monday. ''The place was packed and they didn't want to wait,'' Munz
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Suburban Contractors Association originally offered a
95-cent raise over four years and only single-person insurance,
Munz said.
</P>
<P>
   Barry White, a spokesman and negotiator for the Suburban
Contractors Association, declined comment Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The old contract, which expired April 9, set wages at $6.65 an
hour and offered insurance coverage for the worker only.
</P>
<P>
   The strike included 4,500 janitors who work at suburban office
buildings. It began April 18 with 500 workers leaving their
cleaning crew jobs. The so-called rolling strike added a few
hundred workers at a time over the last several days.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of no new negotiations, the union had threatened to
set up picket lines at downtown buildings, with city janitors
agreeing to honor the lines.
</P>
<P>
   In separate talks, 5,500 downtown janitors ratified a new
contract April 18 after staging a one-night walkout. And in Los
Angeles, thousands of striking janitors approved a new contract
April 24, ending a three-week walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities also face walkouts. A union local in San Diego is
on strike and contracts in Oakland, Calif.; Silicon Valley, Calif.;
Cleveland and Seattle will expire within the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: SEIU: http://www.seiu.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
