<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Anwar Conviction  </HEADLINE>
By ALVIN UNG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- An appeals court on Saturday
refused to overturn Anwar Ibrahim's corruption conviction and
six-year sentence, prompting the ousted deputy prime minister to
accuse judges of cowardice and political persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have reached a unanimous decision,'' announced the
president of the Court of Appeals, Lamin Yunus, who was flanked by
two other appellate court judges.
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprise move, Lamin refused to read aloud excerpts of
the appellate court's 59-page ruling, saying Anwar's attorneys and
journalists to read the ruling for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This prompted Anwar to jump up from his seat and launch a tirade
against the three judges.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disgusted, no bloody guts,'' he shouted before the stunned
courtroom, after the judges refused his request for them to
summarize their verdict and explain how they reached their
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar was fired as deputy prime minister in September 1998 by
his longtime mentor, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamar. He was
arrested three weeks later and put on trial on four counts of abuse
of power.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, the High Court convicted Anwar in a verdict that
sparked violent anti-government protests in the capital, Kuala
Lumpur, and galvanized a fledgling opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, who is currently standing trial for sodomy, insists all
the charges against him were trumped up by political enemies to
quash his bid to become the Southeast Asian nation's next prime
minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
