<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-28 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam War Journalists Embrace  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP)-- Former members of the Saigon
press corps -- now, for a few days, members of the Ho Chi Minh City
press corps -- gathered in a hotel roof garden Friday to mark the
end of the Vietnam war 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of journalists from the United States, Britain, France,
South Korea, Hong Kong, Japan, Thailand, Indonesia, Australia and
Vietnam itself are in town to cover Sunday's official anniversary
parade, and to renew their own ties with the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's rather fun -- very pleasant and enormously
interesting, fascinating,'' said legendary British scribe Clare
Hollingworth, at age 88 the oldest of some 60 reporters and
photographers at the unofficial press reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Hollingworth, who scooped the world on Adolf Hitler's invasion
of Poland in 1939, flew in from Hong Kong, her Asia base for many
years with London's Sunday Telegraph. It was her second return
since the war ended in 1975, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with food and drink, the journalists tried to assess the
reunion's meaning without getting too mired down in curbstone
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It means we're finally getting the ghosts of Vietnam off our
hands,'' said Saul Lockhart, of Hong Kong's South China Morning
Post.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists gravitated toward the Rex Hotel in downtown Ho Chi
Minh City just as NBC's ''Today'' show was staging an elaborate
sidewalk interview with Sen. John McCain, who sparked controversy
earlier in the day with scathing remarks about the Vietnamese who
held him prisoner for five years.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his wife, Cindy, had been invited to the press
reception but declined. McCain said he had to catch a plane to rush
back to Washington, D.C., to attend the White House correspondents'
dinner on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   A few other ex-soldiers also were invited, among them former
Sgt. David Garcia, who led a reconnaissance team into Laos during
the 1969 battle of Hamburger Hill and was captured and held
prisoner for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be in Saigon means nothing to me,'' said Garcia, 50.
''Tomorrow we're taking a bottle of tequila to Hamburger Hill to
have a drink to absent friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest contingent was The Associated Press, whose 15
attendees included three Pulitzer Prize winners, photographers
Horst Faas, Nick Ut and Neal Ulevich.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were no speeches at the low-key affair, and as is their
custom, the correspondents avoided telling war stories to each
other. But Faas injected the requisite dark humor of their
profession: ''Morituri te salutant. We who are about to die salute
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-28-00 2327 </TRAILER>
