<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Friday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
White Sox-Tigers:
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT: RHP Jeff Weaver, who hit two White Sox batters before
the big brawl broke out last week in Chicago, led the AL in batters
hit last season with 17.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The White Sox selected Jeff Weaver in the second round
of the 1997 draft (62nd overall). But they couldn't agree to terms
with him and he was drafted and signed by Detroit the following
year.
Red Sox-Indians:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Boston's pitchers entered the series leading the AL with
a 3.96 ERA and opponents are batting just .244 against them. ...
The three rainouts in Boston last weekend allowed the Indians to
avoid facing Pedro Martinez, who is 4-0 against them in the regular
season with a 1.83 ERA and 2-0 vs. Cleveland in the postseason.
Martinez will face Charles Nagy in the series finale Sunday. ...
Carl Everett is already on the verge of setting a team record in
his first month with Boston. Everett has seven homers in April, one
fewer than the eight hit by Mo Vaughn in April of 1996 and '97 and
Fred Lynn in '79.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: The massive suspensions and fines handed down by
baseball disciplinarian Frank Robinson have gotten everyone's
attention. But while Indians manager Charlie Manuel understands the
message being sent, he said it's tough not to do anything when one
of his players gets beaned with a pitch. ''It's hard to just sit
there and not do anything,'' he said. ''Evidently, they're tying to
cut down on that.'' ... Indians ace Bartolo Colon, on the 15-day
disabled list with a pulled muscle in his rib cage, threw in the
outfield Friday and is progressing nicely, Manuel said. ... Scott
Morgan, the Indians' minor league player of the year in 1999, was
claimed off waivers by the Anaheim Angels on Friday. Morgan was
designated for assignment and dropped from the 40-man roster on
April 20. ''I think Scotty Morgan will play in the major leagues,''
Manuel said. ''It's kind of unfortunate he had to go. He's got
power, and he's at the point in his career when somebody needs to
give him a chance.''
Rangers-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers entered Friday's game 8-13. They haven't been
8-13 after 21 games since 1988. ... The next home run by 1B Rafael
Palmeiro will move him past Ralph Kiner and into sole possession of
47th place all-time. ... Injured LHP Justin Thompson threw on the
side Friday and could be activated to make his first start of the
season Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: RHP Scott Erickson, on the disabled list following
March surgery to remove bone chips from his pitching elbow, is one
of ''The 50 Most Beautiful People in the World'' in next week's
issue of People magazine. Erickson, who makes a rehabilitation
start for Double-A Bowie on Sunday, brushed off questions about the
honor. ''I'd rather think about pitching,'' he said. ... 2B Delino
DeShields is on a tear. In his last four starts, DeShields is
8-for-18 with a home run and nine RBIs.
Blue Jays-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: David Wells, a crowd favorite during his two years with
the Yankees, starts Saturday against his former team. The
left-hander was greeted with a standing ovation when he returned to
Yankee Stadium last year for the first time since he was traded for
Roger Clemens. ''It was pretty unbelievable being a guy on the
opposing team and getting a bigger ovation than the guys there,''
said Wells, who is 14-8 in his career vs. New York. ... Toronto
called up LHP Eric Gunderson from Triple-A Syracuse and optioned
LHP John Bale to Syracuse. ... Since hitting .217 with 12 homers in
the first eight games, the Blue Jays hit .319 with 31 homers in the
next 15 contests.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Manager Joe Torre, who missed the first six weeks of
last season recovering from prostate cancer surgery, called Yankees
fan and New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani to offer support for dealing
with the disease. ''Our jobs are very similar in that they aren't
five days a week. He is the only one who knows himself and his job
and when he can come back. He has to do what is best for his health
and people will understand that whether they are for him or against
him,'' Torre said of Giuliani, who announced he had prostate cancer
Thursday. ... Yankees relievers entered the game with 7-0 record
and league-leading 2.98 ERA on the year. ... 2B Chuck Knoblauch
returned to the lineup after missing three games with a sprained
left wrist. ... OF Paul O'Neill was also back after leaving
Wednesday's game in the third inning with blurred vision.
Mariners-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: The Mariners are guaranteed to finish April above .500
for the seventh time in their history. ... The Mariners are
starting a brief four-game road trip to Kansas City and Minnesota
hoping to get better pitching away from home. In 12 home games,
their pitchers are 8-4 with a 3.30 ERA. In their first eight road
games, they were 4-4, 6.88.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The David Glass era began with the Royals on Friday
with a wire transfer of $96 million to pay for the team. Glass, the
retired CEO of Wal-Mart, Inc., said his son Dan, 41, would be the
team president. While workmen were setting up for the weekly
post-game show Friday afternoon, about $2,000 in fireworks went off
prematurely. Fire engines were called to the scene, but there were
no injuries and no other damage. The show was still to go on.
Athletics-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Oakland started its longest road trip of the season, a
12-game four-city trip to Minnesota, Kansas City, Texas and
Anaheim. The A's were 4-20 against those teams on the road last
season. ... Thirteen years ago Friday, former Oakland pitcher
Dennis Eckersley committed in error in the A's 7-1 win over Boston.
He would not commit another error for eight years, setting an
American League record for pitchers with 470 consecutive errorless
games.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins opened their longest homestand of the
season, 12 games in 13 days. ... Minnesota needs to sweep Oakland
this weekend in order to have its first winning April since 1996.
Before that, the Twins had not posted a winning record in April
since 1987. ... Matt Lawton leads Minnesota in batting (.378),
games (23), at-bats (90), hits (34), doubles (6), walks (13) and
stolen bases (5).
Devil Rays-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Jose Canseco entered Friday night's game needing
three stolen bases to become the eighth player in history with at
least 200 steals and 400 home runs. The first seven are Hank Aaron,
Willie Mays, Reggie Jackson, Frank Robinson, Dave Winfield, Andre
Dawson and Barry Bonds. ... The Devil Rays' home run-hitting
quartet of Canseco, Fred McGriff, Greg Vaughn and Vinny Castilla
did not have a homer among them in 14 of the team's first 21 games.
Prior to Friday night's contest, Tampa Bay was 2-5 when at least
one of them homered, and 6-8 when none of them did. Castilla missed
the first seven games because of a strained muscle near the left
side of his rib cage. ... Canseco hit 22 homers on the road last
season, but has only one in his first 11 road games this year.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The Angels claimed OF Scott Morgan off waivers from the
Cleveland Indians and placed him on the 40-man roster. Outfielder
Jeff DaVanon was transferred from the 15-day disabled list to the
60-day DL to make room for Morgan. ... One of the things manager
Mike Scioscia likes most about catcher Bengie Molina is his
willingness to play at considerably less than 100 percent -- as he
did on Thursday night despite intestinal flu. ''I think Bengie
understands what is expected of a front-line catcher on a
championship-caliber club and what the demands of that position
are,'' said Scioscia, who caught more games for the Dodgers than
anyone else. ''You're not going to feel 100 percent all the time --
in fact, he was feeling about 40 percent -- but he gave it his best
shot, and that's all you can ask.'' ... Major league batting leader
Darin Erstad, who already has broken Hal Morris' AL record for hits
in the month of April, entered Friday night's game with 44 -- and
needed three more to tie the major league mark set by Dante
Bichette in 1998 with Colorado.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Diamondbacks-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: C Damian Miller was still nursing a sore hamstring
Friday. He'd missed the previous series against the Phillies but
could return Sunday because he works well with Randy Johnson. ...
The Diamondbacks have not lost a road series since last July 18-20.
Since then, they have gone 12-0 with one split in a road series.
... 3B Matt Williams, who's on the disabled list with a broken bone
in his right foot, is making good use of his time while hobbled.
Williams sat on a chair and fed his teammates soft tosses so they
work on their hitting strokes before Friday's game. ... After
winning their first five day games this season, the Diamondbacks
have lost four straight. They play the Cubs Saturday and Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Don Baylor, hit by the pitch more than any player in
major league history, said he understands the tough stance major
league baseball took by doling out big suspensions following a
brawl between the Tigers and White Sox. But Baylor said protecting
players ''has been done the entire history of the game.'' Baylor's
not for head hunting, but for respect. ''If you are pitcher you
have to be able to pitch inside, these guys are hitting home runs
at a record pace. I believe there is a time to pitch in. Some guys
do get hit. I think when they lose their minds out there on the
mound or fire at somebody's head, they should be suspended.'' ...
RHP Ismael Valdes will make a rehab start on Saturday for Class A
Daytona and scheduled to then join the Cubs to be re-evaluated
Sunday. Valdes is on the DL with shoulder tendinitis. ... The Cubs
have homered in 12 straight games.
Cardinals-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: RHP David Wainhouse was placed on the 15-day disabled
list Friday with right shoulder discomfort and LHP Justin Brunette
was recalled from Triple-A Memphis. Brunette pitched in one game
with St. Louis earlier this season. ... Friday's game in Veterans
Stadium was the Cardinals' first on artificial turf this season.
... This weekend's series in Philadelphia are the Cardinals' only
games in a 15-game stretch outside of Busch Stadium. They finished
off a 6-3 homestand Thursday and return home for three games
against the Pirates on Tuesday. ... RHP Matt Morris, who missed
last season with Tommy John elbow surgery, is expected to throw
batting practice Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: RHP Curt Schilling will come off the disabled list
and start Sunday against the Cardinals. He is 5-5 with a 3.93 ERA
against St. Louis. ... 3B Scott Rolen is the only Phillies player
to start all 22 games. ... RHP Jason Boyd, recently claimed from
the Brewers off waivers, made his last rehabilitation appearance
for Triple-A Wilkes-Barre-Scranton on Wednesday. He is out of
options and, if the Phillies don't keep him on their 25-man roster,
must clear waivers before he can return to the minors. ... Through
21 games, Desi Relaford was the only NL starting shortstop without
an error. ... The Phillies will honor the 50th anniversary of the
1950 NL champion ''Whiz Kids'' on July 8. ... The Phillies played
last season's four NL playoff teams in their first five series.
Reds-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Reds catcher Eddie Taubensee was a late scratch from
Friday's lineup because of tightness in his back. Benito Santiago
replaced him. ... Ken Griffey Jr. made his second career appearance
at Three Rivers Stadium on Friday. Griffey was on the American
League team in the 1994 All-Star game. At that time, he said he
wouldn't mind playing for the Pirates some day because he has
western Pennsylvania roots -- his grandparents and parents are from
Donora, Pa. However, when the Pirates made an offer to Seattle for
Griffey last winter, Griffey made it known he would exercise his
veto rights on a a trade to Pittsburgh. ... Reliever Norm
Charlton's Reds comeback ended after two games and a 27.00 ERA. He
was released on Friday and the Reds purchased the contract of
infielder Juan Castro from Triple-A Louisville. Castro was hitting
.317 in 19 games in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: In less than one month, the Pirates have dropped two
relief pitchers, called up two others, revamped the batting order
and now sent third base prospect Aramis Ramirez back to the minors.
The upheaval reflects the urgency ownership has created for this
team to be a contender. They don't have a strong alternative to
Ramirez was will use a pair of 34-year-old utility players -- Mike
Benjamin and Luis Sojo -- to cover Ramirez's old spot. ... Jason
Schmidt will have another sideline throwing session today to
determine if he's ready to come off the disabled list. Manager Gene
Lamont said he wants to see Schmidt really cut loose with his
pitches to show that he's over the shoulder inflammation that put
him on the DL. If Schmidt passes this test, he will start Tuesday's
game in St. Louis.
Astros-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Geoff Jenkins entered Friday night's game tied with
five other players for the NL home run lead with eight. ....
Milwaukee hopes to get starting catcher Henry Blanco back from the
injured list (April 8, lacerated right index finger) next Tuesday
after a two-game rehab with Triple-A Indianapolis starting Sunday.
.... Brewers starter Jaime Navarro entered the game with a 0-4
record and an 11.57 ERA, not much of a payback for a player earning
$5 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: The Astros Friday night began their longest road trip
of the season, 10 games against Milwaukee, Chicago and Los Angeles.
They are not back home until May 8. .... The Astros were probably
happy to get out of Houston, anyway, after losing five of six games
on their just completed homestand.
Mets-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The Mets, off to their best start since 1988, when
they won the NL East, embarked on a 13-game, four-city road trip --
their longest since 1995. ... RHP Paul Wilson, the first overall
pick of the 1994 draft, was scheduled to join New York's Triple-A
affiliate Norfolk on Monday as he tries to make a comeback from
elbow and shoulder surgery. He has not pitched in the majors since
1996. He was 2-0 with a 1.40 ERA in five games with Class A St.
Lucie. ... Friday night's starter Mike Hampton entered the game 4-0
at Coors Field, while C Mike Piazza was hitting .408 with 12 homers
and 43 RBIs in 30 games at Coors.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: RHP Jerry Dipoto was placed on the 15-day disabled
list Friday and could miss the rest of the season because of
lingering problems with a bulging disk below his neck. Mike DeJean
was recalled from Triple-A Colorado Springs to replace Dipoto in
the bullpen. ... Pedro Astacio made his first start since April 19.
His scheduled start Monday was rained out, and he did not travel
with the team to Montreal on Tuesday and Wednesday because he did
not want to risk visa problems. ... The Rockies played just their
eighth home game.
Braves-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: The Braves and Padres met for the first time since
their blockbuster trade in December that sent Ryan Klesko and Bret
Boone to San Diego in exchange for Quilvio Veras, Wally Joyner and
Reggie Sanders. ... Sanders is an 0-for-30 slump.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Placed RHP Brian Boehringer on the 15-day disabled
list retroactive to April 21st with a right shoulder strain and
recalled RHP Rodrigo Lopez from Triple-A Las Vegas. Lopez will make
his major league debut on Saturday night against Atlanta's John
Burkett. RHP Woody Williams is being watched day-today after
developing numbness and possible circulation problems in a finger
on his pitching hand after his last start. ... LHP Rodney Myers,
coming off a partially torn rotator cuff is expected to make a
minor league rehab assignment on Sunday. ... RHP Steve Montgomery
experienced soreness in a bullpen workout trying to return from a
right shoulder strain. He was scheduled for an MRI exam on Friday
night.
Marlins-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Florida sent INF Luis Castillo on injury rehab to
Triple-A Calgary. Castillo will join the Cannons for the team's
weekend series in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: LHP Jeff Williams, originally optioned to Triple-A
Albuquerque on April 24, instead has been placed on the disabled
list retroactive to April 20 with a left wrist strain. The Dodgers
requested changing Williams' status and major league baseball
granted it.
Expos-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: LHP Kirk Rueter has been tough on the Expos since
they traded him to San Francisco for Mark Leiter on July 30, 1996.
Rueter (2-1) will start against the Expos on Saturday. So far,
Rueter is unbeaten in seven career starts against Montreal, going
4-0 with a 3.12 ERA. Rueter was 25-12 in 59 games for the Expos
from 1993-96. ... The Giants' defense has been taking a beating.
San Francisco has surrendered an NL-high 19 unearned runs while
committing 17 errors in its first 20 games. ... Giants OF Calvin
Murray, a former first-round pick who spent seven years in the
minors before making the big league club this spring, has had a
considerable impact as one of the team's reserves. He's batting
.407 (11-for-27) and his speed on the bases has ignited some key
rallies for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos became the last team in the majors to play a
game on the grass when they opened a three-game series at San
Francisco's Pacific Bell Park on Friday night. The team's first 20
contests all were played on artificial turf. ... Playing the Expos
is no walk in the park. Heading into Friday night's game at San
Francisco, Montreal pitchers have allowed the fewest walks in the
majors with 47. The Expos ranks ahead of the Atlanta Braves (61)
and Arizona Diamondbacks (68).
</P>
</TEXT>
